 9 /var/log/messages file must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Change the owner of the \"/var/log/messages\" file to \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root /var/log/messages","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"/var/log/messages\" file is owned by root with the following command:\n\t\n$ stat -c \"%U %n\" /var/log/messages\n\t\nroot /var/log/messages\n\t\nIf \"/var/log/messages\" does not have an owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 9 system or platform. Additionally, personally identifiable information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"4731","uuid":"c9319036-860b-4724-b51d-9db9fd528625","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 586930409850D5F7F02C4C800D4D8AA83CD4F78F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 /var/log/messages file must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257917","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257917","title":"SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257917","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","rule_id_src":"SV-257917r1101914_rule","rule_id":"SV-257917","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232185","rule_title":"RHEL 9 /var/log/messages file must be group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Change the group owner of the \"/var/log/messages\" file to \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root /var/log/messages","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"/var/log/messages\" file is group-owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%G %n\" /var/log/messages\n\nroot /var/log/messages\n\nIf \"/var/log/messages\" does not have a group owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 9 system or platform. Additionally, personally identifiable information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"5712","uuid":"3154935a-0358-46b5-9c77-2575b361b953","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DA2317FD7A926BEC0164583BE1AEC39D2BCE9BC5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 /var/log/messages file must be group-owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257918","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257918","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257918","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-257918r1044977_rule","rule_id":"SV-257918","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232190","rule_title":"RHEL 9 system commands must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the system commands to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[FILE]\" with any system command file not owned by \"root\".\n\n$ sudo chown root [FILE]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system commands contained in the following directories are owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/libexec /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -user root -exec stat -L -c \"%U %n\" {} \\;\n\nIf any system commands are found to not be owned by root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If RHEL 9 allowed any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 9 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"6730","uuid":"e8f48427-03d0-4b02-8c3d-30f93b26fdd0","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DE8FF8AB0A113B22614A7A6E3BBAE83C628E746C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 system commands must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257919","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257919","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257919","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-257919r1044979_rule","rule_id":"SV-257919","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232195","rule_title":"RHEL 9 system commands must be group-owned by root or a system account.","fix_text":"Configure the system commands to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[FILE]\" with any system command file not group-owned by \"root\" or a required system account.\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [FILE]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system commands contained in the following directories are group-owned by \"root\", or a required system account, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/libexec /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -group root -exec stat -L -c \"%G %n\" {} \\;\n\nIf any system commands are returned and are not group-owned by a required system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If RHEL 9 allowed any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 9 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"6929","uuid":"faec91dc-2162-442a-bf55-9df003c92dff","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1FAC3A47B779C1E4B31FF73937F64BB11456AD9C\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 system commands must be group-owned by root or a system account.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257920","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257920","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257920","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-257920r1101926_rule","rule_id":"SV-257920","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232200","rule_title":"RHEL 9 library files must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the systemwide shared library files contained in the directories \"/lib\", \"/lib64\", \"/usr/lib\", and \"/usr/lib64\" to be owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 -type f -name '*.so*' ! -user root -exec chown root {} +","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the systemwide shared library files contained in the directories \"/lib\", \"/lib64\", \"/usr/lib\", and \"/usr/lib64\" are owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 -type f -name '*.so*' ! -user root -exec stat -c \"%n %U\" {} +\n\nIf any output is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If RHEL 9 allowed any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 9 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"1601","uuid":"eef62eb2-32e0-44dc-9238-685b0f8e57e4","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 716424E961932863C5EA98618DA489B0241A9C4D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 library files must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257921","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257921","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257921","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-257921r1106308_rule","rule_id":"SV-257921","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232205","rule_title":"RHEL 9 library files must be group-owned by root or a system account.","fix_text":"Configure the systemwide shared library files contained in the directories \"/lib\", \"/lib64\", \"/usr/lib\", and \"/usr/lib64\" to be group owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 -type f -name '*.so*' ! -group root -exec chown :root {} +","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the systemwide shared library files contained in the directories \"/lib\", \"/lib64\", \"/usr/lib\", and \"/usr/lib64\" are group owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 -type f -name '*.so*' ! -group root -exec stat -c \"%n %G\" {} +\n\nIf any output is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If RHEL 9 allowed any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 9 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"4527","uuid":"bb717415-1659-4c37-9a08-cbe1b98150a8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7AE2FB3A6C99B13CD1BCBAA71624D7FE3041B27B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 library files must be group-owned by root or a system account.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257922","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257922","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257922","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-257922r1044988_rule","rule_id":"SV-257922","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232210","rule_title":"RHEL 9 library directories must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the systemwide shared library directories within (/lib, /lib64, /usr/lib and /usr/lib64) to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[DIRECTORY]\" with any library directory not owned by \"root\".\n\n$ sudo chown root [DIRECTORY]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the systemwide shared library directories are owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 ! -user root -type d -exec stat -c \"%U %n\" {} \\;\n\nIf any systemwide shared library directory is not owned by \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If RHEL 9 allowed any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 9 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"3548","uuid":"bc898518-f78d-4fbd-a9e6-6418be33c1a8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 826A8AACF06653054E8A7E45F0E88247ACEE91A8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 library directories must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257923","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257923","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257923","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-257923r1044991_rule","rule_id":"SV-257923","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232215","rule_title":"RHEL 9 library directories must be group-owned by root or a system account.","fix_text":"Configure the systemwide shared library directories (/lib, /lib64, /usr/lib and /usr/lib64) to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[DIRECTORY]\" with any library directory not group-owned by \"root\".\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [DIRECTORY]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the systemwide shared library directories are group-owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 ! -group root -type d -exec stat -c \"%G %n\" {} \\;\n\nIf any systemwide shared library directory is returned and is not group-owned by a required system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If RHEL 9 allowed any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 9 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"5345","uuid":"7a1cc36e-2a6e-47db-80af-5438bab5e050","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 74FFFF37B6503DCEF3B807EFB9278141753E0FF9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 library directories must be group-owned by root or a system account.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257924","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257924","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257924","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-257924r991557_rule","rule_id":"SV-257924","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232220","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit tools must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the audit tools to be owned by \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool not owned by \"root\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit tools are owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%U %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\n\nroot /sbin/auditctl\nroot /sbin/aureport\nroot /sbin/ausearch\nroot /sbin/autrace\nroot /sbin/auditd\nroot /sbin/rsyslogd\nroot /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any audit tools do not have an owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nRHEL 9 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"5234","uuid":"bccf9aed-09d0-4923-8cad-6bdfd2b155ea","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5B09D0E7E2FE0D734B83DCD12508E645CD5A5918\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit tools must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257925","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257925","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257925","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-257925r991557_rule","rule_id":"SV-257925","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232225","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit tools must be group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the audit tools to be group-owned by \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool not group-owned by \"root\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit tools are group owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\n\nroot /sbin/auditctl\nroot /sbin/aureport\nroot /sbin/ausearch\nroot /sbin/autrace\nroot /sbin/auditd\nroot /sbin/rsyslogd\nroot /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any audit tools do not have a group owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data; therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nRHEL 9 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"9253","uuid":"307d0fd9-b653-45ad-aa0d-678f01e57583","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FC979CAC976103EBEF9194E1080F7471038655C2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit tools must be group-owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257926","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257926","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257926","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257926r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257926","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232230","rule_title":"RHEL 9 cron configuration files directory must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure any cron configuration not owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [cron config file]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the ownership of all cron configuration files with the command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%U %n\" /etc/cron*\n\nroot /etc/cron.d\nroot /etc/cron.daily\nroot /etc/cron.deny\nroot /etc/cron.hourly\nroot /etc/cron.monthly\nroot /etc/crontab\nroot /etc/cron.weekly\n\nIf any crontab is not owned by root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services that if configured incorrectly can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations; therefore, service configuration files must be owned by the correct group to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6668","uuid":"e479a804-4b3b-456f-bc57-970938d4863e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 44FE93FB9F9C75F2A2AA182AB0A9EFC24778DD8D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 cron configuration files directory must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257927","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257927","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257927","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257927r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257927","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232235","rule_title":"RHEL 9 cron configuration files directory must be group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure any cron configuration not group-owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [cron config file]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the group ownership of all cron configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%G %n\" /etc/cron*\n\nroot /etc/cron.d\nroot /etc/cron.daily\nroot /etc/cron.deny\nroot /etc/cron.hourly\nroot /etc/cron.monthly\nroot /etc/crontab\nroot /etc/cron.weekly\n\nIf any crontab is not group owned by root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services that if configured incorrectly can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations; therefore, service configuration files should be owned by the correct group to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1079","uuid":"cb872643-8bd2-40e4-9128-40742bc4858c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 010D6435B6FBDAC2BC0F7C3EBECDEA39E2516203\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 cron configuration files directory must be group-owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257928","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257928","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257928","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257928r1155576_rule","rule_id":"SV-257928","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232240","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 world-writable directories must be owned by root, sys, bin, or an application user.","fix_text":"Configure all RHEL 9 public directories to be owned by root or a system account to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.\n\nUse the following command template to set ownership of public directories to root or a system account:\n\n$ sudo chown [root or system account] [Public Directory]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 world writable directories are owned by root, a system account, or an application account with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -xdev -type d -perm -0002 -uid +999 -exec stat -c \"%U, %u, %A, %n\" {} \\; 2>/dev/null\n\nIf there is output that indicates world-writable directories are owned by any account other than root or an approved system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a world-writable directory is not owned by root, sys, bin, or an application user identifier (UID), unauthorized users may be able to modify files created by others.\n\nThe only authorized public directories are those temporary directories supplied with the system or those designed to be temporary file repositories. The setting is normally reserved for directories used by the system and by users for temporary file storage, (e.g., /tmp), and for directories requiring global read/write access.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001090"],"reference_identifier":"3848","uuid":"b4cfc249-5100-4fbf-97e9-2082cd7243b9","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7AD7D30FA4D427A93AC374D5CFB4EA16CA8D2934\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All RHEL 9 world-writable directories must be owned by root, sys, bin, or an application user.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257929","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257929","title":"SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257929","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069","rule_id_src":"SV-257929r1137695_rule","rule_id":"SV-257929","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232245","rule_title":"A sticky bit must be set on all RHEL 9 public directories.","fix_text":"Configure all world-writable directories to have the sticky bit set to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.\n\nSet the sticky bit on all world-writable directories using the command, replace \"[World-Writable Directory]\" with any directory path missing the sticky bit:\n\n$ chmod a+t [World-Writable Directory]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set.\n\nDetermine if all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -type d \\( -perm -0002 -a ! -perm -1000 \\) -print 2>/dev/null\n\ndrwxrwxrwt 7 root root 4096 Jul 26 11:19 /tmp\n\nIf any of the returned directories are world-writable and do not have the sticky bit set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Preventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of particular information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DOD or other government agencies.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001090"],"reference_identifier":"1660","uuid":"b58df159-9849-4dc4-bf96-bfddbe32970c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C8FD389FEA2C69E53967D27A03640D55EC9F8456\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'A sticky bit must be set on all RHEL 9 public directories.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257930","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257930","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257930","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257930r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257930","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232250","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 local files and directories must have a valid group owner.","fix_text":"Either remove all files and directories from RHEL 9 that do not have a valid group, or assign a valid group to all files and directories on the system with the \"chgrp\" command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp <group> <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all local files and directories on RHEL 9 have a valid group with the following command:\n\n$ df --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | sudo xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -nogroup\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned group, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Files without a valid group owner may be unintentionally inherited if a group is assigned the same Group Identifier (GID) as the GID of the files without a valid group owner.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5437","uuid":"5a05bd97-e95a-41a6-ac4c-2c3bedbb7d9e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 240A4EACC99D7D52B632F299D127489B059DC170\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'All RHEL 9 local files and directories must have a valid group owner.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257931","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257931","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257931","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257931r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257931","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232255","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 local files and directories must have a valid owner.","fix_text":"Either remove all files and directories from the system that do not have a valid user, or assign a valid user to all unowned files and directories on RHEL 9 with the \"chown\" command:\n\n$ sudo chown <user> <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all local files and directories on RHEL 9 have a valid owner with the following command:\n\n$ df --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | sudo xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -nouser\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned owner, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unowned files and directories may be unintentionally inherited if a user is assigned the same user identifier \"UID\" as the UID of the unowned files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2647","uuid":"e1c20a5f-cd47-4d59-84f9-3b5391d00f0e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7AA77740942D7BF682853AD51F54FED45751E85C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'All RHEL 9 local files and directories must have a valid owner.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257932","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257932","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257932","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257932r1014838_rule","rule_id":"SV-257932","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232260","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that all system device files are correctly labeled to prevent unauthorized modification.","fix_text":"Restore the SELinux policy for the affected device file from the system policy database using the following command:\n\n$ sudo restorecon -v <device_path>\n\nSubstitute \"<device_path>\" with the path to the affected device file (from the output of the previous commands). An example device file path would be \"/dev/ttyUSB0\". If the output of the above command does not indicate that the device was relabeled to a more specific SELinux type label, then the SELinux policy of the system must be updated with more specific policy for the device class specified. If a package was used to install support for a device class, that package could be reinstalled using the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf reinstall <package_name>\n\nIf a package was not used to install the SELinux policy for a given device class, then it must be generated manually and provide specific type labels.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all system device files are correctly labeled to prevent unauthorized modification.\n\nList all device files on the system that are incorrectly labeled with the following commands:\n\nNote: Device files are normally found under \"/dev\", but applications may place device files in other directories and may necessitate a search of the entire system.\n\n# find /dev -context *:device_t:* \\( -type c -o -type b \\) -printf \"%p %Z\\n\"\n\n# find /dev -context *:unlabeled_t:* \\( -type c -o -type b \\) -printf \"%p %Z\\n\"\n\nNote: There are device files, such as \"/dev/vmci\", that are used when the operating system is a host virtual machine. They will not be owned by a user on the system and require the \"device_t\" label to operate. These device files are not a finding.\n\nIf there is output from either of these commands, other than already noted, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an unauthorized or modified device is allowed to exist on the system, there is the possibility the system may perform unintended or unauthorized operations.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6680","uuid":"f81b473a-072a-4ee3-b1e5-a13f003fa07c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 47D581BDF345F161BD37580E5374A995B1500C84\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that all system device files are correctly labeled to prevent unauthorized modification.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257934","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257934","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257934","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257934r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257934","rule_version":"RHEL-09-232270","rule_title":"RHEL 9 /etc/shadow file must have mode 0000 to prevent unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Change the mode of the file \"/etc/shadow\" to \"0000\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0000 /etc/shadow","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the \"/etc/shadow\" file has mode \"0000\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/shadow\n\n0 /etc/shadow\n\nIf a value of \"0\" is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"/etc/shadow\" file contains the list of local system accounts and stores password hashes. Protection of this file is critical for system security. Failure to give ownership of this file to root provides the designated owner with access to sensitive information, which could weaken the system security posture.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6139","uuid":"1390460f-53cd-49cc-bde0-119f60bf9564","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9B87325063EF50A18D3D0BD0061D94D2A3AA6E31\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 /etc/shadow file must have mode 0000 to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257935","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257935","title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257935","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","rule_id_src":"SV-257935r1044994_rule","rule_id":"SV-257935","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the firewalld package installed.","fix_text":"To install the \"firewalld\" package run the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf install firewalld","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Run the following command to determine if the firewalld package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed firewalld \n\nExample output:\n\nfirewalld.noarch          1.0.0-4.el9\n\nIf the \"firewall\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"\"Firewalld\" provides an easy and effective way to block/limit remote access to the system via ports, services, and protocols.\n\nRemote access services, such as those providing remote access to network devices and information systems, which lack automated control capabilities, increase risk and make remote user access management difficult at best.\n\nRemote access is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nRHEL 9 functionality (e.g., SSH) must be capable of taking enforcement action if the audit reveals unauthorized activity. Automated control of remote access sessions allows organizations to ensure ongoing compliance with remote access policies by enforcing connection rules of remote access applications on a variety of information system components (e.g., servers, workstations, notebook computers, smartphones, and tablets).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050, SRG-OS-000297-GPOS-00115, SRG-OS-000298-GPOS-00116, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00232","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000382","CCI-002314","CCI-002322"],"reference_identifier":"7030","uuid":"739e1bc4-0e68-4767-bda4-7279d164c78f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F289D952A71D4A42C24E26ED6A15205C8AF51D2F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must have the firewalld package installed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257936","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257936","title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257936","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","rule_id_src":"SV-257936r1044995_rule","rule_id":"SV-257936","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251015","rule_title":"The firewalld service on RHEL 9 must be active.","fix_text":"To enable the firewalld service run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now firewalld","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"firewalld\" is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active firewalld \n\nactive\n\nIf the firewalld service is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"\"Firewalld\" provides an easy and effective way to block/limit remote access to the system via ports, services, and protocols.\n\nRemote access services, such as those providing remote access to network devices and information systems, which lack automated control capabilities, increase risk and make remote user access management difficult at best.\n\nRemote access is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, non-organization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nRHEL 9 functionality (e.g., RDP) must be capable of taking enforcement action if the audit reveals unauthorized activity. Automated control of remote access sessions allows organizations to ensure ongoing compliance with remote access policies by enforcing connection rules of remote access applications on a variety of information system components (e.g., servers, workstations, notebook computers, smartphones, and tablets).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050, SRG-OS-000297-GPOS-00115, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00232","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000382","CCI-002314"],"reference_identifier":"3383","uuid":"556dfe8a-a9f3-4c84-8469-074b69f2775e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-257937","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257937","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257937","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257937r1106310_rule","rule_id":"SV-257937","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251020","rule_title":"The RHEL 9 firewall must employ a deny-all, allow-by-exception policy for allowing connections to other systems.","fix_text":"Configure the \"firewalld\" daemon to employ a deny-all, allow-by-exception policy with the following commands:\n\nStart by adding the exceptions that are required for mission functionality to the \"drop\" zone. If SSH access on port 22 is needed, for example, run the following: \"sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=ssh --zone=drop\"\n\nReload the firewall rules to update the runtime configuration from the \"--permanent\" changes made above:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --reload\n\nSet the default zone to the drop zone:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --set-default-zone=drop\nNote: This is a runtime and permanent change.\n\nAdd any interfaces to the newly modified \"drop\" zone:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=drop --change-interface=ens192\n\nReload the firewall rules for changes to take effect:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --reload","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 9 firewalld is configured to employ a deny-all, allow-by-exception policy for allowing connections to other systems with the following commands:\n\nEnsure firewalld is running:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --state\nrunning\n\nIdentify active zones:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones\ndrop\n  interfaces: ens192\n\nCheck what rules are applied in that zone:\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --list-all --zone=$(firewall-cmd --get-default-zone)\ndrop (active)\n  target: DROP\n  icmp-block-inversion: no\n  interfaces: ens192\n  sources:\n  services: ssh\n  ports:\n  protocols:\n  forward: yes\n  masquerade: no\n  forward-ports:\n  source-ports:\n  icmp-blocks:\n  rich rules:\n\nIf no zones are active on the RHEL 9 interfaces or if runtime and permanent targets are set to a different option other than \"DROP\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to restrict network connectivity only to authorized systems permits inbound connections from malicious systems. It also permits outbound connections that may facilitate exfiltration of DOD data.\n\nRHEL 9 incorporates the \"firewalld\" daemon, which allows for many different configurations. One of these configurations is zones. Zones can be utilized to a deny-all, allow-by-exception approach. The default \"drop\" zone will drop all incoming network packets unless it is explicitly allowed by the configuration file or is related to an outgoing network connection.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3287","uuid":"d6fae86a-cc04-4902-86ca-7fe4cb0a6623","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-257939","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257939","title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257939","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","rule_id_src":"SV-257939r1044997_rule","rule_id":"SV-257939","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must protect against or limit the effects of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by ensuring rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces are implemented.","fix_text":"Configure \"nftables\" to be the default \"firewallbackend\" for \"firewalld\" by adding or editing the following line in \"/etc/firewalld/firewalld.conf\":\n\nFirewallBackend=nftables\n\nEstablish rate-limiting rules based on organization-defined types of DoS attacks on impacted network interfaces.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify \"nftables\" is configured to allow rate limits on any connection to the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i firewallbackend /etc/firewalld/firewalld.conf\n\n# FirewallBackend\nFirewallBackend=nftables\n\nIf the \"nftables\" is not set as the \"FirewallBackend\" default, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"DoS is a condition when a resource is not available for legitimate users. When this occurs, the organization either cannot accomplish its mission or must operate at degraded capacity.\n\nThis requirement addresses the configuration of RHEL 9 to mitigate the impact of DoS attacks that have occurred or are ongoing on system availability. For each system, known and potential DoS attacks must be identified and solutions for each type implemented. A variety of technologies exists to limit or, in some cases, eliminate the effects of DoS attacks (e.g., limiting processes or establishing memory partitions). Employing increased capacity and bandwidth, combined with service redundancy, may reduce the susceptibility to some DoS attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"2275","uuid":"c3328275-e831-495c-9e7e-8548ed5d5eed","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 99425C092C6D9848313396DFCB606E4C224DB1B4\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must protect against or limit the effects of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by ensuring rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces are implemented.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257940","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257940","title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257940","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","rule_id_src":"SV-257940r1106312_rule","rule_id":"SV-257940","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured to prohibit or restrict the use of functions, ports, protocols, and/or services, as defined in the Ports, Protocols, and Services Management (PPSM) Category Assignments List (CAL) and vulnerability assessments.","fix_text":"Update the host's firewall settings and/or running services to comply with the PPSM CLSA for the site or program and the PPSM CAL.\n\nThen run the following command to load the newly created rule(s):\n\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --reload","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Inspect the firewall configuration and running services to verify it is configured to prohibit or restrict the use of functions, ports, protocols, and/or services that are unnecessary or prohibited.\n\nCheck which services are currently active with the following command:\n\n$ sudo firewall-cmd --list-all-zones | grep -e \"active\" -e \"services\"\n\nAsk the system administrator for the site or program Ports, Protocols, and Services Management Component Local Service Assessment (PPSM CLSA). Verify the services allowed by the firewall match the PPSM CLSA. \n\nIf there are additional ports, protocols, or services that are not in the PPSM CLSA, or there are ports, protocols, or services that are prohibited by the PPSM CAL, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To prevent unauthorized connection of devices, unauthorized transfer of information, or unauthorized tunneling (i.e., embedding of data types within data types), organizations must disable or restrict unused or unnecessary ports, protocols, and services on information systems.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"6220","uuid":"21ce3d38-ac2d-4b9a-9808-c92f76983a5b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 757BBB6C6316B671D93B6EF9FF55348086C228F5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured to prohibit or restrict the use of functions, ports, protocols, and/or services, as defined in the Ports, Protocols, and Services Management (PPSM) Category Assignments List (CAL) and vulnerability assessments.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257941","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257941","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257941","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257941r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257941","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 network interfaces must not be in promiscuous mode.","fix_text":"Configure network interfaces to turn off promiscuous mode unless approved by the ISSO and documented.\n\nSet the promiscuous mode of an interface to off with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ip link set dev <devicename> multicast off promisc off","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify network interfaces are not in promiscuous mode with the following command:\n\n$ ip link | grep -i promisc\n\nIf network interfaces are found on the system in promiscuous mode and their use has not been approved by the ISSO and documented, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Network interfaces in promiscuous mode allow for the capture of all network traffic visible to the system. If unauthorized individuals can access these applications, it may allow them to collect information such as logon IDs, passwords, and key exchanges between systems.\n\nIf the system is being used to perform a network troubleshooting function, the use of these tools must be documented with the information systems security officer (ISSO) and restricted to only authorized personnel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9894","uuid":"2b8e23a8-177c-4d44-a8d1-f0cfc35c8a2a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3B5641AE08E697983F5C35A1A736D1E995432AFE\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 network interfaces must not be in promiscuous mode.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257942","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257942","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257942","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257942r1155718_rule","rule_id":"SV-257942","rule_version":"RHEL-09-251045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enable hardening for the Berkeley Packet Filter just-in-time compiler.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enable hardening for the BPF JIT compiler.\n\nCreate the drop-in file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-net_core-bpf_jit_harden.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.core.bpf_jit_harden = 2\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 enables hardening for the BPF JIT compiler.\n\nCheck the status of the \"net.core.bpf_jit_harden\" parameter with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.core.bpf_jit_harden\nnet.core.bpf_jit_harden = 2\n\nIf \"net.core.bpf_jit_harden\" is not equal to \"2\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nEnabling hardening for the Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF) Just-in-time (JIT) compiler aids in mitigating JIT spraying attacks. Setting the value to \"2\" enables JIT hardening for all users.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8890","uuid":"b86364f2-2499-42e2-93ee-d716508b808f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C88C847F1BD22608E75603CD5E53C1E1E6BBCCBB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enable hardening for the Berkeley Packet Filter just-in-time compiler.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257943","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257943","title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257943","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","rule_id_src":"SV-257943r1045001_rule","rule_id":"SV-257943","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the chrony package installed.","fix_text":"The chrony package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install chrony","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has the chrony package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed chrony\n\nExample output:\n\nchrony.x86_64          4.1-3.el9       \n\nIf the \"chrony\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004923","CCI-001891"],"reference_identifier":"9209","uuid":"52812943-ba22-40cd-bf34-5fd4ac4cdfd2","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6EE4F8BD90F054C45B2101583DCC7AB1460EC896\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must have the chrony package installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257944","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257944","title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257944","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","rule_id_src":"SV-257944r1038944_rule","rule_id":"SV-257944","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 chronyd service must be enabled.","fix_text":"To enable the chronyd service run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now chronyd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the chronyd service is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active chronyd\n\nactive \n\nIf the chronyd service is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.\n\nSynchronizing internal information system clocks provides uniformity of time stamps for information systems with multiple system clocks and systems connected over a network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004923","CCI-001891"],"reference_identifier":"5292","uuid":"016e0495-c165-486a-a6be-94600021ccc2","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6DC81883563EE60EE0BDDF859E79E9809F94B614\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 chronyd service must be enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257945","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257945","title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257945","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143","rule_id_src":"SV-257945r1038944_rule","rule_id":"SV-257945","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must securely compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to securely compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an NTP server by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/chrony.conf file.\n\nserver [ntp.server.name] iburst maxpoll 16","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is securely comparing internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an NTP server with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grep maxpoll /etc/chrony.conf\n\nserver 0.us.pool.ntp.mil iburst maxpoll 16\n\nIf the \"maxpoll\" option is set to a number greater than 16 or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the \"chrony.conf\" file is configured to an authoritative DOD time source by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i server /etc/chrony.conf\nserver 0.us.pool.ntp.mil \n\nIf the parameter \"server\" is not set or is not set to an authoritative DOD time source, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.\n\nSynchronizing internal information system clocks provides uniformity of time stamps for information systems with multiple system clocks and systems connected over a network.\n\nDepending on the infrastructure being used the \"pool\" directive may not be supported.\n\nAuthoritative time sources include the United States Naval Observatory (USNO) time servers, a time server designated for the appropriate DOD network (NIPRNet/SIPRNet), and/or the Global Positioning System (GPS).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143, SRG-OS-000356-GPOS-00144, SRG-OS-000359-GPOS-00146","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001890","CCI-004923","CCI-004926","CCI-001891","CCI-002046"],"reference_identifier":"7310","uuid":"ba3b076e-cf04-467d-8711-aa6deeca42f3","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E02A923ADC7E6800C21AEE26500C9FC44A9DB9C5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must securely compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257946","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257946","title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257946","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","rule_id_src":"SV-257946r1184307_rule","rule_id":"SV-257946","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable the chrony daemon from acting as a server.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disable the chrony daemon from acting as a server by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/chrony.conf file:\n\nport 0","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the server is serving as an NTP server, this is not applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 disables the chrony daemon from acting as a server with the following command:\n\n$ grep -w port /etc/chrony.conf\n\nport 0\n\nIf the \"port\" option is not set to \"0\", is commented out, or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Minimizing the exposure of the server functionality of the chrony daemon diminishes the attack surface.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050, SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381","CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"1215","uuid":"c934f5ca-a6e8-44a6-8b24-f84687425565","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D476DCE5B8E25B154C3BE30142F2AACA893624B5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must disable the chrony daemon from acting as a server.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257947","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257947","title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257947","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050","rule_id_src":"SV-257947r958480_rule","rule_id":"SV-257947","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable network management of the chrony daemon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disable network management of the chrony daemon by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/chrony.conf file:\n\ncmdport 0","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 disables network management of the chrony daemon with the following command:\n\n$ grep -w cmdport /etc/chrony.conf\n\ncmdport 0\n\nIf the \"cmdport\" option is not set to \"0\", is commented out, or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Not exposing the management interface of the chrony daemon on the network diminishes the attack space.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000096-GPOS-00050, SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381","CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"1368","uuid":"d964af67-6197-48e6-ab1b-9ed2552fb65b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7469E8F8728795156627337978C3ABF6170EA66C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must disable network management of the chrony daemon.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257948","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257948","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257948","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257948r1045004_rule","rule_id":"SV-257948","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 systems using Domain Name Servers (DNS) resolution must have at least two name servers configured.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to use two or more name servers for DNS resolution based on the DNS mode of the system.\n\t\nIf the NetworkManager DNS mode is set to \"none\", add the following lines to \"/etc/resolv.conf\":\n\t\nnameserver [name server 1]\nnameserver [name server 2]\n\t\nReplace [name server 1] and [name server 2] with the IPs of two different DNS resolvers.\n\t\nIf the NetworkManager DNS mode is set to \"default\", add two DNS servers to a NetworkManager connection using the following command:\n\t\n$ nmcli connection modify [connection name] ipv4.dns [name server 1],[name server 2]\n\t\nReplace [name server 1] and [name server 2] with the IPs of two different DNS resolvers. Replace [connection name] with a valid NetworkManager connection name on the system. Replace ipv4 with ipv6 if IPv6 DNS servers are used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system is running in a cloud platform and the cloud provider gives a single, highly available IP address for DNS configuration, this control is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the name servers used by the system with the following command:\n\n$ grep nameserver /etc/resolv.conf\n\nnameserver 192.168.1.2\nnameserver 192.168.1.3\n\nIf fewer than two lines are returned that are not commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To provide availability for name resolution services, multiple redundant name servers are mandated. A failure in name resolution could lead to the failure of security functions requiring name resolution, which may include time synchronization, centralized authentication, and remote system logging.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9274","uuid":"421b618f-e8d6-4b9a-aac9-81ed22c0279c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-257949","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257949","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257949","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257949r1134947_rule","rule_id":"SV-257949","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must configure a DNS processing mode in Network Manager.","fix_text":"Configure NetworkManager in RHEL 9 to use a DNS mode.\n\nIn \"/etc/NetworkManager/NetworkManager.conf\", add the following line in the \"[main]\" section:\n\ndns = <dns processing mode>\n\nWhere <dns processing mode> is default, none, or systemd-resolved.\n\nNetworkManager must be reloaded for the change to take effect.\n\n$ sudo systemctl reload NetworkManager","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has a DNS mode configured in Network Manager.\n\n$ NetworkManager --print-config\n[main]\ndns=none\n\nIf the dns key under main does not exist or is not set to \"default\", \"none\", or \"systemd-resolved\", this is a finding.\n\nNote: If RHEL 9 is configured to use a DNS resolver other than Network Manager, the configuration must be documented and approved by the information system security officer (ISSO).","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure that DNS resolver settings are respected, a DNS mode in Network Manager must be configured. The following are common DNS values in NetworkManager.conf [main]:\n\n- default: NetworkManager will update /etc/resolv.conf to reflect the nameservers provided by currently active connections.\n- none: NetworkManager will not modify /etc/resolv.conf. Used when DNS is managed manually or by another service.\n- systemd-resolved: Uses systemd-resolved to manage DNS.\n- dnsmasq: Enables the internal dnsmasq plugin.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1490","uuid":"1d76dd71-491b-40f1-bab4-f3ff864db75d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0DD30E79CAD411C5B69584CAD2C30C90AF5FF64F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must configure a DNS processing mode in Network Manager.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257950","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257950","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257950","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257950r1045006_rule","rule_id":"SV-257950","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not have unauthorized IP tunnels configured.","fix_text":"Remove all unapproved tunnels from the system, or document them with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 does not have unauthorized IP tunnels configured.\n\nDetermine if the \"IPsec\" service is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active ipsec\n\nInactive\n\nIf the \"IPsec\" service is active, check for configured IPsec connections (\"conn\"), with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -rni conn /etc/ipsec.conf /etc/ipsec.d/ \n\nVerify any returned results are documented with the ISSO.\n\nIf the IPsec tunnels are active and not approved, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"IP tunneling mechanisms can be used to bypass network filtering. If tunneling is required, it must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9245","uuid":"b76899be-0bf2-49d6-91bf-dd09a2e1e329","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0F672504D2C152E48C927F8086B5A705DF1CE35B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not have unauthorized IP tunnels configured.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257951","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257951","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257951","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257951r1014843_rule","rule_id":"SV-257951","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured to prevent unrestricted mail relaying.","fix_text":"Modify the postfix configuration file to restrict client connections to the local network with the following command:\n\n$ sudo postconf -e 'smtpd_client_restrictions = permit_mynetworks,reject'","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If postfix is not installed, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 is configured to prevent unrestricted mail relaying with the following command:\n\n$ postconf -n smtpd_client_restrictions \n\nsmtpd_client_restrictions = permit_mynetworks,reject \n\nIf the \"smtpd_client_restrictions\" parameter contains any entries other than \"permit_mynetworks\" and \"reject\", and the additional entries have not been documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If unrestricted mail relaying is permitted, unauthorized senders could use this host as a mail relay for the purpose of sending spam or other unauthorized activity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7517","uuid":"af53af3d-066a-4aab-8253-eb5271fa307b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F4F26CD756BE2E20BD8FFDC5D92ED83034C0D7C5\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured to prevent unrestricted mail relaying.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257953","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257953","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257953","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-257953r958424_rule","rule_id":"SV-257953","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must forward mail from postmaster to the root account using a postfix alias.","fix_text":"Configure a valid email address as an alias for the root account.\n\nAppend the following line to \"/etc/aliases\":\n\npostmaster: root\n\nThen, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo newaliases","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the administrators are notified in the event of an audit processing failure.\n\nCheck that the \"/etc/aliases\" file has a defined value for \"root\".\n\n$ sudo grep \"postmaster:\\s*root$\" /etc/aliases\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how they and the information systems security officer (ISSO) are notified of an audit process failure. If there is no evidence of the proper personnel being notified of an audit processing failure, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139"],"reference_identifier":"2531","uuid":"2a91a043-81cb-4edc-9aa4-a1afe5138cbf","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EC45927450B3A3E95358D8DB801D4C0785964712\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must forward mail from postmaster to the root account using a postfix alias.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257954","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257954","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257954","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257954r1106315_rule","rule_id":"SV-257954","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252065","rule_title":"RHEL 9 libreswan package must be installed.","fix_text":"Install the libreswan service (if it is not already installed) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf install libreswan","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If there is no operational need for Libreswan to be installed, this rule is not applicable.\n\nVerify that RHEL 9 libreswan service package is installed.\n\nCheck that the libreswan service package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed libreswan\n\nExample output:\n\nlibreswan.x86_64          4.6-3.el9\n\nIf the \"libreswan\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Providing the ability for remote users or systems to initiate a secure VPN connection protects information when it is transmitted over a wide area network.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000803"],"reference_identifier":"7718","uuid":"354541ac-cd3a-49ed-9444-ca7d131e26f8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 36853E12859CC368C29E473CC37F4F89AB511FE8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 libreswan package must be installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257955","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257955","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257955","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257955r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257955","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252070","rule_title":"There must be no shosts.equiv files on RHEL 9.","fix_text":"Remove any found \"shosts.equiv\" files from the system.\n\n$ sudo rm /[path]/[to]/[file]/shosts.equiv","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify there are no \"shosts.equiv\" files on RHEL 9 with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -name shosts.equiv\n\nIf a \"shosts.equiv\" file is found, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The shosts.equiv files are used to configure host-based authentication for the system via SSH. Host-based authentication is not sufficient for preventing unauthorized access to the system, as it does not require interactive identification and authentication of a connection request, or for the use of two-factor authentication.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9638","uuid":"80264c4b-8162-4e69-bb23-3ebe32571a15","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 162B5DE4109088C001A2284D7CE40338CF7192F7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'There must be no shosts.equiv files on RHEL 9.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257956","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257956","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257956","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257956r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-257956","rule_version":"RHEL-09-252075","rule_title":"There must be no .shosts files on RHEL 9.","fix_text":"Remove any found \".shosts\" files from the system.\n\n$ sudo rm /[path]/[to]/[file]/.shosts","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify there are no \".shosts\" files on RHEL 9 with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -name .shosts\n\nIf a \".shosts\" file is found, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The .shosts files are used to configure host-based authentication for individual users or the system via SSH. Host-based authentication is not sufficient for preventing unauthorized access to the system, as it does not require interactive identification and authentication of a connection request, or for the use of two-factor authentication.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3500","uuid":"15453bbe-0bf3-4806-850a-528f50d49d5e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 84A4448A8B564785DE59AF1D3C7375481C7AF72F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'There must be no .shosts files on RHEL 9.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257957","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257957","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257957","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257957r1155618_rule","rule_id":"SV-257957","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured to use TCP syncookies.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use TCP syncookies.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_tcp_syncookies.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to use IPv4 TCP syncookies.\n\nCheck the value of all \"tcp_syncookies\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies\nnet.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1\n\nIf the network parameter \"ipv4.tcp_syncookies\" is not equal to \"1\" or nothing is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Preventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of particular information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DOD or other government agencies.\n\nThere may be shared resources with configurable protections (e.g., files in storage) that may be assessed on specific information system components.\n\nRestricting access to the kernel message buffer limits access to only root. This prevents attackers from gaining additional system information as a nonprivileged user.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186, SRG-OS-000142-GPOS-00071","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001095","CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"4566","uuid":"00b5a6cc-5d24-473e-93ab-eec1db2aa2e4","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AAD2111E7FB870BBBE4829239F7F36F07AE887A8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured to use TCP syncookies.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257958","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257958","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257958","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257958r1155721_rule","rule_id":"SV-257958","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must ignore Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to ignore IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_accept_redirects.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 will not accept IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of all \"net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5913","uuid":"2bec2f30-2e35-425d-ba60-542c940cbbf6","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-257959","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257959","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257959","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257959r1155724_rule","rule_id":"SV-257959","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not forward Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) source-routed packets.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to ignore IPv4 source-routed packets.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_accept_source.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 will not accept IPv4 source-routed packets.\n\nCheck the value of the \"accept_source_route\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of which of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4253","uuid":"61ab42c0-4f5b-4ef2-8215-5aa8a61a4b64","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3D404A338952D8C69860D91E3036901DA16707DA\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not forward Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) source-routed packets.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257960","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257960","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257960","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257960r1155727_rule","rule_id":"SV-257960","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to log martian packets on IPv4 interfaces.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_log_martians.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians=1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 logs IPv4 martian packets.\n\nCheck the value of the \"log_martians\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians = 1\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The presence of \"martian\" packets (which have impossible addresses) as well as spoofed packets, source-routed packets, and redirects could be a sign of nefarious network activity. Logging these packets enables this activity to be detected.\n\nPreventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of particular information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DOD or other government agencies.\n\nThere may be shared resources with configurable protections (e.g., files in storage) that may be assessed on specific information system components.\n\nRestricting access to the kernel message buffer limits access to only root. This prevents attackers from gaining additional system information as a nonprivileged user.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4014","uuid":"af19f2b0-bf23-436e-977c-1ff8f49c0a3f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0D952A2AC78DA26A9AB01626F230597A4AA80BD2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257961","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257961","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257961","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257961r1155730_rule","rule_id":"SV-257961","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses by default.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to log martian packets on IPv4 interfaces by default.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_log_martians.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians=1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 logs IPv4 martian packets by default.\n\nCheck the value of the \"default.log_martians\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians = 1\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The presence of \"martian\" packets (which have impossible addresses) as well as spoofed packets, source-routed packets, and redirects could be a sign of nefarious network activity. Logging these packets enables this activity to be detected.\n\nPreventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of particular information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DOD or other government agencies.\n\nThere may be shared resources with configurable protections (e.g., files in storage) that may be assessed on specific information system components.\n\nRestricting access to the kernel message buffer limits access to only root. This prevents attackers from gaining additional system information as a nonprivileged user.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4150","uuid":"6e551ab3-1632-4734-a136-b71c557858eb","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2880829DAAEA57606A66C3E07F57C7C688C9FCA1\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses by default.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257962","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257962","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257962","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257962r1155733_rule","rule_id":"SV-257962","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_rp_filter.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter = 1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 uses reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces.\n\nCheck the value of the \"rp_filter\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter = 1\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling reverse path filtering drops packets with source addresses that should not have been able to be received on the interface on which they were received. It must not be used on systems that are routers for complicated networks, but is helpful for end hosts and routers serving small networks.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8908","uuid":"4dd8c18a-abee-4ab0-9bf3-b0c33aad925c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 71A1104616FB708D1C60FB2ACF899D1FF5152308\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must use reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257963","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257963","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257963","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257963r1155736_rule","rule_id":"SV-257963","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent IPv4 ICMP redirect messages from being accepted.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_accept_redirects.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 will not accept IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the default \"accept_redirects\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThis feature of the IPv4 protocol has few legitimate uses. It must be disabled unless absolutely required.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1798","uuid":"a54dfd28-9520-4bbb-89e1-4f4f2721514a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 196B4F980B44EC4EA1F5D251FC904AC3DD189EE9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257964","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257964","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257964","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257964r1155739_rule","rule_id":"SV-257964","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ipv4_accept_source_route.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 does not accept IPv4 source-routed packets by default.\n\nCheck the value of the \"accept source route\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9849","uuid":"a19a0703-9861-4e7f-9bd3-bd0f806ec927","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3B9C11EE394CA608CEF26347AEC653386AF11ABB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257965","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257965","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257965","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257965r1155646_rule","rule_id":"SV-257965","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use a reverse-path filter for IPv4 network traffic when possible by default.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use reverse path filtering on IPv4 interfaces by default.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_rp_filter.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter = 1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 uses reverse path filtering on IPv4 interfaces.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling reverse path filtering drops packets with source addresses that should not have been able to be received on the interface on which they were received. It must not be used on systems that are routers for complicated networks, but is helpful for end hosts and routers serving small networks.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4594","uuid":"fd76929d-ca2e-437e-b22b-e21e83989786","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FDEC931F91C1A54E2BBBC1A50E1E8B56F5410187\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must use a reverse-path filter for IPv4 network traffic when possible by default.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257966","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257966","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257966","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257966r1155742_rule","rule_id":"SV-257966","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253055","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not respond to Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echoes sent to a broadcast address.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to ignore IPv4 ICMP echoes sent to a broadcast address.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 ignores ICMP echoes sent to a broadcast address.\n\nCheck the value of the \"icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts\nnet.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Responding to broadcast (ICMP) echoes facilitates network mapping and provides a vector for amplification attacks.\n\nIgnoring ICMP echo requests (pings) sent to broadcast or multicast addresses makes the system slightly more difficult to enumerate on the network.\n\nThere are notable differences between Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6). IPv6 does not implement the same method of broadcast as IPv4. Instead, IPv6 uses multicast addressing to the all-hosts multicast group. Refer to RFC4294 for an explanation of \"IPv6 Node Requirements\", which resulted in this difference between IPv4 and IPv6.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8951","uuid":"82813f7e-1ad3-45cb-93dd-4b784321c020","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 407A31B23F6E093861070DECA7A914ED1A9780C9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not respond to Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echoes sent to a broadcast address.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257967","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257967","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257967","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257967r1155745_rule","rule_id":"SV-257967","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must limit the number of bogus Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) response errors logs.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not log bogus ICMP errors:\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses = 1\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 limits the number of bogus Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) response errors logs.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_response\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses\nnet.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses = 1\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_response\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Some routers will send responses to broadcast frames that violate RFC-1122, which fills up a log file system with many useless error messages. An attacker may take advantage of this and attempt to flood the logs with bogus error logs. Ignoring bogus ICMP error responses reduces log size, although some activity would not be logged.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2127","uuid":"126ef0ac-8925-4bf2-9a50-5acb1897d909","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BA11598E47D37E24D6D3CD103D10B2A346560472\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must limit the number of bogus Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) response errors logs.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257968","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257968","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257968","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257968r1155748_rule","rule_id":"SV-257968","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253065","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not send Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not allow interfaces to perform IPv4 ICMP redirects.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_send_redirects.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 does not IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the \"all send_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages contain information from the system's route table possibly revealing portions of the network topology.\n\nThe ability to send ICMP redirects is only appropriate for systems acting as routers.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3380","uuid":"d65d8c1a-8d1c-45b2-b1ac-c5a38bd6e667","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FAECE641F22F557677D7907F1B5A615287934B6A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not send Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257969","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257969","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257969","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257969r1155623_rule","rule_id":"SV-257969","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253070","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not allow interfaces to perform Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects by default.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not allow interfaces to perform Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) ICMP redirects by default.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_send_redirect.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check the value of the \"default send_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects=0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages contain information from the system's route table possibly revealing portions of the network topology. The ability to send ICMP redirects is only appropriate for systems acting as routers.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3940","uuid":"a068725e-3313-4124-8aee-aa09ef6d41c9","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 33BD79187C2C1AACA6BF7BB3378E4B325F10C44B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not allow interfaces to perform Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects by default.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257970","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257970","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257970","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257970r1155751_rule","rule_id":"SV-257970","rule_version":"RHEL-09-253075","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not enable IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not allow IPv4 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_forwarding.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is not performing IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.\n\nCheck that \"net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding\" is disabled using the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding\" is not set to \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this capability is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6980","uuid":"8564714c-a142-44e3-8225-e77a2788250e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9BF5F33F13D005B4DD8013B24F211454AA204959\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must not enable IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257971","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257971","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257971","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257971r1155754_rule","rule_id":"SV-257971","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces unless the system is a router.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv4_accept_ra.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 does not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces, unless the system is a router.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck that \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\" is set to not accept router advertisements by using the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this software is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.\n\nAn illicit router advertisement message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3086","uuid":"2bda0a46-ba27-4b06-94fc-48cd2e0902fb","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 377E984314D28BFFA638DA9E4945A6A0C53C535A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257972","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257972","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257972","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257972r1155757_rule","rule_id":"SV-257972","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must ignore IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to ignore IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv6_accept_redirects.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 ignores IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"accept_redirects\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8000","uuid":"e19fb57e-f99c-4a38-8b6d-d8aa3af00b60","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7BB3FFAB11FD2398CBE82D1D77475AFCF11E5519\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must ignore IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257973","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257973","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257973","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257973r1155760_rule","rule_id":"SV-257973","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not accept IPv6 source-routed packets.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv6_accept_source_route.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 does not accept IPv6 source-routed packets.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3209","uuid":"de3ed4bd-77c5-401d-99f9-404c76f3bfbc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E92BCED89DCDA045BC61492AB516C611BC0E8211\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257974","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257974","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257974","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257974r1155763_rule","rule_id":"SV-257974","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not enable IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not allow IPv6 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv6_forwarding.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is not performing IPv6 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this software is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3170","uuid":"758ce708-f006-4a4d-923b-240110f78a11","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5C793709261DB8D0043AD01AEBE8648AF218E824\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must not enable IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257975","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257975","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257975","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257975r1155766_rule","rule_id":"SV-257975","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default unless the system is a router.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv6_accept_ra.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 does not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default, unless the system is a router.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this software is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network. An illicit router advertisement message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5434","uuid":"8a6cc7d4-de53-46ee-9f45-3e9b95e2254c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 530CC4D7050ADB62F7B6AC5D7639F276AEC267FF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257976","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257976","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257976","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257976r1155769_rule","rule_id":"SV-257976","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent IPv6 ICMP redirect messages from being accepted.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv6_accept_redirects.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 to prevent IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4830","uuid":"33d20c16-dce3-4639-a3a7-a5ab522277b3","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 267763FEE8DED8347735A1064FB7312ED28DE40C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257977","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257977","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257977","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257977r1155772_rule","rule_id":"SV-257977","rule_version":"RHEL-09-254040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets by default.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not accept IPv6 source-routed packets by default.\n\nCreate a configuration file if it does not already exist:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/ipv6_accept_source_route.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nReload settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 does not accept IPv6 source-routed packets by default.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nAccepting source-routed packets in the IPv6 protocol has few legitimate uses. It must be disabled unless it is absolutely required.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of the directories in which they reside. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6940","uuid":"1f220583-21b5-41c7-960e-2a9258afd52a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CB62E416F905B654F198F287D9094D1223E18204\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets by default.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257978","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257978","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257978","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-257978r1045013_rule","rule_id":"SV-257978","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255010","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 networked systems must have SSH installed.","fix_text":"The openssh-server package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install openssh-server","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has the openssh-server package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed openssh-server\n\nExample output:\n\nopenssh-server.x86_64          8.7p1-8.el9\n\nIf the \"openssh-server\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered. \n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of information system components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification. \n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188, SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189, SRG-OS-000426-GPOS-00190","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002418","CCI-002420","CCI-002421","CCI-002422"],"reference_identifier":"7908","uuid":"a08ad9c5-dd16-4f1d-b684-77d8bf1cb492","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 396FF73ED29435B765586B54D2D2AA11D628E236\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All RHEL 9 networked systems must have SSH installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257979","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257979","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257979","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-257979r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-257979","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255015","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 networked systems must have and implement SSH to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted and received information, as well as information during preparation for transmission.","fix_text":"To enable the sshd service run the following command:\n\n$ systemctl enable --now sshd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"sshd\" is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active sshd\n\nactive\n\nIf the \"sshd\" service is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered. \n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of information system components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification. \n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188, SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189, SRG-OS-000426-GPOS-00190","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002418","CCI-002420","CCI-002421","CCI-002422"],"reference_identifier":"9755","uuid":"1765af48-6d2e-4b92-8a0c-2d688c72be54","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9F34FA7C47ED22D44292029C711E12765C9D4977\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'All RHEL 9 networked systems must have and implement SSH to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted and received information, as well as information during preparation for transmission.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257980","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257980","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257980","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257980r1045016_rule","rule_id":"SV-257980","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the openssh-clients package installed.","fix_text":"The openssh-clients package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install openssh-clients","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has the openssh-clients package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed openssh-clients\n\nExample output:\n\nopenssh-clients.x86_64          8.7p1-8.el9\n\nIf the \"openssh-clients\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This package includes utilities to make encrypted connections and transfer files securely to SSH servers.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4993","uuid":"94fd068c-cb1c-442b-9e35-c2369a6becc1","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9285828598CF4832626BF210C4F35563955E0021\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must have the openssh-clients package installed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257981","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257981","title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257981","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","rule_id_src":"SV-257981r1101970_rule","rule_id":"SV-257981","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a SSH logon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system via ssh.\n\nEdit the \"etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file or a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" to uncomment the banner keyword and configure it to point to a file that will contain the logon banner (this file may be named differently or be in a different location if using a version of SSH that is provided by a third-party vendor).\n\nAn example configuration line is:\n\nBanner /etc/issue","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify any SSH connection to RHEL 9 displays the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system.\n\nCheck for the location of the banner file being used with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*banner'\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/80-bannerPointer.conf:Banner /etc/issue\n\nThis command will return the banner keyword and the name of the file that contains the SSH banner (in this case \"/etc/issue\").\n\nIf the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The warning message reinforces policy awareness during the logon process and facilitates possible legal action against attackers. Alternatively, systems whose ownership should not be obvious should ensure usage of a banner that does not provide easy attribution.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000048","CCI-001384","CCI-001385","CCI-001386","CCI-001387","CCI-001388"],"reference_identifier":"4044","uuid":"197d616c-a81f-4104-87a8-49959b271895","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 01BBDFF36DB348C5F92E2C4865B6CECFF4275373\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a SSH logon.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257982","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257982","title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257982","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","rule_id_src":"SV-257982r1045021_rule","rule_id":"SV-257982","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must log SSH connection attempts and failures to the server.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to log connection attempts add or modify the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\".\n\nLogLevel VERBOSE\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 logs SSH connection attempts and failures to the server.\n\nCheck what the SSH daemon's \"LogLevel\" option is set to with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*loglevel'\n\nLogLevel VERBOSE\n\nIf a value of \"VERBOSE\" is not returned or the line is commented out or missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"SSH provides several logging levels with varying amounts of verbosity. \"DEBUG\" is specifically not recommended other than strictly for debugging SSH communications since it provides so much data that it is difficult to identify important security information. \"INFO\" or \"VERBOSE\" level is the basic level that only records login activity of SSH users. In many situations, such as Incident Response, it is important to determine when a particular user was active on a system. The logout record can eliminate those users who disconnected, which helps narrow the field.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000067"],"reference_identifier":"9556","uuid":"2d2ac12a-f7eb-4bb8-a1dd-3974951bfc39","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7A3F442F3936B67E04409D2C8539F5F6A2AD864D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must log SSH connection attempts and failures to the server.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257983","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257983","title":"SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257983","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052","rule_id_src":"SV-257983r1045024_rule","rule_id":"SV-257983","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSHD must accept public key authentication.","fix_text":"To configure the system, add or modify the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\".\n\nPubkeyAuthentication yes\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that RHEL 9 SSH daemon accepts public key encryption with the following command:\n \n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*pubkeyauthentication'\n\nPubkeyAuthentication yes\n \nIf \"PubkeyAuthentication\" is set to no, the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the use of multifactor authentication, the ease of access to privileged functions is greatly increased. Multifactor authentication requires using two or more factors to achieve authentication. A privileged account is defined as an information system account with authorizations of a privileged user. A DOD common access card (CAC) with DOD-approved PKI is an example of multifactor authentication.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052, SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053, SRG-OS-000107-GPOS-00054, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00055","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000765","CCI-000766","CCI-000767","CCI-000768"],"reference_identifier":"1332","uuid":"f3dbd0b5-c0cc-41f4-b778-be97347ab225","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 29C6A9F4E3197AEC53A55D6FC102C4FB9EA018DA\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSHD must accept public key authentication.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257984","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257984","title":"SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257984","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053","rule_id_src":"SV-257984r1045026_rule","rule_id":"SV-257984","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSHD must not allow blank passwords.","fix_text":"To configure the system to prevent SSH users from logging on with blank passwords edit the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\":\n\nPermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 remote access using SSH prevents logging on with a blank password with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*permitemptypasswords'\n\nPermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nIf the \"PermitEmptyPasswords\" keyword is set to \"yes\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account has an empty password, anyone could log on and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000766"],"reference_identifier":"1187","uuid":"e354d4c0-fc28-4e97-a3d4-e9e5d59c1272","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BCB37A1105B3C93A04F605F93273B77FDF005379\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSHD must not allow blank passwords.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257985","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257985","title":"SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257985","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056","rule_id_src":"SV-257985r1069364_rule","rule_id":"SV-257985","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not permit direct logons to the root account using remote access via SSH.","fix_text":"To configure the system to prevent SSH users from logging on directly as root add or modify the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\".\n\nPermitRootLogin no\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 remote access using SSH prevents users from logging on directly as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*permitrootlogin'\n\nPermitRootLogin no\n\nIf the \"PermitRootLogin\" keyword is set to any value other than \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Even though the communications channel may be encrypted, an additional layer of security is gained by extending the policy of not logging directly on as root. In addition, logging in with a user-specific account provides individual accountability of actions performed on the system and also helps to minimize direct attack attempts on root's password.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004045","CCI-000770"],"reference_identifier":"1948","uuid":"4eabacc9-b213-4dd3-9522-a666db82e0ed","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 048D6386CC56F8DF4995BFF2BDE8E9197EF64554\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must not permit direct logons to the root account using remote access via SSH.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257986","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257986","title":"SRG-OS-000125-GPOS-00065","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257986","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000125-GPOS-00065","rule_id_src":"SV-257986r1045030_rule","rule_id":"SV-257986","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enable the Pluggable Authentication Module (PAM) interface for SSHD.","fix_text":"Configure the RHEL 9 SSHD to use the UsePAM interface by adding or modifying the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\".\n\nUsePAM yes\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 9 SSHD is configured to allow for the UsePAM interface with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*usepam'\n\nUsePAM yes\n\nIf the \"UsePAM\" keyword is set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When UsePAM is set to \"yes\", PAM runs through account and session types properly. This is important when restricted access to services based off of IP, time, or other factors of the account is needed. Additionally, this ensures users can inherit certain environment variables on login or disallow access to the server.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000877"],"reference_identifier":"8047","uuid":"2967f5b5-2d0a-413a-b144-7a3bc66a3064","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 568F985D919B3239182E0FF1C94FAEBE8D72B4FF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enable the Pluggable Authentication Module (PAM) interface for SSHD.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257989","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257989","title":"SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257989","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093","rule_id_src":"SV-257989r1184309_rule","rule_id":"SV-257989","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255065","rule_title":"The RHEL 9 SSH server must be configured to use only DOD-approved encryption ciphers employing FIPS 140-3 validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.","fix_text":"Configure the RHEL 9 SSH server to use only ciphers employing FIPS 140-3 approved algorithms.\n\nReinstall crypto-policies with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf -y reinstall crypto-policies\n\nSet the crypto-policy to FIPS with the following command:\n\n$ sudo update-crypto-policies --set FIPS\n\nSetting system policy to FIPS\n\nNote: Systemwide crypto policies are applied on application startup. It is recommended to restart the system for the change of policies to fully take place.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH server is configured to use only ciphers employing FIPS 140-3 approved algorithms.\n\nTo verify the ciphers in the systemwide SSH configuration file, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i Ciphers /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config \nCiphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr\n\nIf the cipher entries in the \"opensshserver.config\" file have any ciphers other than \"aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr\", or they are missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without cryptographic integrity protections, information can be altered by unauthorized users without detection.\n\nRemote access (e.g., RDP) is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nCryptographic mechanisms used for protecting the integrity of information include, for example, signed hash functions using asymmetric cryptography enabling distribution of the public key to verify the hash information while maintaining the confidentiality of the secret key used to generate the hash.\n\nRHEL 9 incorporates systemwide crypto policies by default. The SSH configuration file has no effect on the ciphers, MACs, or algorithms unless specifically defined in the /etc/sysconfig/sshd file. The employed algorithms can be viewed in the /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config file.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001453"],"reference_identifier":"9275","uuid":"4aec74b8-e133-4155-aaf3-0aed8b623f68","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C8870404A27520CFE77DBC986DFC710D66F70796\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The RHEL 9 SSH server must be configured to use only DOD-approved encryption ciphers employing FIPS 140-3 validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257991","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257991","title":"SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257991","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093","rule_id_src":"SV-257991r1184311_rule","rule_id":"SV-257991","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255075","rule_title":"The RHEL 9 SSH server must be configured to use only Message Authentication Codes (MACs) employing FIPS 140-3 validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.","fix_text":"Configure the RHEL 9 SSH server to use only MACs employing FIPS 140-3 approved algorithms.\n\nReinstall crypto-policies with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf -y reinstall crypto-policies\n\nSet the crypto-policy to FIPS with the following command:\n\n$ sudo update-crypto-policies --set FIPS\n\nSetting system policy to FIPS\n\nNote: Systemwide crypto policies are applied on application startup. It is recommended to restart the system for the change of policies to fully take place.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH server is configured to use only MACs employing FIPS 140-3 approved algorithms.\n\nTo verify the MACs in the systemwide SSH configuration file, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i MACs /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config\n\nMACs hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256,hmac-sha2-512\n\nIf the MACs entries in the \"opensshserver.config\" file have any hashes other than \"hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256,hmac-sha2-512\", or they are missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without cryptographic integrity protections, information can be altered by unauthorized users without detection.\n\nRemote access (e.g., RDP) is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nCryptographic mechanisms used for protecting the integrity of information include, for example, signed hash functions using asymmetric cryptography enabling distribution of the public key to verify the hash information while maintaining the confidentiality of the secret key used to generate the hash.\n\nRHEL 9 incorporates systemwide crypto policies by default. The SSH configuration file has no effect on the ciphers, MACs, or algorithms unless specifically defined in the /etc/sysconfig/sshd file. The employed algorithms can be viewed in the /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config file.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001453"],"reference_identifier":"6997","uuid":"7a6baa7b-279f-4cc7-a918-b8f783324367","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C28BCDE657953C5F373A1F1743CB5A2461785D55\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The RHEL 9 SSH server must be configured to use only Message Authentication Codes (MACs) employing FIPS 140-3 validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257992","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257992","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257992","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","rule_id_src":"SV-257992r1045047_rule","rule_id":"SV-257992","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255080","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not allow a noncertificate trusted host SSH logon to the system.","fix_text":"To configure RHEL 9 to not allow a noncertificate trusted host SSH logon to the system, add or modify the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\".\n\nHostbasedAuthentication no\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system does not allow a noncertificate trusted host SSH logon to the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*hostbasedauthentication'\n\nHostbasedAuthentication no\n\nIf the \"HostbasedAuthentication\" keyword is not set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the required value is not set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"SSH trust relationships mean a compromise on one host can allow an attacker to move trivially to other hosts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8550","uuid":"72dd573e-e6d7-4a36-b4ee-97737f9c4a67","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 191D3B7C35E84805E626227E3D6E50D90AE73F9D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not allow a noncertificate trusted host SSH logon to the system.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257993","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257993","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257993","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","rule_id_src":"SV-257993r1045049_rule","rule_id":"SV-257993","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255085","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not allow users to override SSH environment variables.","fix_text":"Configure the RHEL 9 SSH daemon to not allow unattended or automatic logon to the system by editing the following line in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\":\n\nPermitUserEnvironment no\n\nRestart the SSH daemon  for the setting to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that unattended or automatic logon via SSH is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*permituserenvironment'\n\nPermitUserEnvironment no\n\nIf \"PermitUserEnvironment\" is set to \"yes\", is missing completely, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the required value is not set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"SSH environment options potentially allow users to bypass access restriction in some configurations.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9985","uuid":"df6380cd-5010-4a61-ae61-6f14de4a7e03","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 19F7A44160D79BD77A77F861712D206913D63F44\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not allow users to override SSH environment variables.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257994","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257994","title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257994","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187","rule_id_src":"SV-257994r1045051_rule","rule_id":"SV-257994","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255090","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must force a frequent session key renegotiation for SSH connections to the server.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to force a frequent session key renegotiation for SSH connections to the server by adding or modifying the following line in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\":\n\nRekeyLimit 1G 1h\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect.\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH server is configured to force frequent session key renegotiation with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*rekeylimit'\n\nRekeyLimit 1G 1h\n\nIf \"RekeyLimit\" does not have a maximum data amount and maximum time defined, is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered. \n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of information system components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification. \n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.\n\nSession key regeneration limits the chances of a session key becoming compromised.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000033-GPOS-00014, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000068","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"2442","uuid":"03152f4e-476c-4757-8378-6f0c21c0cf98","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 38B7C81CC6567649B59A14D2BE70EAA230ABA48C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must force a frequent session key renegotiation for SSH connections to the server.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257995","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257995","title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257995","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","rule_id_src":"SV-257995r1045053_rule","rule_id":"SV-257995","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255095","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic terminate after becoming unresponsive.","fix_text":"Note: This setting must be applied in conjunction with RHEL-09-255100 to function correctly.\n\nConfigure the SSH server to terminate a user session automatically after the SSH client has become unresponsive.\n\nModify or append the following lines in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\":\n\nClientAliveCountMax 1\n\nFor the changes to take effect, the SSH daemon must be restarted.\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is set to \"1\" by performing the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*clientalivecountmax'\n\nClientAliveCountMax 1\n\nIf \"ClientAliveCountMax\" does not exist, is not set to a value of \"1\" in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Terminating an unresponsive SSH session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended. In addition, quickly terminating an idle SSH session will also free up resources committed by the managed network element.\n\nTerminating network connections associated with communications sessions includes, for example, deallocating associated TCP/IP address/port pairs at the operating system level and deallocating networking assignments at the application level if multiple application sessions are using a single operating system-level network connection. This does not mean the operating system terminates all sessions or network access; it only ends the unresponsive session and releases the resources associated with that session.\n\nRHEL 9 utilizes /etc/ssh/sshd_config for configurations of OpenSSH. Within the sshd_config, the product of the values of \"ClientAliveInterval\" and \"ClientAliveCountMax\" are used to establish the inactivity threshold. The \"ClientAliveInterval\" is a timeout interval in seconds, after which if no data has been received from the client, sshd will send a message through the encrypted channel to request a response from the client. The \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is the number of client alive messages that may be sent without sshd receiving any messages back from the client. If this threshold is met, sshd will disconnect the client. For more information on these settings and others, refer to the sshd_config man pages.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072, SRG-OS-000279-GPOS-00109","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001133","CCI-002361"],"reference_identifier":"6562","uuid":"24a7cab6-09e6-4866-95a2-4df5a1800371","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 92C6DFA6FA6978A109A87F0E1A017B576F3DCEE7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic terminate after becoming unresponsive.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257996","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257996","title":"SRG-OS-000126-GPOS-00066","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257996","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000126-GPOS-00066","rule_id_src":"SV-257996r1134915_rule","rule_id":"SV-257996","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255100","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic are terminated after 10 minutes of becoming unresponsive.","fix_text":"Note: This setting must be applied in conjunction with RHEL-09-255095 to function correctly.\n\nConfigure the SSH server to terminate a user session automatically after the SSH client has been unresponsive for 10 minutes.\n\nModify or append the following lines in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\":\n\nClientAliveInterval 600\n\nFor the changes to take effect, the SSH daemon must be restarted.\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"ClientAliveInterval\" variable is set to a value of \"600\" or less by performing the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*clientaliveinterval'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/ClientAliveInterval.conf:ClientAliveInterval 600\n\nVerify the runtime value of \"ClientAliveInterval\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sshd -T | grep -i clientaliveinterval\n\nclientaliveinterval 600\n\nIf \"ClientAliveInterval\" does not exist, does not have a value of \"600\" or less in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Terminating an unresponsive SSH session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended. In addition, quickly terminating an idle SSH session will also free up resources committed by the managed network element.\n\nTerminating network connections associated with communications sessions includes, for example, deallocating associated TCP/IP address/port pairs at the operating system level and deallocating networking assignments at the application level if multiple application sessions are using a single operating system-level network connection. This does not mean the operating system terminates all sessions or network access; it only ends the unresponsive session and releases the resources associated with that session.\n\nRHEL 9 utilizes /etc/ssh/sshd_config for configurations of OpenSSH. Within the sshd_config, the product of the values of \"ClientAliveInterval\" and \"ClientAliveCountMax\" are used to establish the inactivity threshold. The \"ClientAliveInterval\" is a timeout interval in seconds, after which if no data has been received from the client, sshd will send a message through the encrypted channel to request a response from the client. The \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is the number of client alive messages that may be sent without sshd receiving any messages back from the client. If this threshold is met, sshd will disconnect the client. For more information on these settings and others, refer to the sshd_config man pages.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000126-GPOS-00066, SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072, SRG-OS-000279-GPOS-00109, SRG-OS-000395-GPOS-00175","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001133","CCI-002361","CCI-002891"],"reference_identifier":"3339","uuid":"943da0b1-008b-4784-9a6c-e955afbecfba","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 68CDE98FFF128DC4A33D77E088B9CB8D29C77037\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic are terminated after 10 minutes of becoming unresponsive.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257997","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257997","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257997","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257997r1069370_rule","rule_id":"SV-257997","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255105","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH server configuration file must be group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file and the contents of \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" to be group-owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the group ownership of the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file and the contents of \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d -exec stat -c \"%G %n\" {} \\;\n\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/50-cloud-init.conf\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/50-redhat.conf\n\nIf the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file or \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" or any files in the sshd_config.d directory do not have a group owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services, which if configured incorrectly, can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations. Therefore, service configuration files must be owned by the correct group to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8363","uuid":"da1c573e-7cf1-4785-9fc3-cf1eb73cc002","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 666DD996E177668CBBFC325662EA8D43BB94B884\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSH server configuration file must be group-owned by root.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257998","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257998","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257998","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257998r1082181_rule","rule_id":"SV-257998","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255110","rule_title":"The RHEL 9 SSH server configuration file must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure  the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file and the contents of \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" to be owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown -R root /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the ownership of the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file and the contents of \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d -exec stat -c \"%U %n\" {} \\;\n\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/50-cloud-init.conf\nroot /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/50-redhat.conf\n\nIf the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file or \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" or any files in the \"sshd_config.d\" directory do not have an owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services, which if configured incorrectly, can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations. Therefore, service configuration files must be owned by the correct group to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4255","uuid":"a5aeb286-a7d5-4b77-9e34-9476d8202616","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B6B22BAABF2A2989405D4F3E8D0E09A7B1AE3A46\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The RHEL 9 SSH server configuration file must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-257999","group_tree":[{"id":"V-257999","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-257999","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-257999r1155686_rule","rule_id":"SV-257999","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255115","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH server configuration files' permissions must not be modified.","fix_text":"Run the following commands to restore the correct permissions of OpenSSH server configuration files:\n\n$ sudo rpm --setugids openssh-server\n$ sudo rpm --setperms openssh-server","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the permissions of the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo rpm --verify openssh-server | awk '! ($2 == \"c\" && $1 ~ /^.\\..\\.\\.\\.\\..\\./) {print $0}'\n\nIf the command returns any output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services, that if configured incorrectly, can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations. Therefore, service configuration files must have correct permissions (owner, group owner, mode) to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9295","uuid":"eac5189d-482e-402c-8ef8-8179759a5283","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 030E55A54DE2A7E747A280435F98D82BE008CCA0\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSH server configuration files' permissions must not be modified.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258000","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258000","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258000","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258000r1045063_rule","rule_id":"SV-258000","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255120","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH private host key files must have mode 0640 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Configure the mode of SSH private host key files under \"/etc/ssh\" to \"0640\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/ssh/ssh_host*key\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH private host key files have a mode of \"0640\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/ssh/*_key\n\n640 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_dsa_key\n640 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key\n640 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\n640 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key\n\nIf any private host key file has a mode more permissive than \"0640\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an unauthorized user obtains the private SSH host key file, the host could be impersonated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2847","uuid":"c386b461-4f1e-4dd6-8ddb-74095806e778","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BB313451584BCE98442A8EF9FDCC8E11A0848FC5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 SSH private host key files must have mode 0640 or less permissive.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258001","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258001","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258001","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258001r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258001","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255125","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH public host key files must have mode 0644 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Change the mode of public host key files under \"/etc/ssh\" to \"0644\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0644 /etc/ssh/*key.pub\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH public host key files have a mode of \"0644\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\nNote: SSH public key files may be found in other directories on the system depending on the installation.\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/ssh/*.pub\n\n644 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_dsa_key.pub\n644 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key.pub\n644 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key.pub\n644 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key.pub\n\nIf any key.pub file has a mode more permissive than \"0644\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a public host key file is modified by an unauthorized user, the SSH service may be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2383","uuid":"2d40a139-3ee7-47c1-9acd-01f2a24858db","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 20ACE5A8DCC2FE9E8B66418D7B95C5F8FAE1AE95\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 SSH public host key files must have mode 0644 or less permissive.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258002","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258002","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258002","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258002r1155590_rule","rule_id":"SV-258002","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255130","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow compression or must only allow compression after successful authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to not allow compression.\n\nUncomment the \"Compression\" keyword in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" on the system and set the value to \"delayed\" or \"no\":\n\nCompression no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 9 SSH daemon performs compression after a user successfully authenticates with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*compression'\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:Compression no\n\nIf the \"Compression\" keyword is set to \"yes\", is missing, or the returned line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If compression is allowed in an SSH connection prior to authentication, vulnerabilities in the compression software could result in compromise of the system from an unauthenticated connection, potentially with root privileges.\n\nCompression options are:\nno - disables compression\ndelayed - allow compression only after authentication\nyes - enables compression before authentication, which can leak sensitive metadata and is not recommended","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7889","uuid":"75bda306-f137-44ee-b73b-86149ea89e5e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B608E7AAB294AC4AA85AE3195A718EED06FD5365\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow compression or must only allow compression after successful authentication.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258003","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258003","title":"SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258003","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151","rule_id_src":"SV-258003r1045065_rule","rule_id":"SV-258003","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255135","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow GSSAPI authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to not allow GSSAPI authentication.\n\nAdd or uncomment the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\" and set the value to \"no\":\n\nGSSAPIAuthentication no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon does not allow GSSAPI authentication with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*gssapiauthentication'\n\nGSSAPIAuthentication no\n\nIf the value is returned as \"yes\", the returned line is commented out, no output is returned, and the use of GSSAPI authentication has not been documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.\n\nIf the required value is not set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Generic Security Service Application Program Interface (GSSAPI) authentication is used to provide additional authentication mechanisms to applications. Allowing GSSAPI authentication through SSH exposes the system's GSSAPI to remote hosts, increasing the attack surface of the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001813"],"reference_identifier":"2542","uuid":"2b0ae4eb-c488-4543-9c94-ae552e271172","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8B80E79204E89F99BF8894E5E6C7E204FA054C62\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow GSSAPI authentication.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258004","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258004","title":"SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258004","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151","rule_id_src":"SV-258004r1045067_rule","rule_id":"SV-258004","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255140","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow Kerberos authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to not allow Kerberos authentication.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"no\":\n\nKerberosAuthentication no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon does not allow Kerberos authentication with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*kerberosauthentication'\n\nKerberosAuthentication no\n\nIf the value is returned as \"yes\", the returned line is commented out, no output is returned, and the use of Kerberos authentication has not been documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Kerberos authentication for SSH is often implemented using Generic Security Service Application Program Interface (GSSAPI). If Kerberos is enabled through SSH, the SSH daemon provides a means of access to the system's Kerberos implementation. Vulnerabilities in the system's Kerberos implementations may be subject to exploitation.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001813"],"reference_identifier":"7038","uuid":"f8a11f4c-341b-4d88-a5cf-c5549522cf29","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 76983D7B201BF31308FB655280BF98C5A981FDB4\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow Kerberos authentication.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258005","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258005","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258005","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258005r1045069_rule","rule_id":"SV-258005","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255145","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow rhosts authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to not allow rhosts authentication.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"yes\":\n\nIgnoreRhosts yes\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon does not allow rhosts authentication with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*ignorerhosts'\n\nIgnoreRhosts yes\n\nIf the value is returned as \"no\", the returned line is commented out, or no output is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"SSH trust relationships mean a compromise on one host can allow an attacker to move trivially to other hosts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2376","uuid":"5d5592e1-b619-4017-ada8-f940ff52043f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258006","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258006","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258006","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258006r1045071_rule","rule_id":"SV-258006","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255150","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow known hosts authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to not allow known hosts authentication.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"yes\":\n\nIgnoreUserKnownHosts yes\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon does not allow known hosts authentication with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*ignoreuserknownhosts'\n\nIgnoreUserKnownHosts yes\n\nIf the value is returned as \"no\", the returned line is commented out, or no output is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the IgnoreUserKnownHosts setting for the SSH daemon provides additional assurance that remote login via SSH will require a password, even in the event of misconfiguration elsewhere.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2815","uuid":"fe3c206e-0c83-401a-8a7c-152c362f2e11","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2EADEAA06809A00DAF2946DD5A22860777B2FA85\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must not allow known hosts authentication.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258007","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258007","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258007","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258007r1045073_rule","rule_id":"SV-258007","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255155","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must disable remote X connections for interactive users.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to not allow X11 forwarding.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"no\":\n\nX11forwarding no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon does not allow X11Forwarding with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*x11forwarding'\n\nX11forwarding no\n\nIf the value is returned as \"yes\", the returned line is commented out, or no output is returned, and X11 forwarding is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When X11 forwarding is enabled, there may be additional exposure to the server and client displays if the sshd proxy display is configured to listen on the wildcard address.  By default, sshd binds the forwarding server to the loopback address and sets the hostname part of the DISPLAY environment variable to localhost. This prevents remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8577","uuid":"74610e99-b334-4df1-ae70-9197fdc388dc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5AB8DF72261405BAAB35C48E279E86ED21850CB3\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must disable remote X connections for interactive users.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258008","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258008","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258008","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258008r1045075_rule","rule_id":"SV-258008","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255160","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must perform strict mode checking of home directory configuration files.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to perform strict mode checking of home directory configuration files.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"yes\":\n\nStrictModes yes\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon performs strict mode checking of home directory configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*strictmodes'\n\nStrictModes yes\n\nIf the \"StrictModes\" keyword is set to \"no\", the returned line is commented out, or no output is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If other users have access to modify user-specific SSH configuration files, they may be able to log into the system as another user.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9576","uuid":"e79d0128-d4fd-430f-9c2e-e058cc6d4ba5","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C6FDF5325B5CEDA2E9A586F74493A353E437427A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must perform strict mode checking of home directory configuration files.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258009","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258009","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258009","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258009r1045077_rule","rule_id":"SV-258009","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255165","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must display the date and time of the last successful account logon upon an SSH logon.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to provide users with feedback on when account accesses last occurred.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"yes\":\n\nPrintLastLog yes\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon provides users with feedback on when account accesses last occurred with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*printlastlog'\n\nPrintLastLog yes\n\nIf the \"PrintLastLog\" keyword is set to \"no\", the returned line is commented out, or no output is returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Providing users feedback on when account accesses last occurred facilitates user recognition and reporting of unauthorized account use.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6876","uuid":"3d00f5f8-8ec7-47bf-bac5-15db5728e290","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CE91AD29F1F86E86CE42C1C5A5ADFB89A5CE1941\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must display the date and time of the last successful account logon upon an SSH logon.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258011","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258011","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258011","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258011r1045079_rule","rule_id":"SV-258011","rule_version":"RHEL-09-255175","rule_title":"RHEL 9 SSH daemon must prevent remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.","fix_text":"Configure the SSH daemon to prevent remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or to a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"yes\":\n\nX11UseLocalhost yes\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SSH daemon prevents remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*x11uselocalhost'\n\nX11UseLocalhost yes\n\nIf the \"X11UseLocalhost\" keyword is set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When X11 forwarding is enabled, there may be additional exposure to the server and client displays if the sshd proxy display is configured to listen on the wildcard address. By default, sshd binds the forwarding server to the loopback address and sets the hostname part of the \"DISPLAY\" environment variable to localhost. This prevents remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8513","uuid":"78d8a093-c049-4973-8f3c-5e856cc59531","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B4C355C31C71B59B172328D25B062091E3CADFA1\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 SSH daemon must prevent remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258012","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258012","title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258012","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","rule_id_src":"SV-258012r1014855_rule","rule_id":"SV-258012","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system via a graphical user logon.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\n\nAdd the following lines to the [org/gnome/login-screen] section of the \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\":\n\n[org/gnome/login-screen]\n\nbanner-message-enable=true\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 displays the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the operating system via a graphical user logon.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine if the operating system displays a banner at the logon screen with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.login-screen banner-message-enable\n\ntrue\n\nIf the result is \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\n\nFor U.S. Government systems, system use notifications are required only for access via login interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000048","CCI-001384","CCI-001385","CCI-001386","CCI-001387","CCI-001388"],"reference_identifier":"1348","uuid":"2fcd684d-732c-4a2a-ad48-94f3a8ab9378","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1864A58CD13BE00FB986EBF7BB898140EF91748B\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258013","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258013","title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258013","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","rule_id_src":"SV-258013r1045082_rule","rule_id":"SV-258013","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the banner-message-enable setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent a user from overriding the banner setting for graphical user interfaces. \n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent nonprivileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/login-screen/banner-message-enable\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces. \n\nDetermine if the org.gnome.login-screen banner-message-enable key is writable with the following command:\n\t\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.login-screen banner-message-enable\n\t \nfalse\n\t \nIf \"banner-message-enable\" is writable or the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\n\nFor U.S. Government systems, system use notifications are required only for access via login interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000048","CCI-001384","CCI-001385","CCI-001386","CCI-001387","CCI-001388"],"reference_identifier":"2476","uuid":"ee96f38b-77bb-4c62-b0f3-88ce63e723ba","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 27B0FAC9F163C760D3EF01A0B28385400EC5D9C1\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the banner-message-enable setting for the graphical user interface.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258014","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258014","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258014","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","rule_id_src":"SV-258014r1045084_rule","rule_id":"SV-258014","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable the graphical user interface automount function unless required.","fix_text":"Configure the GNOME desktop to disable automated mounting of removable media.\n\nThe dconf settings can be edited in the /etc/dconf/db/* location.\n\nUpdate the [org/gnome/desktop/media-handling] section of the \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-security-settings\" database file and add or update the following lines:\n\n[org/gnome/desktop/media-handling]\nautomount-open=false\n\nThen update the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 disables the graphical user interface automount function with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.media-handling automount-open \n\nfalse\n\nIf \"automount-open\" is set to \"true\", and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Automatically mounting file systems permits easy introduction of unknown devices, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000778","CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"8078","uuid":"3fbeccce-48ec-4842-82e0-003324cc1644","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1F36FD5D42EFDB776EFF2325338B1803368A6E73\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must disable the graphical user interface automount function unless required.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258015","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258015","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258015","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","rule_id_src":"SV-258015r1045086_rule","rule_id":"SV-258015","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disabling of the graphical user interface automount function.","fix_text":"Configure the GNOME desktop to not allow a user to change the setting that disables automated mounting of removable media.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/00-security-settings-lock\" to prevent user modification:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/media-handling/automount-open\n\nThen update the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 disables the ability of the user to override the graphical user interface automount setting.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n\nsystem-db:local\n\nCheck that the automount setting is locked from nonprivileged user modification with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n$ grep 'automount-open' /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/* \n\n/org/gnome/desktop/media-handling/automount-open\n\nIf the command does not return at least the example result, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A nonprivileged account is any operating system account with authorizations of a nonprivileged user.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000778","CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"1276","uuid":"156c7bb5-8302-4fbd-9a7b-d20c3cd20db4","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D821FF4E3CACAEE015F0C3A938D3CE65DE61BB1F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disabling of the graphical user interface automount function.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258016","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258016","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258016","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-258016r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-258016","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable the graphical user interface autorun function unless required.","fix_text":"Configure the GNOME desktop to disable the autorun function on removable media.\n\nThe dconf settings can be edited in the /etc/dconf/db/* location.\n\nUpdate the [org/gnome/desktop/media-handling] section of the \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-security-settings\" database file and add or update the following lines:\n\n[org/gnome/desktop/media-handling]\nautorun-never=true\n\nThen update the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 disables the graphical user interface autorun function with the following command:\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.media-handling autorun-never \n\ntrue\n\nIf \"autorun-never\" is set to \"false\", and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing autorun commands to execute may introduce malicious code to a system. Configuring this setting prevents autorun commands from executing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"4254","uuid":"4771d368-3e4b-4fc0-89f0-fe4b72b09e0c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EF3D98D18C7678B08D6210109A64A1FA7330ABD9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must disable the graphical user interface autorun function unless required.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258017","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258017","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258017","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","rule_id_src":"SV-258017r1155688_rule","rule_id":"SV-258017","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disabling of the graphical user interface autorun function.","fix_text":"Configure the GNOME desktop to not allow a user to change the setting that disables autorun on removable media.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/00-security-settings-lock\" to prevent user modification:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/media-handling/autorun-never\n\nThen update the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 disables ability of the user to override the graphical user interface autorun setting.\n\nCheck that the autorun setting is set to prevent user modification with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.desktop.media-handling autorun-never\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"autorun-never\" is writable, the result is \"true\". If this is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Techniques used to address this include protocols using nonces (e.g., numbers generated for a specific one-time use) or challenges (e.g., TLS, WS_Security). Additional techniques include time-synchronous or challenge-response one-time authenticators.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000778","CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"8499","uuid":"69306bdb-b3ad-4505-83db-47d3fd85f23d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A54EB6CE466DC71F06C037301EB652A01D6CBF10\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disabling of the graphical user interface autorun function.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258018","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258018","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258018","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","rule_id_src":"SV-258018r1045090_rule","rule_id":"SV-258018","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not allow unattended or automatic logon via the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure the GNOME desktop display manager to disable automatic login.\n\nSet AutomaticLoginEnable to false in the [daemon] section in /etc/gdm/custom.conf. For example:\n\n[daemon]\nAutomaticLoginEnable=false","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 does not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" in the \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n$  grep -i automaticlogin /etc/gdm/custom.conf\n\nAutomaticLoginEnable=false\n\nIf the value of \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" is not set to \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to restrict system access to authenticated users negatively impacts operating system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8792","uuid":"bf5d9631-121c-48df-8ce5-a634e860462f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258019","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258019","title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258019","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","rule_id_src":"SV-258019r1045092_rule","rule_id":"SV-258019","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be able to initiate directly a session lock for all connection types using smart card when the smart card is removed.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enable a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.\n\nSelect or create an authselect profile and incorporate the \"with-smartcard-lock-on-removal\" feature with the following example:\n\n$ sudo authselect select sssd with-smartcard with-smartcard-lock-on-removal\n\nAlternatively, the dconf settings can be edited in the /etc/dconf/db/* location.\n\nAdd or update the [org/gnome/settings-daemon/peripherals/smartcard] section of the /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-security-settings\" database file and add or update the following lines:\n\n[org/gnome/settings-daemon/peripherals/smartcard]\nremoval-action='lock-screen'\n\nThen update the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 enables a user's session lock until that user reestablishes access using established identification and authentication procedures with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.settings-daemon.peripherals.smartcard removal-action\n \n'lock-screen'\n \nIf the result is not 'lock-screen', this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined. Rather than be forced to wait for a period of time to expire before the user session can be locked, RHEL 9 needs to provide users with the ability to manually invoke a session lock so users can secure their session if it is necessary to temporarily vacate the immediate physical vicinity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000056","CCI-000057","CCI-000058"],"reference_identifier":"5499","uuid":"24ab6883-ff54-424e-b860-ad2319fe109e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 027A80C5A6D1EB6C84180A6D9C5875CC3B9DD36E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must be able to initiate directly a session lock for all connection types using smart card when the smart card is removed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258020","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258020","title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258020","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","rule_id_src":"SV-258020r1045094_rule","rule_id":"SV-258020","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disabling of the graphical user smart card removal action.","fix_text":"Add the following line to \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/00-security-settings-lock\" to prevent user override of the smart card removal action:\n\n/org/gnome/settings-daemon/peripherals/smartcard/removal-action\n\nThen update the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 disables ability of the user to override the smart card removal action setting.\n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.settings-daemon.peripherals.smartcard removal-action\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"removal-action\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined. Rather than be forced to wait for a period of time to expire before the user session can be locked, RHEL 9 needs to provide users with the ability to manually invoke a session lock so users can secure their session if it is necessary to temporarily vacate the immediate physical vicinity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000056","CCI-000057","CCI-000058"],"reference_identifier":"1740","uuid":"cb4df6d2-2bfd-4914-919b-511b339ecaf6","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8FB5DB8D9B58ADEC7E6AA4D403489D55FAD5A3D4\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disabling of the graphical user smart card removal action.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258021","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258021","title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258021","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","rule_id_src":"SV-258021r1015088_rule","rule_id":"SV-258021","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271055","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enable a user session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures for graphical user sessions.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enable a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following example:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nEdit the \"[org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\" section of the database file and add or update the following lines:\n\n# Set this to true to lock the screen when the screensaver activates\nlock-enabled=true\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 enables a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures with the following command:\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.screensaver lock-enabled\n\ntrue\n\nIf the setting is \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined.\n\nRegardless of where the session lock is determined and implemented, once invoked, the session lock must remain in place until the user reauthenticates. No other activity aside from reauthentication must unlock the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000056","CCI-000057","CCI-000058"],"reference_identifier":"6350","uuid":"63e30b86-600f-4b48-80aa-6bc2c87880aa","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 33C1C9242FA2208A59FB813745B963A221C94C04\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enable a user session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures for graphical user sessions.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258022","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258022","title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258022","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","rule_id_src":"SV-258022r1045097_rule","rule_id":"SV-258022","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver lock-enabled setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system. If the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent nonprivileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces. \n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.desktop.screensaver lock-enabled\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"lock-enabled\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.\n\nImplementing session settings will have little value if a user is able to manipulate these settings from the defaults prescribed in the other requirements of this implementation guide.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000056","CCI-000057","CCI-000058"],"reference_identifier":"6393","uuid":"b7e7c81d-e3aa-40d6-b72a-3d9d0b29ab91","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 91D371D11C4F2DDD36E398A429933263C6B5828E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver lock-enabled setting for the graphical user interface.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258023","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258023","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258023","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","rule_id_src":"SV-258023r1155656_rule","rule_id":"SV-258023","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271065","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must automatically lock graphical user sessions after 10 minutes of inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to initiate a screensaver after a 10-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nEdit /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver and add or update the following lines:\n\n[org/gnome/desktop/session]\n# Set the lock time out to 600 seconds before the session is considered idle\nidle-delay=uint32 600\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 initiates a session lock after a 10-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces with the following command:\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ sudo gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.session idle-delay\n\nuint32 600\n\nIf \"idle-delay\" is set to \"0\" or a value greater than \"600\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not logout because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, the GNOME desktop can be configured to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate a session lock.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010, SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000057","CCI-000060"],"reference_identifier":"3755","uuid":"d85105ce-048e-4106-a5f2-7509af81448e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4584BA865FBC061D28C5D925C190034A19E117FF\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must automatically lock graphical user sessions after 10 minutes of inactivity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258024","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258024","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258024","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","rule_id_src":"SV-258024r1045100_rule","rule_id":"SV-258024","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271070","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the session idle-delay setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system. If the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent nonprivileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/session/idle-delay\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces. \n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.desktop.session idle-delay\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"idle-delay\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not logout because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, the GNOME desktop can be configured to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock. As such, users should not be allowed to change session settings.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010, SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000057","CCI-000060"],"reference_identifier":"1229","uuid":"b711cf33-5e13-4416-ae90-a6e0c9561a43","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DD3D50D095D951F40C350D04016A57515AF006BB\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the session idle-delay setting for the graphical user interface.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258025","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258025","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258025","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","rule_id_src":"SV-258025r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-258025","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271075","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must initiate a session lock for graphical user interfaces when the screensaver is activated.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to initiate a session lock for graphical user interfaces when a screensaver is activated.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\n[org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\nlock-delay=uint32 5\n\nThe \"uint32\" must be included along with the integer key values as shown.\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 initiates a session lock for graphical user interfaces when the screensaver is activated with the following command:\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.screensaver lock-delay\n\nuint32 5\n\nIf the \"uint32\" setting is not set to \"5\" or less, or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to logout because of the temporary nature of the absence.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"3427","uuid":"e0a2e458-b345-4d69-bca4-4836a9290954","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1746F15BF9A5BE612709CBA43129CBC80672EEF8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must initiate a session lock for graphical user interfaces when the screensaver is activated.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258026","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258026","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258026","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","rule_id_src":"SV-258026r1045103_rule","rule_id":"SV-258026","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271080","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the session lock-delay setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system. If the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent nonprivileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces. \n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.desktop.screensaver lock-delay\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"lock-delay\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not logout because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, the GNOME desktop can be configured to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock. As such, users should not be allowed to change session settings.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"7083","uuid":"205ed1ba-50a9-4003-9f5a-fb48316d92aa","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5EB922A9346E267282F14CECFE82B7B934E62949\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the session lock-delay setting for the graphical user interface.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258027","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258027","title":"SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258027","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012","rule_id_src":"SV-258027r1045106_rule","rule_id":"SV-258027","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271085","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must conceal, via the session lock, information previously visible on the display with a publicly viewable image.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent a user from overriding the picture-uri setting for graphical user interfaces.\n\nIn the file \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-security-settings\", add or update the following lines:\n\n[org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\npicture-uri=''\n\nPrevent user modification by adding the following line to \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/00-security-settings-lock\":\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/picture-uri\n\nUpdate the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nTo ensure the screensaver is configured to be blank, run the following command:\n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.desktop.screensaver picture-uri\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"picture-uri\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Setting the screensaver mode to blank-only conceals the contents of the display from passersby.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000060"],"reference_identifier":"5776","uuid":"782554a4-28ec-4dc7-8707-0c7744546356","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC30AB54EF27D6C39B8593850736EC7634BBB858\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must conceal, via the session lock, information previously visible on the display with a publicly viewable image.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258028","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258028","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258028","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258028r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258028","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271090","rule_title":"RHEL 9 effective dconf policy must match the policy keyfiles.","fix_text":"Update the dconf databases by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check the last modification time of the local databases, comparing it to the last modification time of the related keyfiles. The following command will check every dconf database and compare its modification time to the related system keyfiles:\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ function dconf_needs_update { for db in $(find /etc/dconf/db -maxdepth 1 -type f); do db_mtime=$(stat -c %Y \"$db\"); keyfile_mtime=$(stat -c %Y \"$db\".d/* | sort -n | tail -1); if [ -n \"$db_mtime\" ] && [ -n \"$keyfile_mtime\" ] && [ \"$db_mtime\" -lt \"$keyfile_mtime\" ]; then echo \"$db needs update\"; return 1; fi; done; }; dconf_needs_update\n\nIf the command has any output, then a dconf database needs to be updated, and this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unlike text-based keyfiles, the binary database is impossible to check through most automated and all manual means; therefore, in order to evaluate dconf configuration, both have to be true at the same time - configuration files have to be compliant, and the database needs to be more recent than those keyfiles, which gives confidence that it reflects them.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1179","uuid":"5b19d79c-86a1-4dfa-accb-4cc34fca97c9","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D99DAE253BA8BB3901A6F0ED7C88B0EC66D8E3C8\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 effective dconf policy must match the policy keyfiles.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258029","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258029","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258029","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258029r1045109_rule","rule_id":"SV-258029","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271095","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable the ability of a user to restart the system from the login screen.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disable a user's ability to restart the system.\n\n$ gsettings set org.gnome.login-screen disable-restart-buttons true\n\nUpdate the dconf system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 disables a user's ability to restart the system with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.login-screen disable-restart-buttons\n \ntrue\n \nIf \"disable-restart-buttons\" is \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A user who is at the console can reboot the system at the login screen. If restart or shutdown buttons are pressed at the login screen, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to reboot.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3684","uuid":"e2109c49-2963-4d53-9fb6-ac6c7fdfdb2d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C44928C6D95DF5180B74DB691155BA724B190E35\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must disable the ability of a user to restart the system from the login screen.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258030","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258030","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258030","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258030r1045112_rule","rule_id":"SV-258030","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271100","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disable-restart-buttons setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent a user from overriding the disable-restart-buttons setting for graphical user interfaces. \n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following line to prevent nonprivileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/login-screen/disable-restart-buttons\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 prevents a user from overriding the disable-restart-buttons setting for graphical user interfaces. \n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.login-screen disable-restart-buttons\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"disable-restart-buttons\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A user who is at the console can reboot the system at the login screen. If restart or shutdown buttons are pressed at the login screen, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to reboot.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5666","uuid":"b6a98a2e-cb7a-462f-ad71-d912c9fc0253","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 24BDCF8859ADC34B2AFBEEA8AEDB9C7EF77F628B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the disable-restart-buttons setting for the graphical user interface.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258031","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258031","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258031","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258031r1134920_rule","rule_id":"SV-258031","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271105","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable the ability of a user to accidentally press Ctrl-Alt-Del and cause a system to shut down or reboot.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to ignore the Ctrl-Alt-Del sequence in the GNOME desktop.\n\nRun the following command to set the media-keys logout setting:\n\n$ gsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys logout \"['']\"\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to ignore the Ctrl-Alt-Del sequence in the GNOME desktop with the following command:\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is not applicable.\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys logout \n\n['']\n\nIf the GNOME desktop is configured to shut down when Ctrl-Alt-Del is pressed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A locally logged-in user who presses Ctrl-Alt-Del, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2683","uuid":"b040f77f-65f6-4b41-90b8-6a73cdd9fa6f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9797938C6B9E99261DF531BD70DEDB1270D3FE16\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must disable the ability of a user to accidentally press Ctrl-Alt-Del and cause a system to shut down or reboot.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258032","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258032","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258032","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258032r1045117_rule","rule_id":"SV-258032","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271110","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the Ctrl-Alt-Del sequence settings for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disallow the user changing the Ctrl-Alt-Del sequence in the GNOME desktop.\n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following line to the session locks file to prevent nonprivileged users from modifying the Ctrl-Alt-Del setting:\n\n/org/gnome/settings-daemon/plugins/media-keys/logout\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that users cannot enable the Ctrl-Alt-Del sequence in the GNOME desktop with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings writable org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys logout\n \nfalse\n \nIf \"logout\" is writable and the result is \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A locally logged-in user who presses Ctrl-Alt-Del, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3116","uuid":"c3859dad-997c-41c9-9831-5ae0660db7e9","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 92B8C3C04C1D4746764D374C1A0A1D8A7EDE42FA\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent a user from overriding the Ctrl-Alt-Del sequence settings for the graphical user interface.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258033","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258033","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258033","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258033r1045120_rule","rule_id":"SV-258033","rule_version":"RHEL-09-271115","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable the user list at logon for graphical user interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disable the user list at logon for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the systemwide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system. If the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/02-login-screen\n\n[org/gnome/login-screen]\ndisable-user-list=true\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 9 default graphical user interface, the GNOME desktop environment. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that RHEL 9 disables the user logon list for graphical user interfaces with the following command:\n\n$ gsettings get org.gnome.login-screen disable-user-list\n\ntrue\n\nIf the setting is \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Leaving the user list enabled is a security risk since it allows anyone with physical access to the system to enumerate known user accounts without authenticated access to the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2150","uuid":"72e2d29d-9aa9-47f6-a059-b7086aea68da","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 615DEAB14F97012ADE34B4DBF6600E427EBAFAC6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must disable the user list at logon for graphical user interfaces.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258034","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258034","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258034","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","rule_id_src":"SV-258034r1051267_rule","rule_id":"SV-258034","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured to disable USB mass storage.","fix_text":"To configure the system to prevent the usb-storage kernel module from being loaded, add the following lines to the file \"/etc/modprobe.d/usb-storage.conf\" (or create \"usb-storage.conf\" if it does not exist):\n\ninstall usb-storage /bin/false\nblacklist usb-storage","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 disables the ability to load the USB Storage kernel module with the following command:\n\n$ grep -r usb-storage /etc/modprobe.conf /etc/modprobe.d/* \n\ninstall usb-storage /bin/false\nblacklist usb-storage\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or either line is commented out, and use of USB Storage is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"USB mass storage permits easy introduction of unknown devices, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000778","CCI-001958","CCI-003959"],"reference_identifier":"3582","uuid":"3237c1b3-fd64-4a47-b522-1ced4b4636fd","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D55914DF603DF598269E57AAD7558C2B14F3AB4D\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured to disable USB mass storage.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258035","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258035","title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258035","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","rule_id_src":"SV-258035r1045125_rule","rule_id":"SV-258035","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the USBGuard package installed.","fix_text":"Install the usbguard package with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf install usbguard\n\nEnable the service to start on boot and then start it with the following commands:\n$ sudo systemctl enable usbguard\n$ sudo systemctl start usbguard\n\nVerify the status of the service with the following command:\n$ sudo systemctl status usbguard\n\nNote: usbguard will need to be configured to allow authorized devices once it is enabled on RHEL 9.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify USBGuard is installed on the operating system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf list installed usbguard\n\nExample output:\n\nInstalled Packages\nusbguard.x86_64          1.0.0-10.el9_1.2          @rhel-9-for-x86_64-appstream-rpms\n\nIf the USBGuard package is not installed, ask the SA to indicate how unauthorized peripherals are being blocked.\n\nIf there is no evidence that unauthorized peripherals are being blocked before establishing a connection, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system is virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The USBguard-daemon is the main component of the USBGuard software framework. It runs as a service in the background and enforces the USB device authorization policy for all USB devices. The policy is defined by a set of rules using a rule language described in the usbguard-rules.conf file. The policy and the authorization state of USB devices can be modified during runtime using the usbguard tool.\n\nThe system administrator (SA) must work with the site information system security officer (ISSO) to determine a list of authorized peripherals and establish rules within the USBGuard software framework to allow only authorized devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001958","CCI-003959"],"reference_identifier":"2263","uuid":"13765dc1-4856-47dd-99ff-db1d438e9ec5","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CDA5A8CDC4338D4441306C40CC2BCA652AC24716\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must have the USBGuard package installed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258036","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258036","title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258036","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","rule_id_src":"SV-258036r1014861_rule","rule_id":"SV-258036","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the USBGuard package enabled.","fix_text":"To enable the USBGuard service run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now usbguard","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 has USBGuard enabled with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active usbguard\n\nactive\n\nIf usbguard is not active, ask the SA to indicate how unauthorized peripherals are being blocked.\n\nIf there is no evidence that unauthorized peripherals are being blocked before establishing a connection, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system is virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The USBguard-daemon is the main component of the USBGuard software framework. It runs as a service in the background and enforces the USB device authorization policy for all USB devices. The policy is defined by a set of rules using a rule language described in the usbguard-rules.conf file. The policy and the authorization state of USB devices can be modified during runtime using the usbguard tool.\n\nThe system administrator (SA) must work with the site information system security officer (ISSO) to determine a list of authorized peripherals and establish rules within the USBGuard software framework to allow only authorized devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001958","CCI-003959"],"reference_identifier":"5779","uuid":"85b232b5-d85f-4ed7-8891-7f61b8504a59","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D01C9BA58B4F845F58C4B402E7E3CB26BCEAA9FB\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must have the USBGuard package enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258037","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258037","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258037","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-258037r1014863_rule","rule_id":"SV-258037","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enable Linux audit logging for the USBGuard daemon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 USBGuard AuditBackend to use the audit system.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in /etc/usbguard/usbguard-daemon.conf \n\nAuditBackend=LinuxAudit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"To verify that Linux Audit logging is enabled for the USBGuard daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep AuditBackend /etc/usbguard/usbguard-daemon.conf \n\nAuditBackend=LinuxAudit \n\nIf \"AuditBackend\" is not set to \"LinuxAudit\", this is a finding.\n\nIf the system is virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nThe list of audited events is the set of events for which audits are to be generated. This set of events is typically a subset of the list of all events for which the system is capable of generating audit records.\n\nDOD has defined the list of events for which RHEL 9 will provide an audit record generation capability as the following:\n\n1) Successful and unsuccessful attempts to access, modify, or delete privileges, security objects, security levels, or categories of information (e.g., classification levels);\n\n2) Access actions, such as successful and unsuccessful logon attempts, privileged activities or other system-level access, starting and ending time for user access to the system, concurrent logons from different workstations, successful and unsuccessful accesses to objects, all program initiations, and all direct access to the information system;\n\n3) All account creations, modifications, disabling, and terminations; and \n\n4) All kernel module load, unload, and restart actions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"3475","uuid":"0c36db1f-8838-4ea2-a93a-703bb121ab28","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 02CE0AE510FBD3ADB62D03A7DE4C9454218D7EDA\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enable Linux audit logging for the USBGuard daemon.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258038","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258038","title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258038","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","rule_id_src":"SV-258038r1045128_rule","rule_id":"SV-258038","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must block unauthorized peripherals before establishing a connection.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enable the blocking of unauthorized peripherals with the following command:\n\nNote: This command must be run from a root shell and will create an allow list for any usb devices currently connected to the system.\n\n# usbguard generate-policy --no-hash > /etc/usbguard/rules.conf\n\nNote: Enabling and starting usbguard without properly configuring it for an individual system will immediately prevent any access over a usb device such as a keyboard or mouse.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system is virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the USBGuard has a policy configured with the following command:\n\n$ sudo usbguard list-rules\n\nallow id 1d6b:0001 serial\n\nIf the command does not return results or an error is returned, ask the SA to indicate how unauthorized peripherals are being blocked.\n\nIf there is no evidence that unauthorized peripherals are being blocked before establishing a connection, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The USBguard-daemon is the main component of the USBGuard software framework. It runs as a service in the background and enforces the USB device authorization policy for all USB devices. The policy is defined by a set of rules using a rule language described in the usbguard-rules.conf file. The policy and the authorization state of USB devices can be modified during runtime using the usbguard tool.\n\nThe system administrator (SA) must work with the site information system security officer (ISSO) to determine a list of authorized peripherals and establish rules within the USBGuard software framework to allow only authorized devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"6289","uuid":"35f45999-e0ea-4898-b869-be1fb4c4c1bf","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E79299C78CEEAF5AA902B21DC5FB016CE4D6833D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must block unauthorized peripherals before establishing a connection.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258039","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258039","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258039","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-258039r1045131_rule","rule_id":"SV-258039","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 Bluetooth must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disable the Bluetooth adapter when not in use.\n\nCreate or modify the \"/etc/modprobe.d/bluetooth.conf\" file with the following lines:\n\ninstall bluetooth /bin/false\nblacklist bluetooth\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 disables the ability to load the Bluetooth kernel module with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r bluetooth /etc/modprobe.conf /etc/modprobe.d/* \n\ninstall bluetooth /bin/false\nblacklist bluetooth\n\t\nIf the command does not return any output, or the lines are commented out, and use of Bluetooth is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This requirement applies to wireless peripheral technologies (e.g., wireless mice, keyboards, displays, etc.) used with RHEL 9 systems. Wireless peripherals (e.g., Wi-Fi/Bluetooth/IR keyboards, mice and pointing devices, and near field communications [NFC]) present a unique challenge by creating an open, unsecured port on a computer. Wireless peripherals must meet DOD requirements for wireless data transmission and be approved for use by the Authorizing Official (AO). Even though some wireless peripherals, such as mice and pointing devices, do not ordinarily carry information that need to be protected, modification of communications with these wireless peripherals may be used to compromise the RHEL 9 operating system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049, SRG-OS-000300-GPOS-00118","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381","CCI-001443"],"reference_identifier":"9980","uuid":"c84deaaf-70ce-417a-847c-50f6ab348f6e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 651D530216716A509A305A8DCC1E61A434801056\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 Bluetooth must be disabled.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258040","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258040","title":"SRG-OS-000299-GPOS-00117","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258040","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000299-GPOS-00117","rule_id_src":"SV-258040r991568_rule","rule_id":"SV-258040","rule_version":"RHEL-09-291040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 wireless network adapters must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the system to disable all wireless network interfaces with the following command:\n\n$ nmcli radio all off","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify there are no wireless interfaces configured on the system with the following command:\n\nNote: This requirement is Not Applicable for systems that do not have physical wireless network radios.\n\n$ nmcli device status\n\nDEVICE                    TYPE            STATE                    CONNECTION\nvirbr0                      bridge         connected             virbr0\nwlp7s0                    wifi              connected            wifiSSID\nenp6s0                    ethernet     disconnected        --\np2p-dev-wlp7s0     wifi-p2p     disconnected        --\nlo                             loopback    unmanaged           --\nvirbr0-nic                tun              unmanaged          --\n\nIf a wireless interface is configured and has not been documented and approved by the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This requirement applies to wireless peripheral technologies (e.g., wireless mice, keyboards, displays, etc.) used with RHEL 9 systems. Wireless peripherals (e.g., Wi-Fi/Bluetooth/IR keyboards, mice and pointing devices, and near field communications [NFC]) present a unique challenge by creating an open, unsecured port on a computer. Wireless peripherals must meet DOD requirements for wireless data transmission and be approved for use by the Authorizing Official (AO). Even though some wireless peripherals, such as mice and pointing devices, do not ordinarily carry information that need to be protected, modification of communications with these wireless peripherals may be used to compromise the RHEL 9 operating system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000299-GPOS-00117, SRG-OS-000300-GPOS-00118, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188, SRG-OS-000481-GPOS-00481","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001443","CCI-001444","CCI-002418","CCI-002421"],"reference_identifier":"6804","uuid":"04122e6c-a188-4bae-b09e-84f6b2eb71f2","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258041","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258041","title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258041","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","rule_id_src":"SV-258041r1038967_rule","rule_id":"SV-258041","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 user account passwords for new users or password changes must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file:\n\nPASS_MAX_DAYS 60","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces a 60-day maximum password lifetime for new user accounts by running the following command:\n\n$ grep -i pass_max_days /etc/login.defs\n\nPASS_MAX_DAYS 60\n\nIf the \"PASS_MAX_DAYS\" parameter value is greater than \"60\", or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked; therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If the operating system does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that the operating system passwords could be compromised.\n\nSetting the password maximum age ensures users are required to periodically change their passwords. Requiring shorter password lifetimes increases the risk of users writing down the password in a convenient location subject to physical compromise.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000199"],"reference_identifier":"1842","uuid":"351098cd-c74d-4b0c-b59f-43a7bdbf031e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9E98DF6216BF1BB1B9D42D9A58F28DEC58154EB2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 user account passwords for new users or password changes must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258042","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258042","title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258042","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","rule_id_src":"SV-258042r1045133_rule","rule_id":"SV-258042","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 user account passwords must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.","fix_text":"Configure noncompliant accounts to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.\n\npasswd -x 60 [user]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the maximum time period for existing passwords is restricted to 60 days with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$5 > 60 {printf \"%s %d\\n\", $1, $5}' /etc/shadow\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$5 <= 0 {printf \"%s %d\\n\", $1, $5}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked; therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If RHEL 9 does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that RHEL 9 passwords could be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000199"],"reference_identifier":"9766","uuid":"f0057bd3-078b-4b48-839a-22e58f576897","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258043","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258043","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258043","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258043r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258043","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411020","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 local interactive user accounts must be assigned a home directory upon creation.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to assign home directories to all new local interactive users by setting the \"CREATE_HOME\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" to \"yes\" as follows.\n\nCREATE_HOME yes","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all local interactive users on RHEL 9 are assigned a home directory upon creation with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i create_home /etc/login.defs\n\nCREATE_HOME yes\n\nIf the value for \"CREATE_HOME\" parameter is not set to \"yes\", the line is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If local interactive users are not assigned a valid home directory, there is no place for the storage and control of files they should own.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4539","uuid":"d599d6ec-8e3e-440d-87e0-1a23c6ff057d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC2A736CDDB1450AAB646D308457D8E23FB81798\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All RHEL 9 local interactive user accounts must be assigned a home directory upon creation.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258044","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258044","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258044","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258044r1184313_rule","rule_id":"SV-258044","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.","fix_text":"Remove the umask statement from all local interactive user's initialization files. \n\nIf the account is for an application, the requirement for a umask less restrictive than \"077\" can be documented with the information system security officer, but the user agreement for access to the account must specify that the local interactive user must log on to their account first and then switch the user to the application account with the correct option to gain the account's environment variables.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the default umask for all local interactive users is \"077\".\n\nIdentify the locations of all local interactive user home directories by looking at the \"/etc/passwd\" file.\n\nCheck all local interactive user initialization files for interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The example is for a system that is configured to create users home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n$ sudo find /home -maxdepth 2 -type f -name \".[^.]*\" -exec grep -iH -d skip --exclude=.bash_history umask {} \\;\n\n/home/disauser/.bash_history:grep -i umask /etc/bashrc /etc/csh.cshrc /etc/profile\n/home/disauser/.bash_history:grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files are found to have a umask statement that sets a value less restrictive than \"077\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1030","uuid":"0945a523-d4ef-45bc-9930-f106f95d600a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 10444F6882C168B66AED1F90CC575EBCDAE13ABE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258045","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258045","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258045","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-258045r958482_rule","rule_id":"SV-258045","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 duplicate User IDs (UIDs) must not exist for interactive users.","fix_text":"Edit the file \"/etc/passwd\" and provide each interactive user account that has a duplicate UID with a unique UID.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 contains no duplicate UIDs for interactive users with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F \":\" 'list[$3]++{print $1, $3}' /etc/passwd \n\nIf output is produced and the accounts listed are interactive user accounts, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, interactive users must be identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051, SRG-OS-000121-GPOS-00062, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000135","CCI-000764","CCI-000804"],"reference_identifier":"3304","uuid":"b64ca78f-f309-4cb3-aad7-ad215f7bf755","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258046","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258046","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258046","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258046r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258046","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 system accounts must not have an interactive login shell.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 so that all noninteractive accounts on the system do not have an interactive shell assigned to them.\n\nIf the system account needs a shell assigned for mission operations, document the need with the information system security officer (ISSO).\n\nRun the following command to disable the interactive shell for a specific noninteractive user account:\n\nReplace <user> with the user that has a login shell.\n\n$ sudo usermod --shell /sbin/nologin <user>\n\nDo not perform the steps in this section on the root account. Doing so will cause the system to become inaccessible.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that system accounts must not have an interactive login shell with the following command:\n\n$ awk -F: '($3<1000){print $1 \":\" $3 \":\" $7}' /etc/passwd\n\nroot:0:/bin/bash\nbin:1:/sbin/nologin\ndaemon:2:/sbin/nologin\nadm:3:/sbin/nologin\nlp:4:/sbin/nologin\n\nIdentify the system accounts from this listing that do not have a nologin shell.\n\nIf any system account (other than the root account) has a login shell and it is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Ensuring shells are not given to system accounts upon login makes it more difficult for attackers to make use of system accounts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5321","uuid":"f6d6e5d2-1498-49c5-8205-fc6ab0644bcd","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258047","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258047","title":"SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258047","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064","rule_id_src":"SV-258047r1101951_rule","rule_id":"SV-258047","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must automatically expire temporary accounts within 72 hours.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to expire temporary accounts after 72 hours with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chage -E $(date -d +3days +%Y-%m-%d) <temporary_account_name>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify temporary accounts have been provisioned with an expiration date of 72 hours.\n\nFor every existing temporary account, run the following command to obtain its account expiration information:\n\n$ sudo chage -l <temporary_account_name> | grep -i \"account expires\"\n\nVerify each of these accounts has an expiration date set within 72 hours. \n\nIf any temporary accounts have no expiration date set or do not expire within 72 hours, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Temporary accounts are privileged or nonprivileged accounts that are established during pressing circumstances, such as new software or hardware configuration or an incident response, where the need for prompt account activation requires bypassing normal account authorization procedures. If any inactive temporary accounts are left enabled on the system and are not either manually removed or automatically expired within 72 hours, the security posture of the system will be degraded and exposed to exploitation by unauthorized users or insider threat actors.\n\nTemporary accounts are different from emergency accounts. Emergency accounts, also known as \"last resort\" or \"break glass\" accounts, are local logon accounts enabled on the system for emergency use by authorized system administrators to manage a system when standard logon methods are failing or not available. Emergency accounts are not subject to manual removal or scheduled expiration requirements.\n\nThe automatic expiration of temporary accounts may be extended as needed by the circumstances but it must not be extended indefinitely. A documented permanent account should be established for privileged users who need long-term maintenance accounts.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064, SRG-OS-000002-GPOS-00002","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000016","CCI-001682"],"reference_identifier":"4984","uuid":"b98f7b53-5fbb-4563-a8bd-f006d9344b1b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2E54D744C58AF63144C9AFB4030E958D9ADD7BBD\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must automatically expire temporary accounts within 72 hours.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258048","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258048","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258048","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-258048r1069380_rule","rule_id":"SV-258048","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411045","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 interactive users must have a primary group that exists.","fix_text":"Configure the system so that all GIDs are referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" are defined in \"/etc/group\".\n\nEdit the file \"/etc/passwd\" and ensure that every user's GID is a valid GID.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all RHEL 9 interactive users have a valid GID.\n\nCheck that the interactive users have a valid GID with the following command:\n\n$ sudo pwck -r\n\nIf pwck reports \"no group\" for any interactive user, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a user is assigned the Group Identifier (GID) of a group that does not exist on the system, and a group with the GID is subsequently created, the user may have unintended rights to any files associated with the group.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"3889","uuid":"eadb9d91-8efd-4dd9-851a-2b9c3d7819a8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DC55D3A196ACE86AA6FC1B994978803FDEF37027\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All RHEL 9 interactive users must have a primary group that exists.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258049","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258049","title":"SRG-OS-000118-GPOS-00060","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258049","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000118-GPOS-00060","rule_id_src":"SV-258049r1015092_rule","rule_id":"SV-258049","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to disable account identifiers after 35 days of inactivity after the password expiration. \n\nRun the following command to change the configuration for useradd:\n\n$ sudo useradd -D -f 35\n\nThe recommendation is 35 days, but a lower value is acceptable.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) are disabled after 35 days of inactivity with the following command:\n\nCheck the account inactivity value by performing the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i inactive /etc/default/useradd\n\nINACTIVE=35\n\nIf \"INACTIVE\" is set to \"-1\", a value greater than \"35\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inactive identifiers pose a risk to systems and applications because attackers may exploit an inactive identifier and potentially obtain undetected access to the system.\n\nDisabling inactive accounts ensures that accounts which may not have been responsibly removed are not available to attackers who may have compromised their credentials.\n\nOwners of inactive accounts will not notice if unauthorized access to their user account has been obtained.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003627","CCI-003628","CCI-000795"],"reference_identifier":"9391","uuid":"0a088887-9a82-4df3-8b29-1565543b2318","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D93E21B4788826BC093865C3E85A982E1AD99B06\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258050","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258050","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258050","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258050r1045137_rule","rule_id":"SV-258050","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411055","rule_title":"Executable search paths within the initialization files of all local interactive RHEL 9 users must only contain paths that resolve to the system default or the users home directory.","fix_text":"Edit the local interactive user initialization files to change any PATH variable statements that reference directories other than their home directory.\n\nIf a local interactive user requires path variables to reference a directory owned by the application, it must be documented with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all local interactive user initialization file executable search path statements do not contain statements that will reference a working directory other than user home directories with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo find /home -maxdepth 2 -type f -name \".[^.]*\" -exec grep -iH path= {} \\;\n\nPATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$HOME/bin:$PATH\"\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files have executable search path statements that include directories outside of their home directory, and this is not documented with the ISSO as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The executable search path (typically the PATH environment variable) contains a list of directories for the shell to search to find executables. If this path includes the current working directory (other than the users home directory), executables in these directories may be executed instead of system commands.\n\nThis variable is formatted as a colon-separated list of directories. If there is an empty entry, such as a leading or trailing colon or two consecutive colons, this is interpreted as the current working directory. If deviations from the default system search path for the local interactive user are required, they must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9355","uuid":"ab7298b1-ec05-4f59-9feb-8cef26c68877","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BBA7B6183FA111160FC982BA6F4CA6A7BA206DC3\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Executable search paths within the initialization files of all local interactive RHEL 9 users must only contain paths that resolve to the system default or the users home directory.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258051","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258051","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258051","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258051r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258051","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411060","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 local interactive users must have a home directory assigned in the /etc/passwd file.","fix_text":"Create and assign home directories to all local interactive users on RHEL 9 that currently do not have a home directory assigned.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that interactive users on the system have a home directory assigned with the following command:\n \n$ sudo awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $3, $6}' /etc/passwd\n\nsmithk:x:1000:1000:smithk:/home/smithk:/bin/bash\nscsaustin:x:1001:1001:scsaustin:/home/scsaustin:/bin/bash\ndjohnson:x:1002:1002:djohnson:/home/djohnson:/bin/bash\n\nInspect the output and verify that all interactive users (normally users with a user identifier (UID) greater that 1000) have a home directory defined.\n\nIf users home directory is not defined, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If local interactive users are not assigned a valid home directory, there is no place for the storage and control of files they should own.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6782","uuid":"f82f4e4b-62a6-4255-a1f9-ec03d2d8608a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8CB380572C7FC8B81555585B614AC71FCA1523CB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All RHEL 9 local interactive users must have a home directory assigned in the /etc/passwd file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258052","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258052","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258052","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258052r1184315_rule","rule_id":"SV-258052","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411065","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 local interactive user home directories defined in the /etc/passwd file must exist.","fix_text":"Create home directories to all local interactive users that currently do not have a home directory assigned. Use the following commands to create the user home directory assigned in \"/etc/ passwd\":\n\nNote: The example will be for the user disauser, who has a home directory of \"/home/disauser\", a user identifier (UID) of \"disauser\", and a group identifier (GID) of \"users assigned\" in \"/etc/passwd\".\n\n$ sudo mkdir /home/disauser \n$ sudo chown disauser /home/disauser\n$ sudo chgrp users /home/disauser\n$ sudo chmod 0750 /home/disauser","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the assigned home directories of all interactive users on the system exist with the following command:\n\n$ sudo pwck -r \n\nThe output should not return any interactive (human) users.\n\nAsk the system administrator (SA) if any users found without home directories are local interactive users. \nIf the SA is unable to provide a response, check for users with a user identifier (UID) of 1000 or greater with the following command:\n\n$ awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($1!=\"nobody\"){print $1 \":\" $3}' /etc/passwd\n\nIf any interactive users do not have a home directory assigned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a local interactive user has a home directory defined that does not exist, the user may be given access to the / directory as the current working directory upon logon. This could create a denial of service because the user would not be able to access their logon configuration files, and it may give them visibility to system files they normally would not be able to access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6938","uuid":"623ae6ae-ec8d-4caa-85d7-1d3fe4104c6c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A20A9545B8A057897E3C9D0AC13C0120BFF3223A\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'All RHEL 9 local interactive user home directories defined in the /etc/passwd file must exist.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258053","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258053","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258053","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258053r1184318_rule","rule_id":"SV-258053","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411070","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 local interactive user home directories must be group-owned by the home directory owner's primary group.","fix_text":"Change the group owner of a local interactive user's home directory to the group found in \"/etc/passwd\". To change the group owner of a local interactive user's home directory, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"disauser\", who has a home directory of \"/home/disauser\", and has a primary group of users.\n\n$ sudo chgrp users /home/disauser","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the assigned home directory of all local interactive users is group-owned by that user's primary GID with the following command:\n\nNote: This may miss local interactive users that have been assigned a privileged user identifier (UID). Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information. The returned directory \"/home/disauser\" is used as an example.\n\n$ sudo ls -ld $(awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $6}' /etc/passwd)\n\ndrwxr-x--- 2 disauser admin 4096 Jun 5 12:41 disauser\n\nCheck the user's primary group with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep $(grep disauser /etc/passwd | awk -F: \u2018{print $4}') /etc/group\n\nadmin:x:250:disauser,doduser,nsauser\n\nIf the user home directory referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" is not group-owned by that user's primary GID, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the Group Identifier (GID) of a local interactive users home directory is not the same as the primary GID of the user, this would allow unauthorized access to the users files, and users that share the same group may not be able to access files that they legitimately should.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9408","uuid":"23c6d094-6ac5-4289-8650-8ef28bf6e4cb","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CEB4754D54454CE7230CB2C27F1D001E42603FC1\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'All RHEL 9 local interactive user home directories must be group-owned by the home directory owner's primary group.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258054","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258054","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258054","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-258054r958736_rule","rule_id":"SV-258054","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411075","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\ndeny = 3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to lock an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts with the command:\n\n$ grep 'deny =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\ndeny = 3\n\nIf the \"deny\" option is not set to \"3\" or less (but not \"0\"), is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"2723","uuid":"7445c879-66ed-418a-9723-0dee1e6c7599","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6503CC3AFCAB9D45903A5E5BFEBB44D7BC478D65\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258055","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258055","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258055","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-258055r1045140_rule","rule_id":"SV-258055","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411080","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must automatically lock the root account until the root account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.","fix_text":"To configure RHEL 9 to lock out the \"root\" account after a number of incorrect logon attempts using \"pam_faillock.so\", first enable the feature using the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock  \n\nEdit the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" by uncommenting or adding the following line:\n \neven_deny_root","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to lock the root account after three unsuccessful logon attempts with the command:\n\n$ sudo grep even_deny_root /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\neven_deny_root\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" option is not set or is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, also known as brute-forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"1764","uuid":"967747e4-d891-41b6-b161-74721f19dd8b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CEC7FC02D6823471CC695E649FB99BE43463062F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must automatically lock the root account until the root account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258056","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258056","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258056","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-258056r1045143_rule","rule_id":"SV-258056","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411085","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.","fix_text":"To configure RHEL 9 to lock out the \"root\" account after a number of incorrect logon attempts within 15 minutes using \"pam_faillock.so\", enable the feature using the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock  \n\nThen edit the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file as follows:\n\nfail_interval = 900","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator demonstrates the use of an approved centralized account management method that locks an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 locks an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep fail_interval /etc/security/faillock.conf \n\nfail_interval = 900\n\nIf the \"fail_interval\" option is not set to \"900\" or less (but not \"0\"), the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"9756","uuid":"51ce299a-315a-4e55-bbe8-d04692a1586c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3FFA9D60E6653692CACC2B65078BB66FAC9000F7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258057","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258057","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258057","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-258057r1045146_rule","rule_id":"SV-258057","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411090","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must maintain an account lock until the locked account is released by an administrator.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to lock an account until released by an administrator after three unsuccessful logon attempts with the command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock  \n\nEdit the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file as follows:\n\nunlock_time = 0","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to lock an account until released by an administrator after three unsuccessful logon attempts with the command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w unlock_time /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nunlock_time = 0\n\nIf the \"unlock_time\" option is not set to \"0\" or the line is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"5111","uuid":"c95425e1-ba2a-4f96-91bf-c278aa007e6e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B1B4CCE0E94615265DE16D07D08E15ED20C5DB7B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must maintain an account lock until the locked account is released by an administrator.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258058","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258058","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258058","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258058r1045148_rule","rule_id":"SV-258058","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411095","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not have unauthorized accounts.","fix_text":"Remove unauthorized local interactive user accounts with the following command where <unauthorized_user> is the unauthorized account:\n\n$ sudo userdel  <unauthorized_user>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that there are no unauthorized interactive user accounts with the following command:\n\n$ less /etc/passwd  \n\nroot:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n...\ngames:x:12:100:games:/usr/games:/sbin/nologin\nscsaustin:x:1001:1001:scsaustin:/home/scsaustin:/bin/bash\ndjohnson:x:1002:1002:djohnson:/home/djohnson:/bin/bash\n\nInteractive user accounts generally will have a user identifier (UID) of 1000 or greater, a home directory in a specific partition, and an interactive shell.\n\nObtain the list of interactive user accounts authorized to be on the system from the system administrator or information system security officer (ISSO) and compare it to the list of local interactive user accounts on the system.\n\nIf there are unauthorized local user accounts on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Accounts providing no operational purpose provide additional opportunities for system compromise. Unnecessary accounts include user accounts for individuals not requiring access to the system and application accounts for applications not installed on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1346","uuid":"a1834cb8-de1a-4fb3-b1b5-eed7819b4093","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C63ABB18C4E5AEFEAE72A0D2D70388756A39FB1E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must not have unauthorized accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258059","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258059","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258059","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258059r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258059","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411100","rule_title":"The root account must be the only account having unrestricted access to RHEL 9 system.","fix_text":"Change the UID of any account on the system, other than root, that has a UID of \"0\". \n\nIf the account is associated with system commands or applications, the UID should be changed to one greater than \"0\" but less than \"1000\". Otherwise, assign a UID of greater than \"1000\" that has not already been assigned.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that only the \"root\" account has a UID \"0\" assignment with the following command:\n\n$ awk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd\n\nroot\n\nIf any accounts other than \"root\" have a UID of \"0\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An account has root authority if it has a user identifier (UID) of \"0\". Multiple accounts with a UID of \"0\" afford more opportunity for potential intruders to guess a password for a privileged account. Proper configuration of sudo is recommended to afford multiple system administrators access to root privileges in an accountable manner.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8556","uuid":"96cece75-dd10-4d81-9b32-8940cac7e5ff","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 205217E8CB7B9BF4F315F478D8DFA310929377A7\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The root account must be the only account having unrestricted access to RHEL 9 system.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258060","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258060","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258060","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-258060r1045150_rule","rule_id":"SV-258060","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411105","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must ensure account lockouts persist.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 maintain the contents of the faillock directory after a reboot.\n\nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\ndir = /var/log/faillock","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to use a nondefault faillock directory to ensure contents persist after reboot with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w dir /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\ndir = /var/log/faillock\n\nIf the \"dir\" option is not set to a nondefault documented tally log directory or is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Having lockouts persist across reboots ensures that account is only unlocked by an administrator. If the lockouts did not persist across reboots, an attacker could simply reboot the system to continue brute force attacks against the accounts on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"2124","uuid":"588e87fb-f4ee-4e03-9eb9-d6f36c2bf5ad","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0C67D62BF2F4C962FB8D66ACD91839063E2A3DB3\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must ensure account lockouts persist.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258061","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258061","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258061","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-258061r958482_rule","rule_id":"SV-258061","rule_version":"RHEL-09-411110","rule_title":"RHEL 9 groups must have unique Group ID (GID).","fix_text":"Edit the file \"/etc/group\" and provide each group that has a duplicate GID with a unique GID.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 contains no duplicate GIDs for interactive users with the following command:\n \n $  cut -d : -f 3 /etc/group | uniq -d\n \nIf the system has duplicate GIDs, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, groups must be identified uniquely to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"9730","uuid":"f4048409-f98e-435c-a927-2cae9eb9b30e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2F9A77943CC92438AE28E0D1A25042E9583A486E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 groups must have unique Group ID (GID).' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258068","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258068","title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258068","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","rule_id_src":"SV-258068r1101950_rule","rule_id":"SV-258068","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must automatically exit interactive command shell user sessions after 10 minutes of inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to exit interactive command shell user sessions after 10 minutes of inactivity.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in \"/etc/profile.d/tmout.sh\":\n\n#!/bin/bash\n\ndeclare -xr TMOUT=600","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to exit interactive command shell user sessions after 10 minutes of inactivity or less with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i tmout /etc/profile /etc/profile.d/*.sh\n\n/etc/profile.d/tmout.sh:declare -xr TMOUT=600\n\nIf \"TMOUT\" is not set to \"600\" or less in a script located in the \"/etc/'profile.d/ directory, is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Terminating an idle interactive command shell user session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of it when left unattended in a virtual terminal or physical console.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072, SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000057","CCI-001133"],"reference_identifier":"2999","uuid":"c076634a-4e23-4ce7-855c-6ef544e9003e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6E40C9FDF3A895B6150A683004FE2CD6EC4C8234\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must automatically exit interactive command shell user sessions after 10 minutes of inactivity.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258069","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258069","title":"SRG-OS-000027-GPOS-00008","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258069","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000027-GPOS-00008","rule_id_src":"SV-258069r958398_rule","rule_id":"SV-258069","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must limit the number of concurrent sessions to ten for all accounts and/or account types.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to limit the number of concurrent sessions to \"10\" for all accounts and/or account types.\n\nAdd the following line to the top of the /etc/security/limits.conf or in a \".conf\" file defined in /etc/security/limits.d/:\n\n* hard maxlogins 10","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 limits the number of concurrent sessions to \"10\" for all accounts and/or account types with the following command:\n\n$ grep -r -s maxlogins /etc/security/limits.conf /etc/security/limits.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/limits.conf:* hard maxlogins 10\n\nThis can be set as a global domain (with the * wildcard) but may be set differently for multiple domains.\n\nIf the \"maxlogins\" item is missing, commented out, or the value is set greater than \"10\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement for all domains that have the \"maxlogins\" item assigned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Operating system management includes the ability to control the number of users and user sessions that utilize an operating system. Limiting the number of allowed users and sessions per user is helpful in reducing the risks related to denial-of-service (DoS) attacks.\n\nThis requirement addresses concurrent sessions for information system accounts and does not address concurrent sessions by single users via multiple system accounts. The maximum number of concurrent sessions must be defined based on mission needs and the operational environment for each system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000054"],"reference_identifier":"4170","uuid":"6aed08a6-4737-456b-81e4-e7880dfb2830","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 48E6DD2F81FD07E23AE897FD6A6F75DE310F331F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must limit the number of concurrent sessions to ten for all accounts and/or account types.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258070","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258070","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258070","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-258070r1045153_rule","rule_id":"SV-258070","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nEnable the feature using the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock \n \nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\naudit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep audit /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\naudit\n\nIf the \"audit\" option is not set, is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without auditing of these events, it may be harder or impossible to identify what an attacker did after an attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"9119","uuid":"d83a2596-10f9-42f8-b876-8e6ca9193dee","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5B3AFD2B0844E75B66B60696E612E0CA90AA6367\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258071","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258071","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00226","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258071","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00226","rule_id_src":"SV-258071r991588_rule","rule_id":"SV-258071","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.","fix_text":"Configure the RHEL 9 to enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed console logon attempt.\n\nModify the \"/etc/login.defs\" file to set the \"FAIL_DELAY\" parameter to 4 or greater:\n\nFAIL_DELAY 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 enforces a delay of at least four seconds between console logon prompts following a failed logon attempt with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i fail_delay /etc/login.defs\n\nFAIL_DELAY 4\n\nIf the value of \"FAIL_DELAY\" is not set to \"4\" or greater, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Increasing the time between a failed authentication attempt and reprompting to enter credentials helps to slow a single-threaded brute force attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8074","uuid":"dc66c18c-93d0-41d9-8926-e365dc3103d6","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0C25711F8748C86447B3BDA6395EC584B2B1301B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258072","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258072","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258072","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","rule_id_src":"SV-258072r1184320_rule","rule_id":"SV-258072","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412055","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must define default permissions for the bash shell.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to define default permissions for all authenticated users using the bash shell.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/bashrc\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"umask\" setting is configured correctly in the \"/etc/bashrc\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/bashrc\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ grep umask /etc/bashrc \n\n[ `umask` -eq 0 ] && umask 077  \n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7781","uuid":"3217b3ae-549c-4f63-9cdb-004680e4cfc4","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AD1A4CDB0C34EFA7A40B51D193802C025E656557\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must define default permissions for the bash shell.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258073","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258073","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258073","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","rule_id_src":"SV-258073r1184322_rule","rule_id":"SV-258073","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must define default permissions for the c shell.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to define default permissions for all authenticated users using the c shell.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"umask\" setting is configured correctly in the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ grep umask /etc/csh.cshrc \n\numask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8732","uuid":"1f7ce63c-3906-4c07-9add-610d125c83ae","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E223952A5631B5BB4347D37FA51B0C520EEDD465\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must define default permissions for the c shell.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258074","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258074","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258074","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","rule_id_src":"SV-258074r991590_rule","rule_id":"SV-258074","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412065","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"UMASK\" parameter in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file to \"077\":\n\nUMASK 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 defines default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter is set to \"000\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n# grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\n\nUMASK 077\n\nIf the value for the \"UMASK\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"UMASK\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Setting the most restrictive default permissions ensures that when new accounts are created, they do not have unnecessary access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3249","uuid":"96c6ed5a-7e31-4f40-a49b-87f9dab66a1d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5E2F6236672FB9AD4E17E512C8715EABEFFE2D92\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258075","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258075","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258075","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","rule_id_src":"SV-258075r1184324_rule","rule_id":"SV-258075","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412070","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must define default permissions for the system default profile.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/profile\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"umask\" setting is configured correctly in the \"/etc/profile\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/profile\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ grep umask /etc/profile \n\numask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8588","uuid":"a6e61102-ab3d-4758-8b46-dd3c74faed12","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CB4975635310D29E6B1BE30AEEB975C97C2E0D99\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must define default permissions for the system default profile.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258077","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258077","title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258077","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","rule_id_src":"SV-258077r1155659_rule","rule_id":"SV-258077","rule_version":"RHEL-09-412080","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must terminate idle user sessions.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to log out idle sessions.\n\nCreate the directory if necessary:\n\n$ mkdir -p /etc/systemd/logind.conf.d/\n\nCreate a *.conf file in /etc/systemd/logind.conf.d/ with the following content:\n\n[Login]\nStopIdleSessionSec=600\nKillUserProcesses=no\n\nRestart systemd-logind:\n\n$ systemctl restart systemd-logind","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 logs out sessions that are idle for 10 minutes with the following command:\n\n$ systemd-analyze cat-config systemd/logind.conf | grep StopIdleSessionSec\n\n#StopIdleSessionSec=infinity\nStopIdleSessionSec=600\n\nIf \"StopIdleSessionSec\" is not configured to \"600\" seconds, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Terminating an idle session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001133"],"reference_identifier":"1024","uuid":"4f8c0476-645a-4817-866f-187e04778977","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258078","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258078","title":"SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258078","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","rule_id_src":"SV-258078r958944_rule","rule_id":"SV-258078","rule_version":"RHEL-09-431010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use a Linux Security Module configured to enforce limits on system services.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to verify correct operation of security functions.\n\nEdit the file \"/etc/selinux/config\" and add or modify the following line:\n\n SELINUX=enforcing \n\nA reboot is required for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Ensure that RHEL 9 verifies correct operation of security functions through the use of SELinux with the following command:\n\n$ getenforce\n\nEnforcing\n\nIf SELINUX is not set to \"Enforcing\", this is a finding.\n\nVerify that SELinux is configured to be enforcing at boot.\n\ngrep \"SELINUX=\" /etc/selinux/config\n# SELINUX= can take one of these three values:\n# NOTE: In earlier Fedora kernel builds, SELINUX=disabled would also\nSELINUX=enforcing\n\nIf SELINUX line is missing, commented out, or not set to \"enforcing\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nThis requirement applies to operating systems performing security function verification/testing and/or systems and environments that require this functionality.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199, SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001084","CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"4497","uuid":"d8086b32-e611-42f2-8b23-7cf5d7aea6b1","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D45B278DCA060F73B45DECB500B5434A0C58A354\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must use a Linux Security Module configured to enforce limits on system services.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258079","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258079","title":"SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258079","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","rule_id_src":"SV-258079r1045159_rule","rule_id":"SV-258079","rule_version":"RHEL-09-431015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enable the SELinux targeted policy.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use the targetd SELINUX policy.\n\nEdit the file \"/etc/selinux/config\" and add or modify the following line:\n\n SELINUXTYPE=targeted \n\nA reboot is required for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the SELINUX on RHEL 9 is using the targeted policy with the following command:\n\n$ sestatus | grep \"policy name\" \n\nLoaded policy name:             targeted\n\nIf the loaded policy name is not \"targeted\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Setting the SELinux policy to \"targeted\" or a more specialized policy ensures the system will confine processes that are likely to be targeted for exploitation, such as network or system services.\n\nNote: During the development or debugging of SELinux modules, it is common to temporarily place nonproduction systems in \"permissive\" mode. In such temporary cases, SELinux policies should be developed, and once work is completed, the system should be reconfigured to \"targeted\".","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"8958","uuid":"47985659-c6a1-4a04-a43e-8ffd23549042","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 37B06B9617F00FBE7F94201DB4FCFCEBD60A1247\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enable the SELinux targeted policy.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258080","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258080","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258080","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-258080r1045162_rule","rule_id":"SV-258080","rule_version":"RHEL-09-431020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must configure SELinux context type to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory while SELinux enforces a targeted policy. \n\nFirst enable the feature using the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock \n \nCreate a nondefault faillock tally directory (if it does not already exist) with the following example:\n\n$ sudo mkdir /var/log/faillock\n\nThen add/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n \ndir = /var/log/faillock\n\nUpdate the /etc/selinux/targeted/contexts/files/file_contexts.local with \"faillog_t\" context type for the nondefault faillock tally directory with the following command:\n\n$ sudo semanage fcontext -a -t faillog_t \"/var/log/faillock(/.*)?\"\n\nNext, update the context type of the nondefault faillock directory/subdirectories and files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo restorecon -R -v /var/log/faillock","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the location of the nondefault tally directory for the pam_faillock module with the following command:\n\nNote: If the system does not have SELinux enabled and enforcing a targeted policy, or if the pam_faillock module is not configured for use, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep -w dir /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\ndir = /var/log/faillock\n\nCheck the security context type of the nondefault tally directory with the following command:\n\n$ ls -Zd /var/log/faillock\n\nunconfined_u:object_r:faillog_t:s0 /var/log/faillock\n\nIf the security context type of the nondefault tally directory is not \"faillog_t\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Not having the correct SELinux context on the faillock directory may lead to unauthorized access to the directory.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"9062","uuid":"132ebcd4-4243-4a0c-9a58-1032ff05613b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E3A070FECC6CFDA559FFE13C07FFB44C335A7669\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must configure SELinux context type to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258081","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258081","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258081","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258081r1045164_rule","rule_id":"SV-258081","rule_version":"RHEL-09-431025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have policycoreutils package installed.","fix_text":"The policycoreutils package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install policycoreutils","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 has the policycoreutils package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed policycoreutils\n\nExample output:\n\npolicycoreutils.x86_64          3.3-6.el9_0                                                 \n\nIf the \"policycoreutils\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nPolicycoreutils contains the policy core utilities that are required for basic operation of an SELinux-enabled system. These utilities include load_policy to load SELinux policies, setfile to label filesystems, newrole to switch roles, and run_init to run /etc/init.d scripts in the proper context.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001084"],"reference_identifier":"2790","uuid":"34a20563-b8b6-42d8-92ba-64c6d7901493","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D0CB5B9E4871724C2334C84ACF380FC816C4CFB6\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must have policycoreutils package installed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258082","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258082","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258082","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258082r1045166_rule","rule_id":"SV-258082","rule_version":"RHEL-09-431030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 policycoreutils-python-utils package must be installed.","fix_text":"Install the policycoreutils-python-utils service package (if the policycoreutils-python-utils service is not already installed) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf install policycoreutils-python-utils","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 policycoreutils-python-utils service package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed policycoreutils-python-utils\n\nExample output:\n\npolicycoreutils-python-utils.noarch          3.3-6.el9_0\n\nIf the \"policycoreutils-python-utils\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The policycoreutils-python-utils package is required to operate and manage an SELinux environment and its policies. It provides utilities such as semanage, audit2allow, audit2why, chcat, and sandbox.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7402","uuid":"376ee37c-d8ac-4370-ae67-af8a3470423e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E136FE0FB463BE166F4EC55B85595D78A2BF57F8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 policycoreutils-python-utils package must be installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258083","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258083","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258083","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","rule_id_src":"SV-258083r1045168_rule","rule_id":"SV-258083","rule_version":"RHEL-09-432010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the sudo package installed.","fix_text":"The  sudo  package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install sudo","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 sudo package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed sudo\n\nExample output:\n\nsudo.x86_64          1.9.5p2-7.el9\n\nIf the \"sudo\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"\"sudo\" is a program designed to allow a system administrator to give limited root privileges to users and log root activity. The basic philosophy is to give as few privileges as possible but still allow system users to get their work done.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"4585","uuid":"00c6353f-fa9d-4a63-92a7-f0bb089c8e7b","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BF89F07729D0A1F6401A5B30865A10695E445346\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must have the sudo package installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258084","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258084","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258084","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","rule_id_src":"SV-258084r1050789_rule","rule_id":"SV-258084","rule_version":"RHEL-09-432015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require reauthentication when using the \"sudo\" command.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to reauthenticate \"sudo\" commands after the specified timeout:\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/sudoers\" or a file in \"/etc/sudoers.d\":\n\nDefaults timestamp_timeout=0","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 requires reauthentication when using the \"sudo\" command to elevate privileges with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -ir 'timestamp_timeout' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/\n\n/etc/sudoers:Defaults timestamp_timeout=0\n\nIf results are returned from more than one file location, this is a finding.\n\nIf \"timestamp_timeout\" is set to a negative number, is commented out, or no results are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without reauthentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization. \n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the organization requires the user to reauthenticate when using the \"sudo\" command.\n\nIf the value is set to an integer less than \"0\", the user's time stamp will not expire and the user will not have to reauthenticate for privileged actions until the user's session is terminated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004895","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"1350","uuid":"a7d2e0be-6e40-4eea-bdb2-2f37362e1188","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3E273C83B6289661B70926716E7ABA68822A108B\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must require reauthentication when using the \"sudo\" command.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258085","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258085","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258085","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258085r1045173_rule","rule_id":"SV-258085","rule_version":"RHEL-09-432020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use the invoking user's password for privilege escalation when using \"sudo\".","fix_text":"Define the following in the Defaults section of the /etc/sudoers file or a single configuration file in the /etc/sudoers.d/ directory:\n\nDefaults !targetpw\nDefaults !rootpw\nDefaults !runaspw","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the sudoers security policy is configured to use the invoking user's password for privilege escalation with the following command:\n\n$ sudo egrep -ir '(!rootpw|!targetpw|!runaspw)' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/ | grep -v '#'\n\n/etc/sudoers:Defaults !targetpw\n/etc/sudoers:Defaults !rootpw\n/etc/sudoers:Defaults !runaspw\n\nIf no results are returned, this is a finding.\n\nIf results are returned from more than one file location, this is a finding.\n\nIf \"Defaults !targetpw\" is not defined, this is a finding.\n\nIf \"Defaults !rootpw\" is not defined, this is a finding.\n\nIf \"Defaults !runaspw\" is not defined, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the rootpw, targetpw, or runaspw flags are defined and not disabled, by default the operating system will prompt the invoking user for the \"root\" user password.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5082","uuid":"71af7ce3-0e86-496a-91ef-ff4aecc43285","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258086","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258086","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258086","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","rule_id_src":"SV-258086r1102063_rule","rule_id":"SV-258086","rule_version":"RHEL-09-432025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require users to reauthenticate for privilege escalation.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not allow users to execute privileged actions without authenticating.\n\nRemove any occurrence of \"!authenticate\" found in \"/etc/sudoers\" file or files in the \"/etc/sudoers.d\" directory.\n\n$ sudo sed -i '/\\!authenticate/ s/^/# /g' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/*","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"/etc/sudoers\" has no occurrences of \"!authenticate\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo egrep -iR '!authenticate' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/\n\nIf any occurrences of \"!authenticate\" are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without reauthentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization.\n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical that the user reauthenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004895","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"9243","uuid":"d5447b84-1c41-4499-bdbf-d7bdc870b428","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 55510709D9B1C1172BE326542CDA90D0486B55E5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require users to reauthenticate for privilege escalation.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258087","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258087","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258087","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258087r1102071_rule","rule_id":"SV-258087","rule_version":"RHEL-09-432030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must restrict privilege elevation to authorized personnel.","fix_text":"Remove the following entries from the /etc/sudoers file or configuration file under /etc/sudoers.d/:\n\nALL     ALL=(ALL) ALL\nALL     ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 restricts privilege elevation to authorized personnel with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iwR 'ALL' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/ | grep -v '#'\n\nIf the either of the following entries are returned, this is a finding:\nALL     ALL=(ALL) ALL\nALL     ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the \"sudoers\" file is not configured correctly, any user defined on the system can initiate privileged actions on the target system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1316","uuid":"16c0a2f4-2117-4ce8-83f8-00b0077151d9","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3101D77AA5E6A467A6B7B5C05B9F5B1EAD2D2BE4\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must restrict privilege elevation to authorized personnel.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258088","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258088","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258088","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","rule_id_src":"SV-258088r1155643_rule","rule_id":"SV-258088","rule_version":"RHEL-09-432035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must restrict the use of the \"su\" command.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require users to be in the \"wheel\" group to run \"su\" command.\n\nIn file \"/etc/pam.d/su\", uncomment the following line:\n\n\"#auth    required    pam_wheel.so use_uid\"\n\n$ sed '/^[[:space:]]*#[[:space:]]*auth[[:space:]]\\+required[[:space:]]\\+pam_wheel\\.so[[:space:]]\\+use_uid$/s/^[[:space:]]*#//' -i /etc/pam.d/su\n\nIf necessary, create a \"wheel\" group and add administrative users to the group.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 includes users who require privilege escalation to be members of the \"wheel\" group with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep pam_wheel /etc/pam.d/su \n\nauth             required        pam_wheel.so use_uid \n\nIf a line for \"pam_wheel.so\" does not exist, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"su\" program allows to run commands with a substitute user and group ID. It is commonly used to run commands as the root user. Limiting access to such commands is considered a good security practice.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000312-GPOS-00123","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004895","CCI-002165","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"2406","uuid":"b1736372-05d9-4adf-8c6f-b4caf8bb5d1d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E0EF1E0893D0CC9346626C65C2B9F66AF231F62E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must restrict the use of the \"su\" command.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258089","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258089","title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258089","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","rule_id_src":"SV-258089r1045179_rule","rule_id":"SV-258089","rule_version":"RHEL-09-433010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 fapolicy module must be installed.","fix_text":"The  fapolicyd  package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install fapolicyd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 fapolicyd package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed fapolicyd\n\nExample output:\n\nfapolicyd.x86_64          1.1-103.el9_0\n\nIf the \"fapolicyd\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as allow listing.\n\nUtilizing an allow list provides a configuration management method for allowing the execution of only authorized software. Using only authorized software decreases risk by limiting the number of potential vulnerabilities. Verification of allow listed software occurs prior to execution or at system startup.\n\nUser home directories/folders may contain information of a sensitive nature. Nonprivileged users should coordinate any sharing of information with an SA through shared resources.\n\nRHEL 9 ships with many optional packages. One such package is a file access policy daemon called \"fapolicyd\". \"fapolicyd\" is a userspace daemon that determines access rights to files based on attributes of the process and file. It can be used to either blocklist or allow list processes or file access.\n\nProceed with caution with enforcing the use of this daemon. Improper configuration may render the system nonfunctional. The \"fapolicyd\" API is not namespace aware and can cause issues when launching or running containers.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155, SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764","CCI-001774"],"reference_identifier":"6637","uuid":"1480c856-4af0-4fd2-a6aa-3d309dfbc0cc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 094D381FB233345610A64D457EADB690B8CEF801\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 fapolicy module must be installed.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258090","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258090","title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258090","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155","rule_id_src":"SV-258090r958808_rule","rule_id":"SV-258090","rule_version":"RHEL-09-433015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 fapolicy module must be enabled.","fix_text":"Enable the fapolicyd with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl enable --now fapolicyd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 fapolicyd is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active fapolicyd\n\nactive\n\nIf fapolicyd module is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as allowlisting.\n\nUtilizing an allowlist provides a configuration management method for allowing the execution of only authorized software. Using only authorized software decreases risk by limiting the number of potential vulnerabilities. Verification of allowlisted software occurs prior to execution or at system startup.\n\nUser home directories/folders may contain information of a sensitive nature. Nonprivileged users should coordinate any sharing of information with an SA through shared resources.\n\nRHEL 9 ships with many optional packages. One such package is a file access policy daemon called \"fapolicyd\". \"fapolicyd\" is a userspace daemon that determines access rights to files based on attributes of the process and file. It can be used to either blocklist or allowlist processes or file access.\n\nProceed with caution with enforcing the use of this daemon. Improper configuration may render the system nonfunctional. The \"fapolicyd\" API is not namespace aware and can cause issues when launching or running containers.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155, SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764","CCI-001774"],"reference_identifier":"2746","uuid":"444c7ddb-2083-4a02-8369-a53a05cd400f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E12DB51849F9D96A098582C8D5ED8676E9468274\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 fapolicy module must be enabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258091","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258091","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258091","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","rule_id_src":"SV-258091r1045185_rule","rule_id":"SV-258091","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must ensure the password complexity module in the system-auth file is configured for three retries or less.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to limit the \"pwquality\" retry option to \"3\".\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"retry\" parameter:\n \nretry = 3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to limit the \"pwquality\" retry option to \"3\".\n\nCheck for the use of the retry option in the security directory with the following command:\n\n$ grep -w retry /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n \nretry = 3\n \nIf the value of \"retry\" is set to \"0\" or greater than \"3\", or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \"pwquality\" enforces complex password construction configuration and has the ability to limit brute-force attacks on the system.\n\nRHEL 9 uses \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. This is set in both:\n/etc/pam.d/password-auth\n/etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nBy limiting the number of attempts to meet the pwquality module complexity requirements before returning with an error, the system will audit abnormal attempts at password changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000192"],"reference_identifier":"6626","uuid":"204b8125-b36a-460c-9f41-43cee5dfbe99","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 187B0EF0FD81B06730CDFF3562A8A902A0CB81EF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must ensure the password complexity module in the system-auth file is configured for three retries or less.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258094","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258094","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258094","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258094r1045187_rule","rule_id":"SV-258094","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not allow blank or null passwords.","fix_text":"If PAM is managed with authselect, use the following command to remove instances of \"nullok\":\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature without-nullok\n\nOtherwise, remove any instances of the \"nullok\" option in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" files to prevent logons with empty passwords.\n\nNote: Manual changes to the listed file may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that null passwords cannot be used with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/system-auth /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nIf output is produced, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system administrator (SA) can demonstrate that the required configuration is contained in a PAM configuration file included or substacked from the system-auth file, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account has an empty password, anyone could log in and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8329","uuid":"bb69f2dc-85e4-4f00-a6f5-88c353ac2ed8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CBA51EE1462B9CDD68B53AF4BF332C1297C1D14F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not allow blank or null passwords.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258095","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258095","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258095","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-258095r1045189_rule","rule_id":"SV-258095","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to include the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file. \n\nIf PAM is managed with authselect, enable the feature with the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock\n \nOtherwise, add/modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file to match the following lines:\nNote: The \"preauth\" line must be listed before pam_unix.so.\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the pam_faillock.so module is present in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file:\n\n$ grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the pam_faillock.so module is not present in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file with the \"preauth\" line listed before pam_unix.so, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system administrator (SA) can demonstrate that the required configuration is contained in a PAM configuration file included or substacked from the system-auth file, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the pam_faillock.so module is not loaded, the system will not correctly lockout accounts to prevent password guessing attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"3217","uuid":"d9d8b842-4494-4f16-97fd-bb655c895b06","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DBB637E39115BC48D66CF95B2ABC505C32F5D31D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258096","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258096","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258096","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-258096r1045191_rule","rule_id":"SV-258096","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to include the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file. If PAM is managed with authselect, enable the feature with the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock\n\nOtherwise, add/modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file to match the following lines:\nNote: The \"preauth\" line must be listed before pam_unix.so.\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the pam_faillock.so module is present in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file:\n\n$ grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the pam_faillock.so module is not present in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file with the \"preauth\" line listed before pam_unix.so, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system administrator (SA) can demonstrate that the required configuration is contained in a PAM configuration file included or substacked from the system-auth file, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the pam_faillock.so module is not loaded, the system will not correctly lockout accounts to prevent password guessing attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"1519","uuid":"a2d6a318-9d2a-424b-a10f-404fd846e3fb","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F1270D408AD06B24418B42DFEDFDA17850B3606B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258097","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258097","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258097","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","rule_id_src":"SV-258097r1045193_rule","rule_id":"SV-258097","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the password-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use \"pwquality\" to enforce password complexity rules.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 uses \"pwquality\" to enforce the password complexity rules in the password-auth file with the following command:\n\n$ grep pam_pwquality /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so \n\nIf the command does not return a line containing the value \"pam_pwquality.so\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system administrator (SA) can demonstrate that the required configuration is contained in a PAM configuration file included or substacked from the system-auth file, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling PAM password complexity permits enforcement of strong passwords and consequently makes the system less prone to dictionary attacks.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037, SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000192","CCI-000193"],"reference_identifier":"1436","uuid":"99a3694e-0d77-4c13-800a-fcf3923fa9ae","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C3FF79B1335C47A0710009FD062CF8FE4419F479\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the password-auth file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258098","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258098","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258098","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258098r1045195_rule","rule_id":"SV-258098","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the system-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use \"pwquality\" to enforce password complexity rules.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file(or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 uses \"pwquality\" to enforce the password complexity rules in the system-auth file with the following command:\n\n$ grep pam_pwquality /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so \n\nIf the command does not return a line containing the value \"pam_pwquality.so\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system administrator (SA) can demonstrate that the required configuration is contained in a PAM configuration file included or substacked from the system-auth file, this is not a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling PAM password complexity permits enforcement of strong passwords and consequently makes the system less prone to dictionary attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4654","uuid":"8f0c4a6e-53ad-4e6d-8676-1bd5aae927a5","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 93668D0FB3CF6F459FFC1DE6DBA03B4830D8C0AF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the system-auth file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258099","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258099","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258099","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-258099r1045198_rule","rule_id":"SV-258099","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 password-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use 100000 hashing rounds for hashing passwords.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" and set \"rounds\" to \"100000\".\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000\n\nNote: Running authselect will overwrite this value unless a custom authselect policy is created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the number of rounds for the password hashing algorithm is configured with the following command:\n\n$ grep rounds /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000\n\nIf a matching line is not returned or \"rounds\" is less than \"100000\", this a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nUsing more hashing rounds makes password cracking attacks more difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000803","CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"4006","uuid":"a66f07e0-1a4b-4871-8c75-77057a6702bf","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DEB468DEB7F0A8388097BCE690CC35343754E43C\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 password-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258100","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258100","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258100","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-258100r1045201_rule","rule_id":"SV-258100","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611055","rule_title":"RHEL 9 system-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use 100000 hashing rounds for hashing passwords.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and set \"rounds\" to 100000.\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000\n\nNote: Running authselect will overwrite this value unless a custom authselect policy is created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the number of rounds for the password hashing algorithm is configured with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep rounds /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000\n\nIf a matching line is not returned or \"rounds\" is less than 100000, this a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nUsing more hashing rounds makes password cracking attacks more difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000803","CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"9438","uuid":"55aa68c2-8fb0-402a-8ce2-1aa034486b49","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F4118696743FD68E8DF8C1A1BFCEFBD1224A15E8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 system-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258101","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258101","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258101","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-258101r1045204_rule","rule_id":"SV-258101","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity rules for the root account.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce password complexity on the root account.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"enforce_for_root\" parameter:\n\nenforce_for_root","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces password complexity rules for the root account.\n\nCheck if root user is required to use complex passwords with the following command:\n\n$ grep enforce_for_root /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:enforce_for_root\n\nIf \"enforce_for_root\" is commented or missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040, SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039, SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038, SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101, SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225, SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000192","CCI-000193","CCI-000194","CCI-000195","CCI-000205","CCI-001619"],"reference_identifier":"8683","uuid":"8a243bca-2834-48ea-9648-2279adb3916c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AB653342F02376AD14FC79AC4ECF972C8AED91AB\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity rules for the root account.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258102","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258102","title":"SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258102","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038","rule_id_src":"SV-258102r1045207_rule","rule_id":"SV-258102","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611065","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring at least one lowercase character be used by setting the \"lcredit\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"lcredit\" parameter:\n\nlcredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one lowercase character.\n\nCheck the value for \"lcredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep lcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:lcredit = -1\n\nIf the value of \"lcredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring a minimum number of lowercase characters makes password guessing attacks more difficult by ensuring a larger search space.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000193"],"reference_identifier":"2933","uuid":"8bf03037-3f54-465f-86e4-96347d1bd828","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1E8184D9AD751123EF019C78F666338FEA801E41\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258103","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258103","title":"SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258103","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039","rule_id_src":"SV-258103r1045210_rule","rule_id":"SV-258103","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611070","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring at least one numeric character be used by setting the \"dcredit\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"dcredit\" parameter:\n\ndcredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one numeric character.\n\nCheck the value for \"dcredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep dcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:dcredit = -1\n\nIf the value of \"dcredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring digits makes password guessing attacks more difficult by ensuring a larger search space.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000194"],"reference_identifier":"8232","uuid":"0823e158-25fe-4941-a927-1d6b1ce6627f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 63EBBA91BC179EDF4ACD9F1BB3A56CF789C9E38A\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258104","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258104","title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258104","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","rule_id_src":"SV-258104r1015104_rule","rule_id":"SV-258104","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611075","rule_title":"RHEL 9 passwords for new users or password changes must have a 24 hours minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce 24 hours as the minimum password lifetime.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/login.defs\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nPASS_MIN_DAYS 1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 enforces 24 hours as the minimum password lifetime for new user accounts.\n\nCheck for the value of \"PASS_MIN_DAYS\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" with the following command: \n\n$ grep -i pass_min_days /etc/login.defs\n\nPASS_MIN_DAYS 1\n\nIf the \"PASS_MIN_DAYS\" parameter value is not \"1\" or greater, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps to prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement. If users are allowed to immediately and continually change their password, then the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.\n\nSetting the minimum password age protects against users cycling back to a favorite password after satisfying the password reuse requirement.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000198"],"reference_identifier":"5009","uuid":"d8ed39e0-a37c-4178-b31f-731b3bbd0048","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4640B69612363D36D12A6DDDE5AC19F96E019E0B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 passwords for new users or password changes must have a 24 hours minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258105","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258105","title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258105","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","rule_id_src":"SV-258105r1045212_rule","rule_id":"SV-258105","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611080","rule_title":"RHEL 9 passwords must have a 24 hours minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/shadow.","fix_text":"Configure noncompliant accounts to enforce a 24 hour minimum password lifetime:\n\n$ sudo passwd -n 1 [user]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has configured the minimum time period between password changes for each user account as one day or greater with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$4 < 1 {printf \"%s %d\\n\", $1, $4}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps to prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement. If users are allowed to immediately and continually change their password, the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000198"],"reference_identifier":"6219","uuid":"7d214bac-0bcb-4a2a-b2ab-6509611f0d72","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D6672C06FB1C183C6AE8CDE1678615FB3D462E0E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 passwords must have a 24 hours minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/shadow.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258106","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258106","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258106","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","rule_id_src":"SV-258106r1102061_rule","rule_id":"SV-258106","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611085","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require users to provide a password for privilege escalation.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not allow users to execute privileged actions without authenticating with a password.\n\nRemove any occurrence of \"NOPASSWD\" found in \"/etc/sudoers\" file or files in the \"/etc/sudoers.d\" directory.\n\n$ sudo find /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d -type f -exec sed -i '/NOPASSWD/ s/^/# /g' {} \\;","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"/etc/sudoers\" has no occurrences of \"NOPASSWD\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iR 'NOPASSWD' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/\n\nIf any occurrences of \"NOPASSWD\" are returned from the command and have not been documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an organizationally defined administrative group using multifactor authentication (MFA), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without reauthentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization.\n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical that the user reauthenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004895","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"6755","uuid":"02fbdbdc-f289-4670-81e5-3667c1f0d9f8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0333D9FA03AE240024A28B866DF9992470D6DDBC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require users to provide a password for privilege escalation.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258107","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258107","title":"SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258107","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046","rule_id_src":"SV-258107r1045218_rule","rule_id":"SV-258107","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611090","rule_title":"RHEL 9 passwords must be created with a minimum of 15 characters.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce a minimum 15-character password length.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"minlen\" parameter:\n\nminlen = 15","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces a minimum 15-character password length with the following command:\n\n$ grep minlen /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\nminlen = 15\n\nIf the command does not return a \"minlen\" value of \"15\" or greater, does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nPassword complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password length is one factor of several that helps to determine strength and how long it takes to crack a password. Use of more characters in a password helps to increase exponentially the time and/or resources required to compromise the password.\n\nRHEL 9 uses \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Configurations are set in the \"etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file.\n\nThe \"minlen\", sometimes noted as minimum length, acts as a \"score\" of complexity based on the credit components of the \"pwquality\" module. By setting the credit components to a negative value, not only will those components be required, but they will not count toward the total \"score\" of \"minlen\". This will enable \"minlen\" to require a 15-character minimum.\n\nThe DOD minimum password requirement is 15 characters.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000205"],"reference_identifier":"4283","uuid":"0f066b29-2f80-4ca0-a7e2-b2c98b6c83dc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8F038528CDC7D428BFADEEC41C31F8786E859D36\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 passwords must be created with a minimum of 15 characters.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258109","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258109","title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258109","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","rule_id_src":"SV-258109r1045220_rule","rule_id":"SV-258109","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611100","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring at least one special character be used by setting the \"ocredit\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"ocredit\" parameter:\n\nocredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one special character with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \n\nocredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"ocredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. RHEL 9 utilizes \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Note that to require special characters without degrading the \"minlen\" value, the credit value must be expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-001619"],"reference_identifier":"3018","uuid":"a831f27b-f2a3-4938-8577-0e18ec6c14db","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258110","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258110","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258110","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225","rule_id_src":"SV-258110r1045223_rule","rule_id":"SV-258110","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611105","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"dictcheck\" parameter:\n\ndictcheck=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 prevents the use of dictionary words for passwords with the following command:\n\n$ grep dictcheck /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:dictcheck = 1\n\nIf \"dictcheck\" does not have a value other than \"0\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. If RHEL 9 allows the user to select passwords based on dictionary words, this increases the chances of password compromise by increasing the opportunity for successful guesses, and brute-force attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9471","uuid":"577ac51d-6142-4029-a909-4498edab70bc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0523E44D6D5B63B640B1927918E39A9431048C82\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258111","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258111","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258111","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","rule_id_src":"SV-258111r1045226_rule","rule_id":"SV-258111","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611110","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used by setting the \"ucredit\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"ucredit\" parameter:\n\nucredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.\n\nCheck the value for \"ucredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep ucredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf  \n\nucredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"ucredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring a minimum number of uppercase characters makes password guessing attacks more difficult by ensuring a larger search space.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000192"],"reference_identifier":"1037","uuid":"f01ac6b7-f654-46d4-bb65-a9ebd0eae8b3","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 11D6FF5099F0812C54AB08D62EDE8DEE7B9B6FFB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258112","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258112","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258112","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-258112r1045229_rule","rule_id":"SV-258112","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611115","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require the change of at least eight characters when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"difok\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"difok\" parameter:\n\ndifok = 8","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 requires the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed.\n\n$ grep difok /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\ndifok = 8\n \nIf the value of \"difok\" is set to less than \"8\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring a minimum number of different characters during password changes ensures that newly changed passwords will not resemble previously compromised ones. Note that passwords changed on compromised systems will still be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"6242","uuid":"1d79813d-8890-4b83-ba7b-b6f326b6f795","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 848C6D62CD746950DC200E18BF608BCBBC9A4FA0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require the change of at least eight characters when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258113","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258113","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258113","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-258113r1045232_rule","rule_id":"SV-258113","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611120","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require the change of the number of repeating characters of the same character class when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxclassrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"maxclassrepeat\" parameter:\n\nmaxclassrepeat = 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 requires that passwords can have a maximum of four repeating characters of the same character class.\n\n$ grep maxclassrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\nmaxclassrepeat = 4\n\nIf the value of \"maxclassrepeat\" is set to \"0\", more than \"4\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex a password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"4818","uuid":"f5292421-2de4-496a-bdcf-e3ebd889688a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5C82E05CDDCD60FB33815E93A6352B65886870DD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258114","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258114","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258114","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-258114r1045235_rule","rule_id":"SV-258114","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611125","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require the change of the number of repeating consecutive characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"maxrepeat\" parameter:\n\nmaxrepeat = 3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 requires that passwords can have a maximum of three of the same consecutive character.\n\n$ grep maxrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n\nmaxrepeat = 3\n\nIf the value of \"maxrepeat\" is set to more than \"3\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex a password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"9530","uuid":"103266fc-b99c-4d81-884a-5c81a53404a2","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E06543C9D734E6E48B2062B69EBBB1AAB790F351\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258115","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258115","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258115","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-258115r1045238_rule","rule_id":"SV-258115","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611130","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed by setting the \"minclass\" option.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/\" directory to contain the \"minclass\" parameter:\n\nminclass = 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 requires passwords to contain at least four character classes.\n\n$ grep minclass /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n \nminclass = 4\n\nIf the value of \"minclass\" is set to less than \"4\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex a password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066","CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"9947","uuid":"56722249-e62e-4b5b-8702-4f34993fa776","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 295E36F81E41EFDCB155BDC9F81B6573056D2512\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258116","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258116","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258116","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-258116r1045240_rule","rule_id":"SV-258116","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611135","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use the SHA-512 algorithm for password hashing.\n\nAdd or change the following line in the \"[defaults]\" section of \"/etc/libuser.conf\" file:\n\ncrypt_style = sha512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords with the following command:\n\n$ grep crypt_style /etc/libuser.conf \n\ncrypt_style = sha512\n\nIf the \"crypt_style\" variable is not set to \"sha512\", is not in the defaults section, is commented out, or does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nThis setting ensures user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. Additionally, the \"crypt_style\" configuration option ensures the use of a strong hashing algorithm that makes password cracking attacks more difficult.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"3868","uuid":"3b54e4c2-f7c9-4108-9728-d7a7fb39d1bd","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F82E8A1E729B7B7A67DBA524C4ED15DF8625AD4C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258117","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258117","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258117","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-258117r1015116_rule","rule_id":"SV-258117","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611140","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured to use the shadow file to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to store only SHA512 encrypted representations of passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file:\n\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system's shadow file is configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords with a hash value of SHA512 with the following command:\n\n# grep -i encrypt_method /etc/login.defs\n\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\nIf \"ENCRYPT_METHOD\" does not have a value of \"SHA512\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nThis setting ensures user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. Additionally, the \"crypt_style\" configuration option ensures the use of a strong hashing algorithm that makes password cracking attacks more difficult.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"6253","uuid":"23c87065-54d3-4c31-9909-832c62bcb158","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 396E53F15329142914C7B041E5820F929BE78177\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured to use the shadow file to store only encrypted representations of passwords.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258118","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258118","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258118","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","rule_id_src":"SV-258118r1050789_rule","rule_id":"SV-258118","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611145","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not be configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require users to supply a password for privilege escalation.\n\nRemove any occurrences of \" pam_succeed_if \" in the  \"/etc/pam.d/sudo\" file.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system is not configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep pam_succeed_if /etc/pam.d/sudo \n\nIf any occurrences of \"pam_succeed_if\" are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without reauthentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization. When operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the user reauthenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004895","CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"6093","uuid":"5fdfe49c-b26c-461e-a487-66727e1ef90d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D76A08A3D8797400C799299666FBB414C7C86F6C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not be configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258120","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258120","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258120","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258120r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258120","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611155","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must not have accounts configured with blank or null passwords.","fix_text":"Configure all accounts on RHEL 9 to have a password or lock the account with the following commands:\n\nPerform a password reset:\n\n$ sudo passwd [username] \n\nTo lock an account:\n\n$ sudo passwd -l [username]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that null or blank passwords cannot be used with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '!$2 {print $1}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf the command returns any results, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account has an empty password, anyone could log in and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3311","uuid":"dc4eeed1-0b94-43f1-932b-5a9f9b2e5902","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 46B9198E77E57EC56683819667C25C5EB69496E9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must not have accounts configured with blank or null passwords.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258121","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258121","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258121","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-258121r1155682_rule","rule_id":"SV-258121","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611160","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use the common access card (CAC) smart card driver.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to load the CAC driver.\n\n$ sudo opensc-tool --set-conf-entry app:default:card_drivers:cac\n\nRestart the pcscd service to apply the changes:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart pcscd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL loads the CAC driver with the following command:\n\n$ sudo opensc-tool --get-conf-entry app:default:card_drivers\n\ncac\n\nIf \"cac\" is not listed as a card driver, or no line is returned for \"card_drivers\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Smart card login provides two-factor authentication stronger than that provided by a username and password combination. Smart cards leverage public key infrastructure to provide and verify credentials. Configuring the smart card driver in use by the organization helps to prevent users from using unauthorized smart cards.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051, SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053, SRG-OS-000107-GPOS-00054, SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00055, SRG-OS-000112-GPOS-00057, SRG-OS-000113-GPOS-00058","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764","CCI-000766","CCI-000765","CCI-004045","CCI-001941","CCI-000767","CCI-000768","CCI-000770","CCI-001942"],"reference_identifier":"6982","uuid":"ecddc6a8-45f8-44a7-9c4d-a707f4dba152","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E22355CFB5C0ED46DC09622D2B750CE2488A9B10\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must use the common access card (CAC) smart card driver.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258122","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258122","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258122","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-258122r1045246_rule","rule_id":"SV-258122","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611165","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must enable certificate based smart card authentication.","fix_text":"Edit the file \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" or a configuration file in \"/etc/sssd/conf.d\" and add or edit the following line:\n\npam_cert_auth = True","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator (SA) demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nTo verify that RHEL 9 has smart cards  enabled in System Security Services Daemon (SSSD), run the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -ir pam_cert_auth /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/\n\npam_cert_auth = True \n\nIf \"pam_cert_auth\" is not set to \"True\", the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the use of multifactor authentication, the ease of access to privileged functions is greatly increased. Multifactor authentication requires using two or more factors to achieve authentication. A privileged account is defined as an information system account with authorizations of a privileged user. The DOD Common Access Card (CAC) with DOD-approved PKI is an example of multifactor authentication.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160, SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000765","CCI-004046","CCI-004047","CCI-001948"],"reference_identifier":"2829","uuid":"94b69640-2000-405a-bee9-b2814c3caefc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: ED2B4812F1C7117728D196F1775B630331AA4824\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must enable certificate based smart card authentication.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258123","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258123","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258123","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-258123r1134923_rule","rule_id":"SV-258123","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611170","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.\n\nReview the \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\" file to determine if the system is configured to prevent OCSP or certificate verification.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\" file:\n\ncertificate_verification = ocsp_dgst=sha512\n\nSet the correct ownership and permissions on the \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\" file by running these commands:\n\n$ sudo chown root:root \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\"\n$ sudo chmod 600 \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\"\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator (SA) demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system implements Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and is using the proper digest value on the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -sir certificate_verification /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/ | grep -v \"^#\"\n\n/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification:certificate_verification = ocsp_dgst=sha512\n\nIf the certificate_verification line is missing from the [sssd] section, or is missing \"ocsp_dgst=sha512\", ask the administrator to indicate what type of multifactor authentication is being used and how the system implements certificate status checking. \n\nIf there is no evidence of certificate status checking being used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using an authentication device, such as a DOD common access card (CAC) or token that is separate from the information system, ensures that even if the information system is compromised, credentials stored on the authentication device will not be affected.\n\nMultifactor solutions that require devices separate from information systems gaining access include, for example, hardware tokens providing time-based or challenge-response authenticators and smart cards such as the U.S. Government Personal Identity Verification (PIV) card and the DOD CAC.\n\nRHEL 9 includes multiple options for configuring certificate status checking, but for this requirement focuses on the System Security Services Daemon (SSSD). By default, SSSD performs Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) checking and certificate verification using a sha256 digest function.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160, SRG-OS-000377-GPOS-00162","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004046","CCI-001954","CCI-001948"],"reference_identifier":"9294","uuid":"afc5b7e7-6ee6-408d-96ca-483fbc7ae77a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 469D47F8FEC412CED984683844188B9ADF9AA5E6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258124","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258124","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258124","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-258124r1045250_rule","rule_id":"SV-258124","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611175","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the pcsc-lite package installed.","fix_text":"The  pcsc-lite  package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install pcsc-lite","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator (SA) demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that RHEL 9 has the pcsc-lite package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed pcsc-lite\n\nExample output:\n\npcsc-lite.x86_64          1.9.4-1.el9\n\nIf the \"pcsc-lite\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The pcsc-lite package must be installed if it is to be available for multifactor authentication using smart cards.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004046","CCI-001948"],"reference_identifier":"6412","uuid":"93507f91-bbac-4f66-80ea-746ae19df090","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC7CA4F25DC7B70334F02C71DA654E8BFC6CD89A\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must have the pcsc-lite package installed.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258125","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258125","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258125","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-258125r1045253_rule","rule_id":"SV-258125","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611180","rule_title":"The pcscd service on RHEL 9 must be active.","fix_text":"To enable the pcscd socket, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now pcscd.socket","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the \"pcscd\" socket is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active pcscd.socket\n\nactive\n\nIf the pcscd socket is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The information system ensures that even if the information system is compromised, that compromise will not affect credentials stored on the authentication device.\n\nThe daemon program for pcsc-lite and the MuscleCard framework is pcscd. It is a resource manager that coordinates communications with smart card readers and smart cards and cryptographic tokens that are connected to the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004046","CCI-001948"],"reference_identifier":"3281","uuid":"7e805a81-73e0-4e73-a2d2-f4bae05a8ee2","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 018E16EADBEE211C8D9CB92AB3A304DABE20EF1C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The pcscd service on RHEL 9 must be active.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258126","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258126","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258126","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-258126r1045255_rule","rule_id":"SV-258126","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611185","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the opensc package installed.","fix_text":"The opensc package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install opensc","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has the opensc package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed opensc\n\nExample output:\n\nopensc.x86_64          0.22.0-2.el9\n\nIf the \"opensc\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of PIV credentials facilitates standardization and reduces the risk of unauthorized access.\n\nThe DOD has mandated the use of the common access card (CAC) to support identity management and personal authentication for systems covered under Homeland Security Presidential Directive (HSPD) 12, as well as making the CAC a primary component of layered protection for national security systems.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160, SRG-OS-000376-GPOS-00161","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004046","CCI-001953","CCI-001948"],"reference_identifier":"8156","uuid":"031b6444-739a-4e75-b549-e5d0a7162a8a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6F420C54F3271E8D10714481D370BFAEB032E6B9\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must have the opensc package installed.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258127","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258127","title":"SRG-OS-000067-GPOS-00035","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258127","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000067-GPOS-00035","rule_id_src":"SV-258127r1155648_rule","rule_id":"SV-258127","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611190","rule_title":"RHEL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must enforce authorized access to the corresponding private key.","fix_text":"Create a new private and public key pair that utilizes a passcode with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ssh-keygen -N [passphrase]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify the SSH private key files have a passcode.\n\nFor each private key stored on the system, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo ssh-keygen -y -f /path/to/file\n\nThe expected output is a password prompt:\n \"Enter passphrase:\"\n\nIf the password prompt is not displayed, and the contents of the key are displayed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the private key is discovered, an attacker can use the key to authenticate as an authorized user and gain access to the network infrastructure.\n\nThe cornerstone of the PKI is the private key used to encrypt or digitally sign information.\n\nIf the private key is stolen, this will lead to the compromise of the authentication and nonrepudiation gained through PKI because the attacker can use the private key to digitally sign documents and pretend to be the authorized user.\n\nBoth the holders of a digital certificate and the issuing authority must protect the computers, storage devices, or whatever they use to keep the private keys.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000186"],"reference_identifier":"4530","uuid":"c050617f-ed00-4e07-97dd-124efe25f069","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3E5A5FFFD9C4ACD49BB2C40ED4D8CF49EEF7303A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must enforce authorized access to the corresponding private key.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258128","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258128","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258128","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-258128r1155626_rule","rule_id":"SV-258128","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611195","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require authentication to access emergency mode.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require authentication for emergency mode.\n\nCreate a directory for supplementary configuration files: \n$ sudo mkdir /etc/systemd/system/emergency.service.d/\n\nCopy the original file emergency.service file to the new directory with:\n$ sudo cp  /usr/lib/systemd/system/emergency.service  /etc/systemd/system/emergency.service.d/emergency.service.conf\n\nOpen the new file:\n$ sudo vi /etc/systemd/system/emergency.service.d/emergency.service.conf\n\nAdd or modify the following line in the new file:\nExecStart=-/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sulogin-shell emergency\n\nComment out or remove the ExecStart and ExecStartPre lines in /usr/lib/systemd/system/emergency.service as they can only exist in one location.\n\nApply changes to unit files without rebooting the system:\n$ sudo systemctl daemon-reload","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 requires authentication for emergency mode with the following command:\n\n$ grep sulogin /usr/lib/systemd/system/emergency.service \n\nExecStart=-/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sulogin-shell emergency\n\nIf the line is not returned from the default systemd file, use the following command to look for modifications to the emergency.service:\n\n$ grep sulogin /etc/systemd/system/emergency.service.d/*.conf \n\nIf the line is not returned from either location this is a finding.\n\nNote: The configuration setting can only be in either the default location, or in the drop in file, not both locations.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To mitigate the risk of unauthorized access to sensitive information by entities that have been issued certificates by DOD-approved PKIs, all DOD systems (e.g., web servers and web portals) must be properly configured to incorporate access control methods that do not rely solely on the possession of a certificate for access. Successful authentication must not automatically give an entity access to an asset or security boundary. Authorization procedures and controls must be implemented to ensure each authenticated entity also has a validated and current authorization. Authorization is the process of determining whether an entity, once authenticated, is permitted to access a specific asset. Information systems use access control policies and enforcement mechanisms to implement this requirement.\n\nThis requirement prevents attackers with physical access from trivially bypassing security on the machine and gaining root access. Such accesses are further prevented by configuring the bootloader password.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"8795","uuid":"ea72d1c6-1618-4c84-bd85-a60357f8fc49","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A4158651100FAE43EC1608A44E26E465E66B1127\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must require authentication to access emergency mode.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258129","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258129","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258129","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-258129r1155628_rule","rule_id":"SV-258129","rule_version":"RHEL-09-611200","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must require authentication to access single-user mode.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to require authentication for single-user mode.\n\nCreate a directory for supplementary configuration files: \n$ sudo mkdir /etc/systemd/system/rescue.service.d/\n\nCopy the original file rescue.service file to the new directory with:\n$ sudo cp  /usr/lib/systemd/system/rescue.service  /etc/systemd/system/rescue.service.d/rescue.service.conf\n\nOpen the new file:\n$ sudo vi etc/systemd/system/rescue.service.d/rescue.service.conf\n\nAdd this line to the new file:\nExecStart=-/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sulogin-shell rescue\n\nComment out or remove the ExecStart and ExecStartPre lines in /usr/lib/systemd/system/rescue.service as they can only exist in one location.\n\nApply changes to unit files without rebooting the system:\n$ sudo systemctl daemon-reload","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 requires authentication for single-user mode with the following command:\n\n$ grep sulogin /usr/lib/systemd/system/rescue.service \n\nExecStart=-/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sulogin-shell rescue\n\nIf the line is not returned from the default systemd file, use the following command to look for modifications to the rescue.service:\n\n$ grep sulogin /etc/systemd/system/rescue.service.d/*.conf \n\nIf the line is not returned from either location this is a finding.\n\nNote: The configuration setting can only be in either the default location, or in the drop in file, not both locations.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To mitigate the risk of unauthorized access to sensitive information by entities that have been issued certificates by DOD-approved PKIs, all DOD systems (e.g., web servers and web portals) must be properly configured to incorporate access control methods that do not rely solely on the possession of a certificate for access. Successful authentication must not automatically give an entity access to an asset or security boundary. Authorization procedures and controls must be implemented to ensure each authenticated entity also has a validated and current authorization. Authorization is the process of determining whether an entity, once authenticated, is permitted to access a specific asset. Information systems use access control policies and enforcement mechanisms to implement this requirement.\n\nThis requirement prevents attackers with physical access from trivially bypassing security on the machine and gaining root access. Such accesses are further prevented by configuring the bootloader password.\n\nTo modify properties, such as dependencies or timeouts, of a service that is handled by a SysV initscript, do not modify the initscript itself. Instead, create a systemd drop-in configuration file for the service. Then manage this service in the same way as a normal systemd service.\n\nFor example, to extend the configuration of the network service, do not modify the /etc/rc.d/init.d/network initscript file. Instead, create new directory /etc/systemd/system/network.service.d/ and a systemd drop-in file /etc/systemd/system/network.service.d/my_config.conf. Then, put the modified values into the drop-in file. Note: systemd knows the network service as network.service, which is why the created directory must be called \"network.service.d\".","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"5220","uuid":"057e6526-2c8b-45e4-9644-cc041f622815","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8C7E833FEF0DF62E21E4D4F1A23477BE81C0D755\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must require authentication to access single-user mode.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258131","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258131","title":"SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258131","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034","rule_id_src":"SV-258131r1134927_rule","rule_id":"SV-258131","rule_version":"RHEL-09-631010","rule_title":"RHEL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9, for PKI-based authentication, to validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.\n\nObtain a valid copy of the DOD root CA file from the PKI CA certificate bundle from cyber.mil and copy the DoD_PKE_CA_chain.pem into the following file:\n/etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 for PKI-based authentication has valid certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.\n\nCheck that the system has a valid DOD root CA installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo openssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem\n\nExample output:\n\nCertificate:\n    Data:\n        Version: 3 (0x2)\n        Serial Number: 1 (0x1)\n        Signature Algorithm: sha256WithRSAEncryption\n        Issuer: C = US, O = U.S. Government, OU = DoD, OU = PKI, CN = DoD Root CA 3\n        Validity\n        Not Before: Mar 20 18:46:41 2012 GMT\n        Not After: Dec 30 18:46:41 2029 GMT\n        Subject: C = US, O = U.S. Government, OU = DoD, OU = PKI, CN = DoD Root CA 3\n        Subject Public Key Info:\n            Public Key Algorithm: rsaEncryption\n\nIf the root CA file is not a DOD-issued certificate with a valid date and installed in the \"/etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem\" location, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without path validation, an informed trust decision by the relying party cannot be made when presented with any certificate not already explicitly trusted.\n\nA trust anchor is an authoritative entity represented via a public key and associated data. It is used in the context of public key infrastructures, X.509 digital certificates, and DNSSEC.\n\nWhen there is a chain of trust, usually the top entity to be trusted becomes the trust anchor; it can be, for example, a certification authority (CA). A certification path starts with the subject certificate and proceeds through a number of intermediate certificates up to a trusted root certificate, typically issued by a trusted CA.\n\nThis requirement verifies that a certification path to an accepted trust anchor is used for certificate validation and that the path includes status information. Path validation is necessary for a relying party to make an informed trust decision when presented with any certificate not already explicitly trusted. Status information for certification paths includes certificate revocation lists or online certificate status protocol responses. Validation of the certificate status information is out of scope for this requirement.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034, SRG-OS-000384-GPOS-00167","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000185","CCI-004068","CCI-001991"],"reference_identifier":"1180","uuid":"358d2dc6-d1de-4517-b24c-ba43cca602df","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B0A83048A96BA4E640E245939CD8EEBF5163AED\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258132","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258132","title":"SRG-OS-000068-GPOS-00036","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258132","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000068-GPOS-00036","rule_id_src":"SV-258132r1134929_rule","rule_id":"SV-258132","rule_version":"RHEL-09-631015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must map the authenticated identity to the user or group account for PKI-based authentication.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to map the authenticated identity to the user or group account by adding or modifying the certmap section of the \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" file based on the following example:\n\n[certmap/testing.test/rule_name]\nmatchrule = .*EDIPI@mil\nmaprule = (userCertificate;binary={cert!bin})\ndomains = testing.test\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator (SA) demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify the certificate of the user or group is mapped to the corresponding user or group in the \"sssd.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/ -type f -exec cat {} \\;\n \n[certmap/testing.test/rule_name]\nmatchrule =<SAN>.*EDIPI@mil\nmaprule = (userCertificate;binary={cert!bin})\ndomains = testing.test\n\nIf the certmap section does not exist, ask the SA to indicate how certificates are mapped to accounts. \n\nIf there is no evidence of certificate mapping, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without mapping the certificate used to authenticate to the user account, the ability to determine the identity of the individual user or group will not be available for forensic analysis.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000187"],"reference_identifier":"5572","uuid":"f9ecd3cf-6753-4cdc-8ce8-6d510dc30feb","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 754F2E31620B2367C3E3B4E4FE7292DA1E565E9A\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must map the authenticated identity to the user or group account for PKI-based authentication.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258133","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258133","title":"SRG-OS-000383-GPOS-00166","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258133","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000383-GPOS-00166","rule_id_src":"SV-258133r1045263_rule","rule_id":"SV-258133","rule_version":"RHEL-09-631020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.","fix_text":"Configure the SSSD to prohibit the use of cached authentications after one day.\n\nEdit the file \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" or a configuration file in \"/etc/sssd/conf.d\" and add or edit the following line just below the line [pam]:\n\noffline_credentials_expiration = 1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the System Security Services Daemon (SSSD) prohibits the use of cached authentications after one day.\n\nNote: Cached authentication settings should be configured even if smart card authentication is not used on the system.\n\nCheck that SSSD allows cached authentications with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -ir cache_credentials /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/\n\ncache_credentials = true\n\nIf \"cache_credentials\" is set to \"false\" or missing from the configuration file, this is not a finding and no further checks are required.\n\nIf \"cache_credentials\" is set to \"true\", check that SSSD prohibits the use of cached authentications after one day with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -ir offline_credentials_expiration /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/\n\noffline_credentials_expiration = 1\n\nIf \"offline_credentials_expiration\" is not set to a value of \"1\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If cached authentication information is out-of-date, the validity of the authentication information may be questionable.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002007"],"reference_identifier":"4581","uuid":"f4534ddb-7d4d-4896-96ce-e4966fe9c44f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 545C663181E7A045DEBB99B8703246ED2A40A030\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258134","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258134","title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258134","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","rule_id_src":"SV-258134r1155620_rule","rule_id":"SV-258134","rule_version":"RHEL-09-651010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the AIDE package installed.","fix_text":"Install AIDE, initialize it, and perform a manual check.\n\nInstall AIDE:\n\n$ sudo dnf install aide\n\nInitialize AIDE:\n     \n$ sudo /usr/sbin/aide --init\n\nExample output:\n\nStart timestamp: 2023-06-05 10:09:04 -0600 (AIDE 0.16)\nAIDE initialized database at /var/lib/aide/aide.db.new.gz\n\nNumber of entries:      86833\n\n---------------------------------------------------\nThe attributes of the (uncompressed) database(s):\n---------------------------------------------------\n\n/var/lib/aide/aide.db.new.gz\n  MD5      : coZUtPHhoFoeD7+k54fUvQ==\n  SHA1     : DVpOEMWJwo0uPgrKZAygIUgSxeM=\n  SHA256   : EQiZH0XNEk001tcDmJa+5STFEjDb4MPE\n             TGdBJ/uvZKc=\n  SHA512   : 86KUqw++PZhoPK0SZvT3zuFq9yu9nnPP\n             toei0nENVELJ1LPurjoMlRig6q69VR8l\n             +44EwO9eYyy9nnbzQsfG1g==\n\nEnd timestamp: 2023-06-05 10:09:57 -0600 (run time: 0m 53s)\n\nThe new database will need to be renamed to be read by AIDE:\n\n$ sudo mv /var/lib/aide/aide.db.new.gz /var/lib/aide/aide.db.gz\n\nPerform a manual check:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/aide --check\n\nExample output:\n\n2023-06-05 10:16:08 -0600 (AIDE 0.16)\nAIDE found NO differences between database and filesystem. Looks okay!!\n\n...","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the file integrity tool is configured to verify ACLs.\n\nNote: AIDE is highly configurable at install time. This requirement assumes the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.\n\nVerify AIDE is installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf list installed aide\n\nUpdating Subscription Management repositories.\nInstalled Packages\naide.x86_64                                0.16-103.el9                                @rhel-9-for-x86_64-appstream-rpms\n\nUse the following command to determine if the file is in a location other than \"/etc/aide/aide.conf\":\n\n$ sudo find / -name aide.conf\n\nIf AIDE is not installed, ask the system administrator (SA) how file integrity checks are performed on the system.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly, and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nSelection lines in the aide.conf file determine which files and directories AIDE will monitor for changes. They follow this format:\n\n<path> <rules>\n\nThe <path> specifies a file, directory or wildcard pattern to monitor.\nThe <rules>define which attributes (hashes, permissions, timestamps, etc.) to check.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150, SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001744","CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"9522","uuid":"4a18c658-4850-434d-82f3-31a6601b6f59","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9BBDF7A25333B3949490F6FAE3FC7EC26F0D8E64\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must have the AIDE package installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258135","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258135","title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258135","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","rule_id_src":"SV-258135r1045267_rule","rule_id":"SV-258135","rule_version":"RHEL-09-651015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must routinely check the baseline configuration for unauthorized changes and notify the system administrator when anomalies in the operation of any security functions are discovered.","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to run automatically on the system at least weekly and to notify designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner. The AIDE tool can be configured to email designated personnel with the use of the cron system.\n \nThe following example output is generic. It will set cron to run AIDE daily and to send email at the completion of the analysis\n\n$ sudo more /etc/cron.daily/aide\n \n#!/bin/bash\n/usr/sbin/aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"$HOSTNAME - Daily aide integrity check run\" root@sysname.mil","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 routinely executes a file integrity scan for changes to the system baseline. The command used in the example will use a daily occurrence.\n\nCheck the cron directories for scripts controlling the execution and notification of results of the file integrity application. For example, if AIDE is installed on the system, use the following commands:\n\n$ sudo ls -al /etc/cron.* | grep aide\n\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root 29 Nov 22 2015 aide\n\n$ sudo grep aide /etc/crontab /var/spool/cron/root\n\n/etc/crontab: 30 04 * * * root usr/sbin/aide\n/var/spool/cron/root: 30 04 * * * root usr/sbin/aide\n\n$ sudo more /etc/cron.daily/aide\n\n#!/bin/bash\n/usr/sbin/aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"$HOSTNAME - Daily aide integrity check run\" root@sysname.mil\n\nIf the file integrity application does not exist, a script file controlling the execution of the file integrity application does not exist, or the file integrity application does not notify designated personnel of changes, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized changes to the baseline configuration could make the system vulnerable to various attacks or allow unauthorized access to the operating system. Changes to operating system configurations can have unintended side effects, some of which may be relevant to security.\n\nDetecting such changes and providing an automated response can help avoid unintended, negative consequences that could ultimately affect the security state of the operating system. The operating system's information management officer (IMO)/information system security officer (ISSO) and system administrators (SAs) must be notified via email and/or monitoring system trap when there is an unauthorized modification of a configuration item.\n\nNotifications provided by information systems include messages to local computer consoles, and/or hardware indications, such as lights.\n\nThis capability must take into account operational requirements for availability for selecting an appropriate response. The organization may choose to shut down or restart the information system upon security function anomaly detection.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150, SRG-OS-000446-GPOS-00200, SRG-OS-000447-GPOS-00201","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001744","CCI-002699","CCI-002702"],"reference_identifier":"1504","uuid":"89394161-3e6e-4778-8618-32981945336c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5AFCA3C8B1E59E805FCB299D49888096D0B77C17\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must routinely check the baseline configuration for unauthorized changes and notify the system administrator when anomalies in the operation of any security functions are discovered.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258136","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258136","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258136","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258136r1045270_rule","rule_id":"SV-258136","rule_version":"RHEL-09-651020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use a file integrity tool that is configured to use FIPS 140-3-approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories.","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to use FIPS 140-3 cryptographic hashes for validating file and directory contents. \n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"sha512\" rule is present on all uncommented file and directory selection lists. Exclude any log files, or files expected to change frequently, to reduce unnecessary notifications.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that AIDE is configured to use FIPS 140-3 file hashing with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep sha512 /etc/aide.conf \n\nAll=p+i+n+u+g+s+m+S+sha512+acl+xattrs+selinux\n\nIf the \"sha512\" rule is not being used on all uncommented selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, or another file integrity tool is not using FIPS 140-3-approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"RHEL 9 installation media ships with an optional file integrity tool called Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE). AIDE is highly configurable at install time. This requirement assumes the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.\n\nFile integrity tools use cryptographic hashes for verifying file contents and directories have not been altered. These hashes must be FIPS 140-3-approved cryptographic hashes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9691","uuid":"fe6088ed-f08c-49dd-b34e-3c2bca7a5156","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 989348AD3105C9DBDC1FB9715C1BA0FA34773FB3\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must use a file integrity tool that is configured to use FIPS 140-3-approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258137","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258137","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258137","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-258137r1102081_rule","rule_id":"SV-258137","rule_version":"RHEL-09-651025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","fix_text":"Add or update the following lines to \"/etc/aide.conf\", to protect the integrity of the audit tools.\n \n/usr/sbin/auditctl p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/auditd p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/ausearch p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/aureport p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/autrace p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/augenrules p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check that AIDE is properly configured to protect the integrity of the audit tools with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /usr/sbin/au /etc/aide.conf\n\n/usr/sbin/auditctl p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/auditd p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/ausearch p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/aureport p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/autrace p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/augenrules p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n\nIf AIDE is not installed, ask the system administrator (SA) how file integrity checks are performed on the system.\n\nIf any of the audit tools listed above do not have a corresponding line, ask the SA to indicate what cryptographic mechanisms are being used to protect the integrity of the audit tools.  \n\nIf there is no evidence of integrity protection, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting the integrity of the tools used for auditing purposes is a critical step toward ensuring the integrity of audit information. Audit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit information system activity.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open-source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nIt is not uncommon for attackers to replace the audit tools or inject code into the existing tools to provide the capability to hide or erase system activity from the audit logs.\n\nTo address this risk, audit tools must be cryptographically signed to provide the capability to identify when the audit tools have been modified, manipulated, or replaced. An example is a checksum hash of the file or files.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097, SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098, SRG-OS-000258-GPOS-00099, SRG-OS-000278-GPOS-00108","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493","CCI-001494","CCI-001495","CCI-001496"],"reference_identifier":"3986","uuid":"9d87a1b8-c288-4084-ae66-ab5fe44f3aec","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DFD47EE045E62F62095E3A2143B465798A5726B9\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258138","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258138","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258138","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258138r1045274_rule","rule_id":"SV-258138","rule_version":"RHEL-09-651030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that the file integrity tool verifies Access Control Lists (ACLs).","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to check file and directory ACLs. \n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"acl\" rule is present on all uncommented file and directory selection lists.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that AIDE is verifying ACLs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep acl /etc/aide.conf\n\nAll= p+i+n+u+g+s+m+S+sha512+acl+xattrs+selinux\n\nIf the \"acl\" rule is not being used on all uncommented selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, or ACLs are not being checked by another file integrity tool, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"RHEL 9 installation media ships with an optional file integrity tool called Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE). AIDE is highly configurable at install time. This requirement assumes the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.\n\nACLs can provide permissions beyond those permitted through the file mode and must be verified by the file integrity tools.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3422","uuid":"fe92f06f-e891-4c82-b37b-cd55d13e095a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7A09ADEE9E10442173DB3AB44C1A10A412CEA7AA\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that the file integrity tool verifies Access Control Lists (ACLs).' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258139","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258139","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258139","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258139r1045276_rule","rule_id":"SV-258139","rule_version":"RHEL-09-651035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that the file integrity tool verifies extended attributes.","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to check file and directory extended attributes. \n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"xattrs\" rule is present on all uncommented file and directory selection lists.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that AIDE is configured to verify extended attributes with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep xattrs /etc/aide.conf\n\nAll= p+i+n+u+g+s+m+S+sha512+acl+xattrs+selinux\n\nIf the \"xattrs\" rule is not being used on all uncommented selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, or extended attributes are not being checked by another file integrity tool, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"RHEL 9 installation media ships with an optional file integrity tool called Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE). AIDE is highly configurable at install time. This requirement assumes the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.\n\nExtended attributes in file systems are used to contain arbitrary data and file metadata with security implications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4426","uuid":"fd7299d0-7701-4bf5-90e2-c70b907e1bca","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A6D1C5F646C2514B3E23096A846608598DC41524\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that the file integrity tool verifies extended attributes.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258140","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258140","title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258140","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","rule_id_src":"SV-258140r1106460_rule","rule_id":"SV-258140","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the rsyslog package installed.","fix_text":"Install the rsyslog package with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install rsyslog","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 has the rsyslog package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed rsyslog\n\nExample output:\n\nrsyslog.x86_64          8.2102.0-101.el9_0.1\n\nIf the \"rsyslog\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"rsyslogd is a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Couple this utility with \"gnutls\" (which is a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS, and DTLS protocols), to create a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224, SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000154","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"1755","uuid":"227171d2-c770-482b-9eeb-3938d39f2d93","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4C39889DACE106784C1C74EFB0FA19D363DF36E3\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must have the rsyslog package installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258141","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258141","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258141","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258141r1045280_rule","rule_id":"SV-258141","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have the packages required for encrypting offloaded audit logs installed.","fix_text":"The  rsyslog-gnutls package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install rsyslog-gnutls","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has the rsyslog-gnutls package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed rsyslog-gnutls\n\nExample output:\n\nrsyslog-gnutls.x86_64          8.2102.0-101.el9_0.1\n\nIf the \"rsyslog-gnutls\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The rsyslog-gnutls package provides Transport Layer Security (TLS) support for the rsyslog daemon, which enables secure remote logging.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000803"],"reference_identifier":"4770","uuid":"faad5669-e7c9-4bbd-989e-6817ce0a6a40","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258142","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258142","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258142","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258142r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258142","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652020","rule_title":"The rsyslog service on RHEL 9 must be active.","fix_text":"To enable the rsyslog service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now rsyslog","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"rsyslog\" is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active rsyslog \n\nactive\n\nIf the rsyslog service is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"rsyslog\" service must be running to provide logging services, which are essential to system administration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1594","uuid":"8cb5419b-d443-4456-95d3-620549fcc371","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F2F23BD1C0556895F8EC9D03A7E19A94035C30B5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The rsyslog service on RHEL 9 must be active.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258143","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258143","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258143","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258143r1184329_rule","rule_id":"SV-258143","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured so that the rsyslog daemon does not accept log messages from other servers unless the server is being used for log aggregation.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to not receive remote logs using rsyslog.\n\nRemove the lines in /etc/rsyslog.conf and any files in the /etc/rsyslog.d directory that match any of the following:\nInputTCPServerRun\nUDPServerRun\nRELPServerRun\nmodule(load=\"imtcp\")\nmodule(load=\"imudp\")\nmodule(load=\"imrelp\")\ninput(type=\"imudp\" port=\"514\")\ninput(type=\"imtcp\" port=\"514\")\ninput(type=\"imrelp\" port=\"514\")\n\nThe rsyslog daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator (SA) can demonstrate that another tool (e.g., SPLUNK) is being used to manage log off-load and aggregation in lieu of rsyslog, this is not applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 9 is not configured to receive remote logs using rsyslog with the following command:\n\n$ ss -tulnp | grep rsyslog\n\nIf no output is returned, rsyslog is not listening for remote messages and is compliant.\n\nIf output appears, check for configured ports (514 is the default for syslog).\n\nCheck for remote logging configuration in rsyslog by examining the rsyslog configuration files:\n\n$ sudo grep -E 'InputTCPServerRun|UDPServerRun|RELPServerRun|imtcp|imudp|imrelp' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*\n\nIf this command returns uncommented lines enabling network listeners, the system is accepting remote logs.  If this system is not documented and authorized as a log aggregation server, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unintentionally running a rsyslog server accepting remote messages puts the system at increased risk. Malicious rsyslog messages sent to the server could exploit vulnerabilities in the server software itself, could introduce misleading information into the system's logs, or could fill the system's storage leading to a denial of service.\n\nIf the system is intended to be a log aggregation server, its use must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1366","uuid":"28e10743-589e-443e-9b17-b3fd1667f1f3","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4D084189F1B9F2581F0C518201FE9DAEF9356597\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured so that the rsyslog daemon does not accept log messages from other servers unless the server is being used for log aggregation.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258144","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258144","title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258144","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","rule_id_src":"SV-258144r1045286_rule","rule_id":"SV-258144","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652030","rule_title":"All RHEL 9 remote access methods must be monitored.","fix_text":"Add or update the following lines to the \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" file or a file in \"/etc/rsyslog.d\":\n\nauth.*;authpriv.*;daemon.* /var/log/secure\n\nThe \"rsyslog\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 monitors all remote access methods.\n\nCheck that remote access methods are being logged by running the following command:\n\n$ grep -rE '(auth.\\*|authpriv.\\*|daemon.\\*)' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:authpriv.*\n \nIf \"auth.*\", \"authpriv.*\" or \"daemon.*\" are not configured to be logged, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Logging remote access methods can be used to trace the decrease in the risks associated with remote user access management. It can also be used to spot cyberattacks and ensure ongoing compliance with organizational policies surrounding the use of remote access methods.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000067"],"reference_identifier":"1976","uuid":"fc422fdb-9f42-4a2a-a7bf-be8a61d822f1","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4556B969491204FF600EE5482C68B0B3C7284041\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All RHEL 9 remote access methods must be monitored.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258146","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258146","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258146","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-258146r1045288_rule","rule_id":"SV-258146","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must authenticate the remote logging server for offloading audit logs via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to authenticate the remote logging server for offloading audit logs by setting the following option in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode x509/name","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 authenticates the remote logging server for offloading audit logs with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i 'StreamDriver[\\.]*AuthMode' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode x509/name \n\nIf the variable name \"StreamDriverAuthMode\" is present in an omfwd statement block, this is not a finding. However, if the \"StreamDriverAuthMode\" variable is in a module block, this is a finding.\n\nIf the value of the \"$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode or StreamDriver.AuthMode\" option is not set to \"x509/name\" or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the audit logs are offloaded to a different system or media. \n\nIf there is no evidence that the transfer of the audit logs being offloaded to another system or media is encrypted, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\n\"Rsyslog\" supported authentication modes include:\nanon - anonymous authentication\nx509/fingerprint - certificate fingerprint authentication\nx509/certvalid - certificate validation only\nx509/name - certificate validation and subject name authentication\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"7579","uuid":"6e2a68eb-8137-4a97-af4a-fcb23c820ad1","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3BF01FCFC6070E1C97265C03F3AA50A7DA73B391\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must authenticate the remote logging server for offloading audit logs via rsyslog.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258147","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258147","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258147","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-258147r1045290_rule","rule_id":"SV-258147","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must encrypt the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to encrypt offloaded audit records via rsyslog by setting the following options in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 encrypts audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i 'StreamDriver[\\.]*Mode' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1 \n\nIf the value of the \"$ActionSendStreamDriverMode or StreamDriver.Mode\" option is not set to \"1\" or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the variable name \"StreamDriverAuthMode\" is present in an omfwd statement block, this is not a finding. However, if the \"StreamDriverAuthMode\" variable is in a module block, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\n\"Rsyslog\" supported authentication modes include:\nanon - anonymous authentication\nx509/fingerprint - certificate fingerprint authentication\nx509/certvalid - certificate validation only\nx509/name - certificate validation and subject name authentication\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"4953","uuid":"a0dce6c5-278a-42fb-a9d3-54d80aed1bcb","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B250FFECB37A02634EB7CA1828F8E9180BE49F4B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must encrypt the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258148","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258148","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258148","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-258148r1045292_rule","rule_id":"SV-258148","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must encrypt via the gtls driver the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to use the gtls driver to encrypt offloaded audit records by setting the following options in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 uses the gtls driver to encrypt audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited with the following command:\n\n$ grep -Ei 'DefaultNetStreamDriver\\b|StreamDriver.Name' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls\n\nIf the value of the \"$DefaultNetstreamDriver or StreamDriver\" option is not set to \"gtls\" or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the variable name \"StreamDriver\" is present in an omfwd statement block, this is not a finding. However, if the \"StreamDriver\" variable is in a module block, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"6070","uuid":"e0619da2-5382-4122-8cac-af2b9f5b80a5","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EBD5C18D4C9F0AE22136C6FD9E204F54E007B244\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must encrypt via the gtls driver the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258149","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258149","title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258149","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","rule_id_src":"SV-258149r1155580_rule","rule_id":"SV-258149","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652055","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must be configured to forward audit records via TCP to a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to off-load audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited via TCP using rsyslog by specifying the remote logging server in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\" with the name or IP address of the log aggregation server. The following are examples of the configuration for the legacy syntax and for the newer Rainer script. Only one should be used.\n\nUsing legacy '@host:port\" syntax example:\n*.* @@[remoteloggingserver]:[port]\n\nUsing Rainer script example:\naction(\n    type=\"omfwd\"\n    target=\"logserver.example.com\"\n    port=\"514\"\n    protocol=\"tcp\"\n    action.resumeRetryCount=\"-1\"\n    queue.type=\"linkedList\"\n    que.size=\"10000\"\n)\n\nNote: The Rainer Script above does not contain the required encryption settings.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 audit system off-loads audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog using TCP with the following commands:\n\nTo check for legacy configuration syntax, perform the following:\n$ sudo grep -ir '@@' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/\n\nTo check for Rainer script syntax, perform the following:\n$ sudo grep -rq 'type=\"omfwd\"' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/\n\nIf a remote server is not configured, or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or media. \n\nIf there is no evidence that the audit logs are being off-loaded to another system or media, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and off-load auditing.\n\nRsyslog provides three ways to forward message: the traditional UDP transport, which is extremely lossy but standard; the plain TCP based transport, which loses messages only during certain situations but is widely available; and the RELP transport, which does not lose messages but is currently available only as part of the rsyslogd 3.15.0 and above.\n\nExamples of each configuration:\nUDP *.* @remotesystemname\nTCP *.* @@remotesystemname\nRELP *.* :omrelp:remotesystemname:2514\nNote that a port number was given as there is no standard port for RELP.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"8665","uuid":"2063bcea-5089-4b6d-a4c6-f11dcef6c5e2","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A89A015A4EFAA48349975ECEF7B0386F85C54C9C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must be configured to forward audit records via TCP to a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258150","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258150","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258150","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258150r1045296_rule","rule_id":"SV-258150","rule_version":"RHEL-09-652060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must use cron logging.","fix_text":"Configure \"rsyslog\" to log all cron messages by adding or updating the following line to \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or a configuration file in the /etc/rsyslog.d/ directory:\n\ncron.* /var/log/cron\n\nThe rsyslog daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"rsyslog\" is configured to log cron events with the following command:\n\nNote: If another logging package is used, substitute the utility configuration file for \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\" files.\n\n$ grep -s cron /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none /var/log/messages\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:cron.* /var/log/cron\n\nIf the command does not return a response, check for cron logging all facilities with the following command:\n\n$ logger -p local0.info \"Test message for all facilities.\"\n\nCheck the logs for the test message with:\n\n$ sudo tail /var/log/messages\n\nIf \"rsyslog\" is not logging messages for the cron facility or all facilities, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Cron logging can be used to trace the successful or unsuccessful execution of cron jobs. It can also be used to spot intrusions into the use of the cron facility by unauthorized and malicious users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3046","uuid":"5dcdbb05-a0b9-4db2-9e47-5fb0abdb57ad","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 33A052AC5C62753F7F4B119C0A9A6AF66C4333F7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must use cron logging.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258151","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258151","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258151","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-258151r1045298_rule","rule_id":"SV-258151","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit package must be installed.","fix_text":"Install the audit service package (if the audit service is not already installed) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf install audit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the RHEL 9 audit service package is installed.\n\nCheck that the audit service package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed audit\n\nExample output:\n\naudit-3.0.7-101.el9_0.2.x86_64\n\nIf the \"audit\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nAssociating event types with detected events in audit logs provides a means of investigating an attack, recognizing resource utilization or capacity thresholds, or identifying an improperly configured RHEL 9 system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000038-GPOS-00016, SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000040-GPOS-00018, SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00021, SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024, SRG-OS-000054-GPOS-00025, SRG-OS-000122-GPOS-00063, SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096, SRG-OS-000337-GPOS-00129, SRG-OS-000348-GPOS-00136, SRG-OS-000349-GPOS-00137, SRG-OS-000350-GPOS-00138, SRG-OS-000351-GPOS-00139, SRG-OS-000352-GPOS-00140, SRG-OS-000353-GPOS-00141, SRG-OS-000354-GPOS-00142, SRG-OS-000358-GPOS-00145, SRG-OS-000365-GPOS-00152, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000475-GPOS-00220, SRG-OS-000055-GPOS-00026","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000131","CCI-000132","CCI-000133","CCI-000134","CCI-000135","CCI-000154","CCI-000158","CCI-000159","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-001464","CCI-001487","CCI-003938","CCI-001875","CCI-001876","CCI-001877","CCI-001878","CCI-001879","CCI-001880","CCI-001881","CCI-001882","CCI-001889","CCI-001914","CCI-002884","CCI-001814"],"reference_identifier":"7752","uuid":"7a00a955-64cd-4d61-a497-79555ecbf6ac","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258152","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258152","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258152","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-258152r1015127_rule","rule_id":"SV-258152","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit service must be enabled.","fix_text":"To enable the auditd service run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now auditd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit service is configured to produce audit records with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl status auditd.service\n\nauditd.service - Security Auditing Service\nLoaded:loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/auditd.service; enabled; vendor preset: enabled)\nActive: active (running) since Tues 2022-05-24 12:56:56 EST; 4 weeks 0 days ago\n\nIf the audit service is not \"active\" and \"running\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack. Ensuring the \"auditd\" service is active ensures audit records generated by the kernel are appropriately recorded.\n\nAdditionally, a properly configured audit subsystem ensures that actions of individual system users can be uniquely traced to those users so they can be held accountable for their actions.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000038-GPOS-00016, SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000040-GPOS-00018, SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00021, SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024, SRG-OS-000054-GPOS-00025, SRG-OS-000122-GPOS-00063, SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096, SRG-OS-000337-GPOS-00129, SRG-OS-000348-GPOS-00136, SRG-OS-000349-GPOS-00137, SRG-OS-000350-GPOS-00138, SRG-OS-000351-GPOS-00139, SRG-OS-000352-GPOS-00140, SRG-OS-000353-GPOS-00141, SRG-OS-000354-GPOS-00142, SRG-OS-000358-GPOS-00145, SRG-OS-000365-GPOS-00152, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000475-GPOS-00220","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000131","CCI-000132","CCI-000133","CCI-000134","CCI-000135","CCI-000154","CCI-000158","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-001464","CCI-001487","CCI-003938","CCI-001875","CCI-001876","CCI-001877","CCI-001878","CCI-001879","CCI-001880","CCI-001881","CCI-001882","CCI-001889","CCI-001914","CCI-002884","CCI-004188","CCI-001814"],"reference_identifier":"8003","uuid":"d801a639-a259-44d7-9841-824988ae08e6","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 24E33F924C238DA2391A7D64A66311AD68994F5A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit service must be enabled.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258153","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258153","title":"SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258153","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","rule_id_src":"SV-258153r1038966_rule","rule_id":"SV-258153","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when an error writing to the audit storage volume occurs.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to shut down by default upon audit failure (unless availability is an overriding concern).\n\nAdd or update the following line (depending on configuration \"disk_error_action\" can be set to \"SYSLOG\" or \"SINGLE\" depending on configuration) in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\ndisk_error_action = HALT\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), configure the operating system to notify SA staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure by setting the \"disk_error_action\" to \"SYSLOG\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 takes the appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs.\n\nCheck that RHEL 9 takes the appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep disk_error_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\ndisk_error_action = HALT\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_error_action\" option is not \"SYSLOG\", \"SINGLE\", or \"HALT\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit process failure occurs. If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical that when the operating system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000140"],"reference_identifier":"7344","uuid":"0558005a-6530-45ae-8400-b3eb5546d5cc","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2EFF37CD87DC351C1986530121CB3E298B3C7F6C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when an error writing to the audit storage volume occurs.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258154","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258154","title":"SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258154","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","rule_id_src":"SV-258154r1038966_rule","rule_id":"SV-258154","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to shut down by default upon audit failure (unless availability is an overriding concern).\n\nAdd or update the following line (depending on configuration \"disk_full_action\" can be set to \"SYSLOG\" or \"SINGLE\" depending on configuration) in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\ndisk_full_action = HALT\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), configure the operating system to notify SA staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure by setting the \"disk_full_action\" to \"SYSLOG\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full. \n\nCheck that RHEL 9 takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep disk_full_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\ndisk_full_action = HALT\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_full_action\" option is not \"SYSLOG\", \"SINGLE\", or \"HALT\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit storage volume is full. If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical that when the operating system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000140"],"reference_identifier":"8658","uuid":"201dd318-7915-4319-8354-a7313e9a12a6","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-258155","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258155","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258155","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-258155r1045300_rule","rule_id":"SV-258155","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records.","fix_text":"Allocate enough storage capacity for at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nIf audit records are stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, resize the partition with sufficient space to contain one week of audit records.\n\nIf audit records are not stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, a new partition with sufficient space will need be to be created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 allocates audit record storage capacity to store at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nNote: The partition size needed to capture a week of audit records is based on the activity level of the system and the total storage capacity available. Typically 10.0GB of storage space for audit records should be sufficient.\n\nDetermine which partition the audit records are being written to with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log \n\nCheck the size of the partition that audit records are written to with the following command and verify whether it is sufficiently large:\n\n # df -h /var/log/audit/\n\n/dev/sda2 24G 10.4G 13.6G 43% /var/log/audit \n\nIf the audit record partition is not allocated for sufficient storage capacity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure RHEL 9 systems have a sufficient storage capacity in which to write the audit logs, RHEL 9 needs to be able to allocate audit record storage capacity.\n\nThe task of allocating audit record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of RHEL 9.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001849","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"6141","uuid":"d77b5687-386a-47ca-bcd0-4431d10a96e4","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3E19B2AB9E2385AA1FFDA3186E1006F2D99DA488\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258156","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258156","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258156","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-258156r1106364_rule","rule_id":"SV-258156","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches (at most) 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file.\n\nspace_left  = 25%","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nspace_left = 25%\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left\" keyword is not set to 25 percent or greater of the storage volume allocated to audit logs, or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and ISSO. If the \"space_left\" value is not configured to the value 25 percent or more, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches a maximum of 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion. The notification can be set to trigger at lower utilization thresholds at the information system security officer's (ISSO's) discretion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"5136","uuid":"b6b4dfc4-b31d-4b0e-a88a-9a73fa353c12","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 516BDA908EC54C23F0947B079A388A3758D80256\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258157","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258157","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258157","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-258157r1134932_rule","rule_id":"SV-258157","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file.\n\nspace_left_action = email","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 notifies the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nspace_left_action = email\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left_action\" is not set to \"email\", or if the line is commented out, ask the SA to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and ISSO.\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"9584","uuid":"a6352ee8-6f62-4132-83c5-92fae9269e4d","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5E982B122D892D7CBB667668140089866529B0A8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258158","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258158","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258158","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-258158r971542_rule","rule_id":"SV-258158","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653045","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to initiate an action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file.\n\nadmin_space_left  = 5%","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w admin_space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nadmin_space_left = 5%\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left\" keyword is not set to 5 percent of the storage volume allocated to audit logs, or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is taking action if the allocated storage is about to reach capacity. If the \"space_left\" value is not configured to the correct value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 95 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"3864","uuid":"6058b2b3-cb7e-4aa0-80fd-54cb62049d82","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7EEDB0747EA2EEADB78A011E797681927157B030\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the audit record storage capacity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258159","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258159","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258159","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-258159r971542_rule","rule_id":"SV-258159","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653050","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure \"auditd\" service  to take action in the event of allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nEdit the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to ensure that the system is forced into single user mode in the event the audit record storage volume is about to reach maximum capacity:\n\nadmin_space_left_action = single \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 is configured to take action in the event of allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep admin_space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nadmin_space_left_action = single\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left_action\" is not set to \"single\", or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and information system security officer (ISSO).\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 95 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"8869","uuid":"ee760e37-9566-4728-9de9-e9c548042907","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 16228F6C96C674AE8784C43939ADD991999C48AE\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258160","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258160","title":"SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258160","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","rule_id_src":"SV-258160r1038966_rule","rule_id":"SV-258160","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653055","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit files have reached maximum size.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to rotate the audit log when it reaches maximum size.\n\nAdd or update the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\nmax_log_file_action = ROTATE","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 takes the appropriate action when the audit files have reached maximum size with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep max_log_file_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nmax_log_file_action = ROTATE\n\nIf the value of the \"max_log_file_action\" option is not \"ROTATE\", \"SINGLE\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA)to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit storage volume is full. If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical that when the operating system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000140"],"reference_identifier":"1565","uuid":"d370af09-f20a-4b99-8646-b41a268807f7","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7ED2663AF692FAB6CBA6B893F9751C38D854F1A2\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit files have reached maximum size.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258161","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258161","title":"SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258161","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017","rule_id_src":"SV-258161r958416_rule","rule_id":"SV-258161","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653060","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must label all offloaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.","fix_text":"Edit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"name_format\" option:\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 Audit Daemon is configured to label all offloaded audit logs, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep name_format /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nIf the \"name_format\" option is not \"hostname\", \"fqd\", or \"numeric\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enriched logging is needed to determine who, what, and when events occur on a system. Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.\n\nWhen audit logs are not labeled before they are sent to a central log server, the audit data will not be able to be analyzed and tied back to the correct system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000132","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"3120","uuid":"8a9db840-7de3-4308-bc90-7a913608a932","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3569E441E9134A10B86AA8D6C48F05C13E0BF2D7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must label all offloaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258162","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258162","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258162","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-258162r1184331_rule","rule_id":"SV-258162","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653065","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.","fix_text":"Edit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"overflow_action\" option:\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 audit system is configured to take an appropriate action when the internal event queue is full:\n\n$ sudo grep -i overflow_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf \n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nIf the value of the \"overflow_action\" option is not set to \"syslog\", \"single\", \"halt\" or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the audit logs are offloaded to a different system or media.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the audit system is configured to off-load the audit logs to another system or media and if the overflow action is not set to take appropriate action if the internal event queue becomes full, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The audit system should have an action setup in the event the internal event queue becomes full so that no data is lost.  Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"3309","uuid":"fa629c22-ff60-4f24-8996-44f970d3cb25","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AF9516BB242861D2F6540887EAE2049743151AEA\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258163","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258163","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258163","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-258163r958424_rule","rule_id":"SV-258163","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653070","rule_title":"RHEL 9 System Administrator (SA) and/or information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) must be alerted of an audit processing failure event.","fix_text":"Configure \"auditd\" service to notify the SA and ISSO in the event of an audit processing failure.\n\nEdit the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to ensure that administrators are notified via email for those situations:\n\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 is configured to notify the SA and/or ISSO (at a minimum) in the event of an audit processing failure with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep action_mail_acct /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nIf the value of the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is not set to \"root\" and/or other accounts for security personnel, the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is missing, or the retuned line is commented out, ask the SA to indicate how they and the ISSO are notified of an audit process failure. If there is no evidence of the proper personnel being notified of an audit processing failure, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nThis requirement applies to each audit data storage repository (i.e., distinct information system component where audit records are stored), the centralized audit storage capacity of organizations (i.e., all audit data storage repositories combined), or both.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022, SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139","CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"1189","uuid":"bc7d5acf-74c6-4659-8604-48d3509adfbe","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B45AC4760FBCAD35B4167183ED50D39494316A66\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 System Administrator (SA) and/or information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) must be alerted of an audit processing failure event.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258164","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258164","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258164","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-258164r1045301_rule","rule_id":"SV-258164","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653075","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit system must audit local events.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to generate audit records for local events by adding or updating the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\":\n\nlocal_events = yes \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the RHEL 9 audit system is configured to audit local events with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep local_events /etc/audit/auditd.conf \n\nlocal_events = yes \n\nIf \"local_events\" isn't set to \"yes\", if the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nIf option \"local_events\" isn't set to \"yes\" only events from network will be aggregated.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"9175","uuid":"0338be80-02bd-4fa4-bc38-3429ebd0e359","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D5B98199718FDD76925DF8C8BB3A183EB2436BBE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit system must audit local events.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258165","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258165","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258165","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-258165r958434_rule","rule_id":"SV-258165","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653080","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit logs must be group-owned by root or by a restricted logging group to prevent unauthorized read access.","fix_text":"Change the group of the directory of \"/var/log/audit\" to be owned by a correct group.\n\nIdentify the group that is configured to own audit log:\n\n$ sudo grep -P '^[ ]*log_group[ ]+=.*$' /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChange the ownership to that group:\n\n$ sudo chgrp ${GROUP} /var/log/audit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit logs are group-owned by \"root\" or a restricted logging group. \n\nFirst determine if a group other than \"root\" has been assigned to the audit logs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep log_group /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nThen determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nThen using the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log is group-owned by \"root\" using the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G %n\" /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nroot /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit log is not group-owned by \"root\" or the configured alternative logging group, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164","CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"5751","uuid":"6a83aba2-ecdc-4785-a59c-e0ffa788ea45","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DE42D67DE760289849CA5C053D5C59CD80B9E69B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit logs must be group-owned by root or by a restricted logging group to prevent unauthorized read access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258166","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258166","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258166","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-258166r1045303_rule","rule_id":"SV-258166","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653085","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit log directory must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.","fix_text":"Configure the audit log to be protected from unauthorized read access by setting the correct owner as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root /var/log/audit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit logs directory is owned by \"root\". \n\nDetermine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nUsing the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log directory is owned by \"root\" using the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c '%U %n' /var/log/audit\n\nroot /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit log directory is not owned by \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164","CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"7259","uuid":"c10e933a-a440-4a9b-a080-e75f8306f482","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 704FDF835869BA70C7EE480087607D34B72DCE85\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 audit log directory must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258167","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258167","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258167","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-258167r1155630_rule","rule_id":"SV-258167","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653090","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audit logs file must have mode 0600 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized access to the audit log.","fix_text":"Configure the audit logs to have a mode of \"0600\" with the following command:\n\nReplace \"[audit_log_file]\" with the path to each audit log file. By default, these logs are located in \"/var/log/audit/.\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 /var/log/audit/[audit_log_file]\n\nCheck the group that owns the system audit logs:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_group /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nIf log_group is set to a user other than root, configure the permissions the following way:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 $log_file\n$ sudo chmod 0440 $log_file.*\n\nOtherwise, configure the permissions the following way:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 $log_file\n$ sudo chmod 0400 $log_file.*","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audit logs have a mode of \"0600\". \n\nDetermine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"^log_file\" /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nUsing the location of the audit log file, determine the mode of each audit log with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /var/log/audit/ -type f -exec stat -c '%a %n' {} \\;\n\n600 /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit logs have a mode more permissive than \"0600\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 9 system or platform. Additionally, Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164","CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"3600","uuid":"b6118bab-fb4b-4f45-8c9e-7503f557519a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3C7AA3D4FB1B71F23FF591BD4D1B6C07680302A5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audit logs file must have mode 0600 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized access to the audit log.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258168","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258168","title":"SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258168","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024","rule_id_src":"SV-258168r958428_rule","rule_id":"SV-258168","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653095","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must periodically flush audit records to disk to prevent the loss of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to flush audit to disk by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\":\n\nfreq = 100\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that audit system is configured to flush to disk after every 100 records with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep freq /etc/audit/auditd.conf \n\nfreq = 100 \n\nIf \"freq\" isn't set to a value between \"1\" and \"100\", the value is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If option \"freq\" is not set to a value that requires audit records being written to disk after a threshold number is reached, then audit records may be lost.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000154"],"reference_identifier":"6065","uuid":"c2829b91-fa79-4371-8b3a-3b3b782f8793","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 796CB1BB563F7BEED99CAB2E41381CF05AB2F9C5\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 9 must periodically flush audit records to disk to prevent the loss of audit records.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258169","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258169","title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258169","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","rule_id_src":"SV-258169r991556_rule","rule_id":"SV-258169","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653100","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.","fix_text":"Edit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"log_format\" option:\n\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 audit system is configured to resolve audit information before writing to disk, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep log_format /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nIf the \"log_format\" option is not \"ENRICHED\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nEnriched logging aids in making sense of who, what, and when events occur on a system. Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366","CCI-001487"],"reference_identifier":"7869","uuid":"4407366a-99da-4fc2-aa85-86c7684ddd7c","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A364F303874B56E686AE91F6D1F22E754B49E300\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258170","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258170","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258170","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-258170r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-258170","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653105","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must write audit records to disk.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to write log files to the disk.\n\nEdit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"write_logs\" option to \"yes\":\n\nwrite_logs = yes \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the audit system is configured to write logs to the disk with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep write_logs /etc/audit/auditd.conf \n\nwrite_logs = yes \n\nIf \"write_logs\" does not have a value of \"yes\", the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Audit data should be synchronously written to disk to ensure log integrity. This setting assures that all audit event data is written disk.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4199","uuid":"7ec5d10a-84a6-4f18-a607-8852109f9755","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 41848D5ACBBABDBC196FB2C704D08E8EEF83CC6D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must write audit records to disk.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258171","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258171","title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258171","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","rule_id_src":"SV-258171r1134934_rule","rule_id":"SV-258171","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653110","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must allow only the information system security manager (ISSM) (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.","fix_text":"Configure the files in directory \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" and the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file to have a mode of \"0640\" with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/rules.d/[customrulesfile].rules\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the files in directory \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" and \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file have a mode of \"0640\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /etc/audit/rules.d/ /etc/audit/audit.rules /etc/audit/auditd.conf -type f -exec stat -c \"%a %n\" {} \\;\n\n600 /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\n640 /etc/audit/audit.rules\n640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nIf the audit configuration files have a mode more permissive than those shown, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to restrict the roles and individuals that can select which events are audited, unauthorized personnel may be able to prevent the auditing of critical events. Misconfigured audits may degrade the system's performance by overwhelming the audit log. Misconfigured audits may also make it more difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000171"],"reference_identifier":"9767","uuid":"159655a4-9aab-44b2-9469-f9e1fb990c8f","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F9A94B5014ACCF010DF6000694A4C8522D5521B0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must allow only the information system security manager (ISSM) (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258173","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258173","title":"SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258173","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095","rule_id_src":"SV-258173r1101933_rule","rule_id":"SV-258173","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653120","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must allocate an audit_backlog_limit of sufficient size to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to allocate sufficient audit_backlog_limit to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=audit_backlog_limit=8192","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 allocates a sufficient audit_backlog_limit to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep args | grep 'audit_backlog_limit'\n\nIf the command returns any outputs, and audit_backlog_limit is less than \"8192\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nAllocating an audit_backlog_limit of sufficient size is critical in maintaining a stable boot process. With an insufficient limit allocated, the system is susceptible to boot failures and crashes.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001464","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"7387","uuid":"94700714-7f58-4a9d-b6a4-b4de22b3082a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC2A54FFC663F3EF1344C72E2D4AC36AB124A862\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must allocate an audit_backlog_limit of sufficient size to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258174","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258174","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258174","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-258174r958424_rule","rule_id":"SV-258174","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653125","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must have mail aliases to notify the information system security officer (ISSO) and system administrator (SA) (at a minimum) in the event of an audit processing failure.","fix_text":"Edit the aliases map file (by default /etc/aliases) used by Postfix and configure a root alias (using the user ISSO as an example):\n\nroot:    ISSO\n\nand then update the aliases database with the command:\n\n$ sudo newaliases","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 is configured to notify the appropriate interactive users in the event of an audit processing failure.\n\nFind the alias maps that are being used with the following command:\n\n$ postconf alias_maps \n\nalias_maps = hash:/etc/aliases\n\nQuery the Postfix alias maps for an alias for the root user with the following command:\n\n$ postmap -q root hash:/etc/aliases\nisso\n\nIf an alias is not set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nThis requirement applies to each audit data storage repository (i.e., distinct information system component where audit records are stored), the centralized audit storage capacity of organizations (i.e., all audit data storage repositories combined), or both.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139"],"reference_identifier":"9659","uuid":"f6162a94-30d2-426a-b1e5-a59db7317202","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 35EEE8142EB5C04140BFDDD382BF1286382F8327\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must have mail aliases to notify the information system security officer (ISSO) and system administrator (SA) (at a minimum) in the event of an audit processing failure.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258175","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258175","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258175","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-258175r1045310_rule","rule_id":"SV-258175","rule_version":"RHEL-09-653130","rule_title":"RHEL 9 audispd-plugins package must be installed.","fix_text":"The audispd-plugins package can be installed with the following command:\n \n$ sudo dnf install audispd-plugins","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 has the audispd-plugins package installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed audispd-plugins\n\nExample output:\n\naudispd-plugins.x86_64          3.0.7-101.el9_0.2\n\nIf the \"audispd-plugins\" package is not installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"\"audispd-plugins\" provides plugins for the real-time interface to the audit subsystem, \"audispd\". These plugins can do things like relay events to remote machines or analyze events for suspicious behavior.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"7766","uuid":"8658a4b2-b5e1-4473-9ddb-399ade4365c9","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CDCCB4C221639D04E73A38456242199DABD086E0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 audispd-plugins package must be installed.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258176","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258176","title":"SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258176","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126","rule_id_src":"SV-258176r1155595_rule","rule_id":"SV-258176","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654010","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit uses of the \"execve\" system call.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to audit the execution of the \"execve\" system call.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rules to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv \n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv \n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv \n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"execve\" system call with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep execve\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv\n\nIf the command does not return all lines, or the lines are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of privileged functions, either intentionally or unintentionally by authorized users, or by unauthorized external entities that have compromised information system accounts, is a serious and ongoing concern and can have significant adverse impacts on organizations. Auditing the use of privileged functions is one way to detect such misuse and identify the risk from insider threats and the advanced persistent threat.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126, SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002233","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"4254","uuid":"dde47331-8421-46d8-a045-044ee9810bc8","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 70AA5C5CC3AE70C58C730945E10E72E40F7E48D9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must audit uses of the \"execve\" system call.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258177","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258177","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258177","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-258177r1155597_rule","rule_id":"SV-258177","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654015","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chmod\", \"fchmod\", and \"fchmodat\" syscalls.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"chmod\", \"fchmod\", and \"fchmodat\" system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chmod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"chmod\", \"fchmod\", and \"fchmodat\" system calls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"6024","uuid":"9638e79a-5c15-45ab-984c-95ae5e77cf14","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8F28B225B0776CF94A0481B0884BF04E09708112\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258178","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258178","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258178","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-258178r1155599_rule","rule_id":"SV-258178","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654020","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\"\" system calls.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the  \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\" system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chown\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S lchown,fchown,chown,fchownat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,lchown,fchownat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\" system calls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"7236","uuid":"81e8d314-1ac1-4f2d-8ab5-0dbcfd22a72e","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D784553775745C3897E4722888822210763181B6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258179","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258179","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258179","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-258179r1155601_rule","rule_id":"SV-258179","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654025","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to audit the execution of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls by adding or updating the following lines to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep xattr\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,lsetxattr,fsetxattr,removexattr,lremovexattr,fremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,lsetxattr,fsetxattr,removexattr,lremovexattr,fremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,lsetxattr,fsetxattr,removexattr,lremovexattr,fremovexattr -F auid=0 -F key=perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,lsetxattr,fsetxattr,removexattr,lremovexattr,fremovexattr -F auid=0 -F key=perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls, or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"7743","uuid":"22920f9c-d4dc-4cf5-9132-fdb30d075559","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 210D89ECA12E5C187F60C34C7889359AE15398E4\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258180","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258180","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258180","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-258180r1045325_rule","rule_id":"SV-258180","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654030","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit all uses of umount system calls.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"umount\" command by adding or updating the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"umount\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /usr/bin/umount\n\n-a always,exit -S all -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"umount\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"5955","uuid":"64cb78fd-04c7-49de-bf3b-fc5cdc611a8a","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F45C02518B182EE8FC3BCA3EA21A4763AA531A9A\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 9 must audit all uses of umount system calls.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258181","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258181","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258181","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-258181r1045328_rule","rule_id":"SV-258181","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654035","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the chacl command.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chacl\" command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"chacl\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chacl\n\n-a always,exit -S all -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2830","uuid":"1d0c0ec8-c095-4a75-a358-87ff864c9d70","stig_uuid":"6cc2160c-e4e9-459c-970b-2f2c250586dd","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2262B20C9AC037AFA39439D693C69455C8EBA8A4\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the chacl command.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-258182","group_tree":[{"id":"V-258182","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-258182","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-258182r1045331_rule","rule_id":"SV-258182","rule_version":"RHEL-09-654040","rule_title":"RHEL 9 must audit all uses of the setfacl command.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setfacl\" command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"setfacl\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep setfacl\n\n-a always,exit -S all -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third